이 이미 감사하고 있다고 전제한다. 동의 여부를 묻지 않고 단정함으로써, 반론의 여지를 미리 없앤다.", "sid": "c5s033"}, {"word": "sacrifice", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsækrɪfaɪs/", "mean": "희생", "ctx": "Afterwards Squealer was sent round the farm to explain the new arrangement to the others.“Comrades,” he said, “I trust that every animal here appreciates the ⟦sacrifice⟧ that Comrade Napoleon has made in taking this extra labour upon himself. Do not imagine, comrades, that leadership is a pleasure!", "marked": true, "note": "남을 위해 자기 것을 내어놓음을 뜻한다. the sacrifice that Comrade Napoleon has made(Napoleon이 치른 희생)는 이 연설의 핵심 수사다. 권력을 빼앗은 행위가 '희생'으로 둔갑한다. 빼앗음을 베풂으로 뒤집는 이 전도가, Squealer 선전의 기본 문법이다.", "sid": "c5s033"}, {"word": "leadership", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈliːdəʃɪp/", "mean": "지도(자의 자리), 통솔", "ctx": "Afterwards Squealer was sent round the farm to explain the new arrangement to the others.“Comrades,” he said, “I trust that every animal here appreciates the sacrifice that Comrade Napoleon has made in taking this extra labour upon himself. Do not imagine, comrades, that ⟦leadership⟧ is a pleasure!", "marked": true, "note": "이끄는 일, 또는 그 지위를 뜻한다. leadership is a pleasure에서 leadership은 Napoleon이 차지한 권력의 자리를 가리킨다. Squealer는 이 자리를 특권이 아니라 부담으로 규정함으로써, 권력 독점을 정당화하려 한다.", "sid": "c5s033"}, {"word": "responsibility", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/rɪˌspɒnsəˈbɪləti/", "mean": "책임, 책무", "ctx": "he said, “I trust that every animal here appreciates the sacrifice that Comrade Napoleon has made in taking this extra labour upon himself. Do not imagine, comrades, that leadership is a pleasure! On the contrary, it is a deep and heavy ⟦responsibility⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "맡아서 감당해야 할 의무를 뜻한다. a deep and heavy responsibility(깊고 무거운 책임)는 권력을 '누리는 특권'이 아니라 '감당하는 짐'으로 규정한다. 지배를 헌신으로 둔갑시키는 이 수사가, 비판을 배은망덕으로 뒤집는 토대가 된다.", "sid": "c5s033"}, {"word": "comrade", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪd/", "mean": "동지, 동무 (뜻을 같이하는 벗)", "ctx": "No one believes more firmly than ⟦Comrade⟧ Napoleon that all animals are equal. He would be only too happy to let you make your decisions for yourselves. But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, comrades, and then where should we be?", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "comrades", "pos": "n. (pl., vocative)", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪdz/", "mean": "동지들이여", "ctx": "No one believes more firmly than Comrade Napoleon that all animals are equal. He would be only too happy to let you make your decisions for yourselves. But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, ⟦comrades⟧, and then where should we be?", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "equal", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈiːkwəl/", "mean": "평등한, 동등한", "ctx": "No one believes more firmly than Comrade Napoleon that all animals are ⟦equal⟧. He would be only too happy to let you make your decisions for yourselves. But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, comrades, and then where should we be?", "marked": true, "note": "차별 없이 같음을 뜻한다. all animals are equal(모든 동물은 평등하다)은 혁명의 근본 원칙이다. Squealer가 이 원칙을 입에 올리는 것은, 그것을 무너뜨린 행위를 도리어 그 원칙의 언어로 가리기 위함이다.", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "only too happy", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈhæpi/", "mean": "더없이 기꺼이 ~하려는", "ctx": "No one believes more firmly than Comrade Napoleon that all animals are equal. He would be ⟦only too happy⟧ to let you make your decisions for yourselves. But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, comrades, and then where should we be?", "marked": true, "note": "기꺼움을 강하게 나타내는 관용 표현이다. would be only too happy to let you(여러분에게 기꺼이 맡기고 싶어 할 것이다)는 관대한 의향을 과장한다. 그러나 앞의 would가, 그 기꺼움이 실현된 사실이 아니라 가정에 머묾을 슬며시 표시한다. 곧 'But'으로 거두어들일 미끼다.", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "moonshine", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈmuːnʃaɪn/", "mean": "허황된 생각, 망상 (헛소리)", "ctx": "But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, comrades, and then where should we be? Suppose you had decided to follow Snowball, with his ⟦moonshine⟧ of windmills — Snowball, who, as we now know, was no better than a criminal?”", "marked": true, "note": "실현 불가능한 공상이나 헛소리를 뜻한다(직역하면 '달빛'). his moonshine of windmills(그의 풍차라는 망상)는 한때 진보의 상징이던 풍차 구상을 비현실적 공상으로 격하한다. 합리적 계획을 조롱거리로 둔갑시키는 폄하의 말이다.", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "no better than", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈbetə/", "mean": "~나 다름없는, ~에 지나지 않는", "ctx": "But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, comrades, and then where should we be? Suppose you had decided to follow Snowball, with his moonshine of windmills — Snowball, who, as we now know, was ⟦no better than⟧ a criminal?”", "marked": true, "note": "둘을 같은 수준으로 끌어내리는 비교 표현이다. was no better than a criminal(범죄자나 다름없었다)은 Snowball을 범죄자와 동급으로 묶는다. '~보다 나을 게 없다'는 우회 표현이, 은근하면서도 확정적인 낙인을 찍는다.", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "criminal", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkrɪmɪnl/", "mean": "범죄자", "ctx": "But sometimes you might make the wrong decisions, comrades, and then where should we be? Suppose you had decided to follow Snowball, with his moonshine of windmills — Snowball, who, as we now know, was no better than a ⟦criminal⟧?”", "marked": true, "note": "죄를 저지른 자를 뜻한다. 한때 농장을 위해 싸운 동지가 a criminal로 다시 규정된다. 과거의 영웅을 현재의 필요에 따라 범죄자로 소급해 낙인찍는 이 전환이, 역사를 다시 쓰는 권력의 작동을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c5s034"}, {"word": "bravely", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈbreɪvli/", "mean": "용감하게", "ctx": "“He fought ⟦bravely⟧ at the Battle of the Cowshed,” said somebody.“Bravery is not enough,” said Squealer. “Loyalty and obedience are more important. And as to the Battle of the Cowshed, I believe the time will come when we shall find that Snowball’s part in it was much exaggerated.", "marked": true, "note": "두려움 없이 맞섬을 뜻한다. He fought bravely at the Battle of the Cowshed(그는 외양간 전투에서 용감히 싸웠다)는 Snowball의 명백한 공적을 상기시키는 항변이다. 부정하기 어려운 이 사실이, 곧 Squealer의 교묘한 응수로 무력화된다.", "sid": "c5s035"}, {"word": "bravery", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbreɪvəri/", "mean": "용기, 용맹", "ctx": "“He fought bravely at the Battle of the Cowshed,” said somebody.“⟦Bravery⟧ is not enough,” said Squealer. “Loyalty and obedience are more important. And as to the Battle of the Cowshed, I believe the time will come when we shall find that Snowball’s part in it was much exaggerated.", "marked": true, "note": "위험 앞에서의 담대함을 뜻한다. Bravery is not enough(용기만으로는 충분하지 않다)에서 Squealer는 용기 자체를 부정하지 않는다. 다만 '충분하지 않다'며 그 가치를 깎는다. 사실은 인정하되 의미를 무력화하는 화법이다.", "sid": "c5s035"}, {"word": "loyalty", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈlɔɪəlti/", "mean": "충성, 충실", "ctx": "“He fought bravely at the Battle of the Cowshed,” said somebody.“Bravery is not enough,” said Squealer. “⟦Loyalty⟧ and obedience are more important. And as to the Battle of the Cowshed, I believe the time will come when we shall find that Snowball’s part in it was much exaggerated.", "marked": true, "note": "한결같이 따르고 지지함을 뜻한다. Loyalty and obedience are more important(충성과 복종이 더 중요하다)에서 loyalty는 최고 미덕의 자리에 오른다. 용기보다 충성을 위에 둠으로써, 비판적 자질 대신 순응이 칭송받게 된다.", "sid": "c5s035"}, {"word": "obedience", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/əˈbiːdiəns/", "mean": "복종, 순종", "ctx": "“He fought bravely at the Battle of the Cowshed,” said somebody.“Bravery is not enough,” said Squealer. “Loyalty and ⟦obedience⟧ are more important. And as to the Battle of the Cowshed, I believe the time will come when we shall find that Snowball’s part in it was much exaggerated.", "marked": true, "note": "명령이나 권위에 따름을 뜻한다. obedience가 loyalty와 나란히 최고 덕목으로 제시된다. 스스로 판단하기보다 시키는 대로 따르는 것이 미덕이 될 때, 비판은 부도덕한 일탈로 바뀐다. 복종의 도덕화가 여기서 시작된다.", "sid": "c5s035"}, {"word": "exaggerated", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɪɡˈzædʒəreɪtɪd/", "mean": "과장된", "ctx": "“He fought bravely at the Battle of the Cowshed,” said somebody.“Bravery is not enough,” said Squealer. “Loyalty and obedience are more important. And as to the Battle of the Cowshed, I believe the time will come when we shall find that Snowball’s part in it was much ⟦exaggerated⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "실제보다 부풀려졌음을 뜻한다. was much exaggerated(크게 과장되었다)는 Snowball의 공적을 '부풀려진 것'으로 규정한다. 사실을 직접 부정하지 않으면서도, 그 무게를 덜어 내며 미래의 역사 재서술을 예고한다.", "sid": "c5s035"}, {"word": "iron", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈaɪən/", "mean": "강철 같은, 무쇠 같은 (단호한)", "ctx": "Discipline, comrades, ⟦iron⟧ discipline! That is the watchword for today. One false step, and our enemies would be upon us. Surely, comrades, you do not want Jones back?”Once again this argument was unanswerable.", "marked": true, "note": "본래 '쇠'를 뜻하지만, 여기서는 비유적으로 '휘지 않고 가차 없는'을 뜻한다. iron discipline(강철 같은 규율)은 어떤 예외도 허용하지 않는 절대적 통제를 그린다. 차갑고 단단한 이미지가 가혹함을 환기한다.", "sid": "c5s036"}, {"word": "watchword", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈwɒtʃwɜːd/", "mean": "표어, 행동 지침", "ctx": "Discipline, comrades, iron discipline! That is the ⟦watchword⟧ for today. One false step, and our enemies would be upon us. Surely, comrades, you do not want Jones back?”Once again this argument was unanswerable.", "marked": true, "note": "집단이 내거는 구호나 행동 지침을 뜻한다. the watchword for today(오늘의 표어)는 규율을 따져 묻는 대상이 아니라 외우고 따를 구호로 못 박는다. 표어가 되는 순간, 규율은 사유의 대상에서 명령으로 바뀐다.", "sid": "c5s036"}, {"word": "false step", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/fɔːls/", "mean": "잘못된 행동, 실수 (헛디딤)", "ctx": "Discipline, comrades, iron discipline! That is the watchword for today. One ⟦false step⟧, and our enemies would be upon us. Surely, comrades, you do not want Jones back?”Once again this argument was unanswerable.", "marked": true, "note": "한 번의 그릇된 행동을 뜻한다. One false step, and our enemies would be upon us(한 번만 헛디뎌도 적들이 우리를 덮칠 것이다)는 작은 실수조차 파국으로 이어진다는 공포를 심는다. 비판이나 이견을 '치명적 헛디딤'으로 몰아 절대 복종을 강요한다.", "sid": "c5s036"}, {"word": "unanswerable", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ʌnˈɑːnsərəbl/", "mean": "반박할 수 없는", "ctx": "Discipline, comrades, iron discipline! That is the watchword for today. One false step, and our enemies would be upon us. Surely, comrades, you do not want Jones back?”Once again this argument was ⟦unanswerable⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "맞받아칠 수 없음을 뜻한다. this argument was unanswerable(이 논리는 반박할 수 없었다)는 서술자의 미묘한 표현이다. 논리가 옳아서가 아니라, 동물들이 반박할 언어와 용기를 갖지 못해 '반박할 수 없는' 것이다. 진짜 무적이 아니라, 무적처럼 느껴질 뿐이다.", "sid": "c5s036"}, {"word": "be liable to", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈlaɪəbl/", "mean": "~하기 쉽다, ~할 가능성이 있다", "ctx": "Discipline, comrades, iron discipline! That is the watchword for today. One false step, and our enemies would be upon us. Surely, comrades, you do not want Jones back?”Once again this argument was unanswerable. Certainly the animals did not want Jones back; if the holding of debates on Sunday mornin…", "marked": false, "note": "어떤 일이 일어나기 쉬움을 뜻한다. was liable to bring him back(그를 돌아오게 할 수 있었다)는 토론과 Jones 복귀 사이에 인과의 고리를 만든다. 입증되지 않은 이 '가능성'이, 마치 확실한 위험인 양 받아들여져 토론 폐지의 근거가 된다.", "sid": "c5s036"}, {"word": "think over (think things over)", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/θɪŋk/", "mean": "곰곰이 생각하다, 숙고하다", "ctx": "Boxer, who had now had time to ⟦think⟧ things over, voiced the general feeling by saying: “If Comrade Napoleon says it, it must be right.” And from then on he adopted the maxim, “Napoleon is always right,” in addition to his private motto of “I will work harder.”", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 일을 시간을 들여 따져 봄을 뜻한다. had now had time to think things over(이제 곰곰이 생각해 볼 시간을 가졌다)는 Boxer의 결론이 충동이 아니라 숙고의 산물임을 강조한다. 바로 그 숙고의 끝이 '생각을 멈추는 것'이라는 데에 비극적 아이러니가 있다.", "sid": "c5s037"}, {"word": "voice", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/vɔɪs/", "mean": "(의견·감정을) 대변하다, 표현하다", "ctx": "Boxer, who had now had time to think things over, ⟦voiced⟧ the general feeling by saying: “If Comrade Napoleon says it, it must be right.” And from then on he adopted the maxim, “Napoleon is always right,” in addition to his private motto of “I will work harder.”", "marked": true, "note": "생각이나 감정을 말로 드러냄을 뜻한다. voiced the general feeling(전반적인 정서를 대변했다)에서 Boxer는 자기 한 사람이 아니라 동물 다수를 대표해 말한다. 그의 굴복이 곧 대중 전체의 굴복임을 보여 주는 표현이다.", "sid": "c5s037"}, {"word": "general feeling", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈdʒenrəl/", "mean": "전반적인 정서, 대다수의 생각", "ctx": "Boxer, who had now had time to think things over, voiced the ⟦general feeling⟧ by saying: “If Comrade Napoleon says it, it must be right.” And from then on he adopted the maxim, “Napoleon is always right,” in addition to his private motto of “I will work harder.”", "marked": true, "note": "집단 다수가 공유하는 분위기나 생각을 뜻한다. the general feeling은 동물들 대부분이 이미 비판을 포기하고 Napoleon에게 판단을 맡기는 쪽으로 기울었음을 가리킨다. Boxer는 그 흐름에 가장 또렷한 목소리를 입힌다.", "sid": "c5s037"}, {"word": "maxim", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈmæksɪm/", "mean": "격언, 좌우명", "ctx": "Boxer, who had now had time to think things over, voiced the general feeling by saying: “If Comrade Napoleon says it, it must be right.” And from then on he adopted the ⟦maxim⟧, “Napoleon is always right,” in addition to his private motto of “I will work harder.”", "marked": true, "note": "행동의 지침으로 삼는 짧은 문구를 뜻한다. adopted the maxim, “Napoleon is always right”(좌우명을 채택했다)에서 Boxer는 복잡한 판단을 하나의 문구로 대체한다. 좌우명이 사유의 자리를 차지하는 순간, 스스로 따지는 일은 멈춘다.", "sid": "c5s037"}, {"word": "motto", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈmɒtəʊ/", "mean": "좌우명, 표어", "ctx": "Boxer, who had now had time to think things over, voiced the general feeling by saying: “If Comrade Napoleon says it, it must be right.” And from then on he adopted the maxim, “Napoleon is always right,” in addition to his private ⟦motto⟧ of “I will work harder.”", "marked": true, "note": "개인이나 집단이 내거는 신조를 뜻한다. his private motto of “I will work harder”(그의 개인적 좌우명 '더 열심히 일하겠다')는 Boxer의 성실함을 압축한다. 이제 그 위에 '맹목적 충성'의 좌우명이 더해져, 노동과 복종이 한 쌍을 이룬다.", "sid": "c5s037"}, {"word": "break (of weather)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/breɪk/", "mean": "(날씨가) 풀리다, 바뀌다", "ctx": "By this time the weather had broken and the spring ploughing had begun. The shed where Snowball had drawn his plans of the windmill had been shut up and it was assumed that the plans had been rubbed off the floor.", "marked": false, "note": "날씨가 한 상태에서 다른 상태로 바뀜을 뜻한다(특히 추위·궂은 날씨가 풀림). the weather had broken(날씨가 풀렸다)는 혹독한 겨울이 끝나고 봄이 왔음을 알린다. 격동의 정치 국면이 지나고 일상의 노동이 다시 시작되는 전환을 자연으로 표시한다.", "sid": "c5s038"}, {"word": "ploughing", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈplaʊɪŋ/", "mean": "쟁기질, 밭갈이", "ctx": "By this time the weather had broken and the spring ⟦ploughing⟧ had begun. The shed where Snowball had drawn his plans of the windmill had been shut up and it was assumed that the plans had been rubbed off the floor.", "marked": true, "note": "쟁기로 땅을 가는 일을 뜻한다(영국식 철자 plough, 미국식 plow). the spring ploughing had begun(봄 쟁기질이 시작되었다)는 계절의 순환과 함께 일상이 회복됨을 보여 준다. 권력 다툼이 무엇이든, 동물들의 고된 노동은 변함없이 이어진다.", "sid": "c5s038"}, {"word": "shed", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ʃed/", "mean": "헛간, 광, 창고", "ctx": "By this time the weather had broken and the spring ploughing had begun. The ⟦shed⟧ where Snowball had drawn his plans of the windmill had been shut up and it was assumed that the plans had been rubbed off the floor.", "marked": true, "note": "물건을 두거나 작업하는 작은 별채를 뜻한다. The shed where Snowball had drawn his plans(Snowball이 설계도를 그렸던 헛간)는 Snowball의 비전이 깃든 공간이었다. 그 헛간이 닫히는 것은, 한 인물과 그의 구상이 함께 봉인됨을 뜻한다.", "sid": "c5s038"}, {"word": "shut up", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ʃʌt/", "mean": "폐쇄하다, 닫아걸다", "ctx": "By this time the weather had broken and the spring ploughing had begun. The shed where Snowball had drawn his plans of the windmill had been ⟦shut up⟧ and it was assumed that the plans had been rubbed off the floor.", "marked": true, "note": "문을 닫아 못 들어가게 함을 뜻한다(여기서는 '입 다물라'는 명령이 아님). had been shut up(폐쇄되었다)는 수동태로, 누가 닫았는지를 밝히지 않는다. 헛간이 조용히 봉인되듯, Snowball의 흔적도 소리 없이 치워진다.", "sid": "c5s038"}, {"word": "rub off", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/rʌb/", "mean": "문질러 지우다, 닦아 없애다", "ctx": "By this time the weather had broken and the spring ploughing had begun. The shed where Snowball had drawn his plans of the windmill had been shut up and it was assumed that the plans had been ⟦rubbed⟧ off the floor.", "marked": true, "note": "문질러서 자국을 없앰을 뜻한다. the plans had been rubbed off the floor(설계도가 바닥에서 지워졌다)는 Snowball의 구상이 물리적으로 소거되었음을 보여 준다. 기록을 지우는 것은, 그 사람과 그의 생각을 역사에서 없애는 일의 시작이다.", "sid": "c5s038"}, {"word": "flagstaff", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈflæɡstɑːf/", "mean": "깃대", "ctx": "Every Sunday morning at ten o’clock the animals assembled in the big barn to receive their orders for the week. The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been disinterred from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the ⟦flagstaff⟧, beside the gun.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c5s039"}, {"word": "hoisting", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈhɔɪstɪŋ/", "mean": "(밧줄·기로) 끌어올리는, 게양하는", "ctx": "The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been disinterred from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the flagstaff, beside the gun. After the ⟦hoisting⟧ of the flag, the animals were required to file past the skull in a reverent manner before entering the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c5s039", "base": "hoist — 끌어올리다, 게양하다"}, {"word": "disinterred", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/ˌdɪsɪnˈtɜːd/", "mean": "파내어졌다, 발굴되었다", "ctx": "Every Sunday morning at ten o’clock the animals assembled in the big barn to receive their orders for the week. The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been ⟦disinterred⟧ from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the flagstaff, beside the gun.", "marked": true, "note": "inter(묻다)에 부정 접두사 dis-가 붙은 말. 땅에 묻힌 Major의 두개골을 다시 파낸 것.", "sid": "c5s039"}, {"word": "disinter", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌdɪsɪnˈtɜː/", "mean": "(땅에서) 파내다, 발굴하다", "ctx": "Every Sunday morning at ten o’clock the animals assembled in the big barn to receive their orders for the week. The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been ⟦disinterred⟧ from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the flagstaff, beside the gun.", "marked": true, "note": "묻힌 것을 도로 파냄을 뜻한다(inter=매장하다의 반대). The skull of old Major... had been disinterred from the orchard(Major의 두개골이 과수원에서 파내어졌다)는 죽은 혁명의 아버지를 다시 끄집어내 전시함을 보여 준다. 안식해야 할 유해가, 정치적 도구로 동원된다.", "sid": "c5s039"}, {"word": "reverent", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈrevərənt/", "mean": "경건한, 공손한", "ctx": "The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been disinterred from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the flagstaff, beside the gun. After the hoisting of the flag, the animals were required to file past the skull in a ⟦reverent⟧ manner before entering the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "깊은 존경과 외경을 담은 태도를 뜻한다(종교적 어감). file past the skull in a reverent manner(경건한 태도로 두개골 앞을 지나가다)는 정치 집회를 종교 의식처럼 만든다. 자발적 경배가 아니라 '요구된' 경건이라는 점이, 그 의례의 강제성을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c5s039"}, {"word": "file (past)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/faɪl/", "mean": "줄지어 지나가다, 행렬하다", "ctx": "The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been disinterred from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the flagstaff, beside the gun. After the hoisting of the flag, the animals were required to ⟦file⟧ past the skull in a reverent manner before entering the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "한 줄로 늘어서 차례로 이동함을 뜻한다. file past the skull(두개골 앞을 줄지어 지나다)는 개개의 동물을 하나의 행렬로 묶는다. 정해진 동작을 함께 반복하는 의례가, 복종을 몸에 새긴다. 줄을 서는 순간, 개인은 집단의 일부가 된다.", "sid": "c5s039"}, {"word": "require", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/rɪˈkwaɪə/", "mean": "요구하다, 의무화하다", "ctx": "The skull of old Major, now clean of flesh, had been disinterred from the orchard and set up on a stump at the foot of the flagstaff, beside the gun. After the hoisting of the flag, the animals were ⟦required⟧ to file past the skull in a reverent manner before entering the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "반드시 하도록 함을 뜻한다. the animals were required to file past the skull(동물들은 두개골 앞을 지나도록 요구되었다)는 수동태로, 누가 요구했는지를 밝히지 않는다. 경건함조차 자발이 아니라 의무다. 마음에서 우러난 존경이 아니라, 강제된 동작이다.", "sid": "c5s039"}, {"word": "composing", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/kəmˈpəʊzɪŋ/", "mean": "(노래·시를) 짓는, 작곡하는", "ctx": "Napoleon, with Squealer and another pig named Minimus, who had a remarkable gift for ⟦composing⟧ songs and poems, sat on the front of the raised platform, with the nine young dogs forming a semicircle round them, and the other pigs sitting behind.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c5s040", "base": "compose — (노래·시를) 짓다, 작곡하다"}, {"word": "raised platform", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈplætfɔːm/", "mean": "높은 단상, 연단", "ctx": "Napoleon, with Squealer and another pig named Minimus, who had a remarkable gift for composing songs and poems, sat on the front of the ⟦raised platform⟧, with the nine young dogs forming a semicircle round them, and the other pigs sitting behind.", "marked": true, "note": "바닥보다 높이 올린 자리를 뜻한다. sat on the front of the raised platform(높은 단상 앞쪽에 앉았다)에서 '높음'은 곧 위계다. 지도부가 물리적으로 높은 곳에 앉음으로써, 권력의 우위가 공간으로 가시화된다.", "sid": "c5s040"}, {"word": "semicircle", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsemisɜːkl/", "mean": "반원", "ctx": "Napoleon, with Squealer and another pig named Minimus, who had a remarkable gift for composing songs and poems, sat on the front of the raised platform, with the nine young dogs forming a ⟦semicircle⟧ round them, and the other pigs sitting behind.", "marked": true, "note": "원의 절반 모양을 뜻한다(semi=절반). the nine young dogs forming a semicircle round them(어린 개 아홉 마리가 그들 둘레로 반원을 이룸)은 지도부를 에워싼 호위를 그린다. 보호의 모양이지만, 동시에 누구도 함부로 다가갈 수 없다는 위협이기도 하다.", "sid": "c5s040"}, {"word": "gruff", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɡrʌf/", "mean": "퉁명스러운, (목소리가) 거친", "ctx": "The rest of the animals sat facing them in the main body of the barn. Napoleon read out the orders for the week in a ⟦gruff⟧ soldierly style, and after a single singing of ‘Beasts of England’, all the animals dispersed.", "marked": true, "note": "무뚝뚝하고 거친 태도나 목소리를 뜻한다. in a gruff soldierly style(퉁명한 군인 같은 어조로)는 Napoleon의 말투를 묘사한다. 설득하거나 토의하는 어조가 아니라, 명령을 내리꽂는 어조다. 부드러움이 사라진 자리에 권위만 남는다.", "sid": "c5s040"}, {"word": "soldierly", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈsəʊldʒəli/", "mean": "군인 같은, 군대식의", "ctx": "The rest of the animals sat facing them in the main body of the barn. Napoleon read out the orders for the week in a gruff ⟦soldierly⟧ style, and after a single singing of ‘Beasts of England’, all the animals dispersed.", "marked": true, "note": "군인다운 태도를 뜻한다(soldier+ly). a gruff soldierly style에서 soldierly는 농장의 운영이 군대처럼 운영됨을 암시한다. 동지적 협의가 아니라 상명하복의 군사 질서가, 일상의 어조에까지 스며든다.", "sid": "c5s040"}, {"word": "disperse", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/dɪˈspɜːs/", "mean": "흩어지다, 해산하다", "ctx": "The rest of the animals sat facing them in the main body of the barn. Napoleon read out the orders for the week in a gruff soldierly style, and after a single singing of ‘Beasts of England’, all the animals ⟦dispersed⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "모였던 무리가 흩어짐을 뜻한다. all the animals dispersed(모든 동물이 해산했다)는 집회의 끝을 알린다. 토론도 표결도 없이, 명령을 받고 노래 한 번 부른 뒤 곧장 흩어진다. 모임의 절차가 최소한의 형식으로 압축되었음을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c5s040"}, {"word": "after all", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˌɑːftər ˈɔːl/", "mean": "결국, (예상과 달리) 어쨌든", "ctx": "On the third Sunday after Snowball’s expulsion, the animals were somewhat surprised to hear Napoleon announce that the windmill was to be built ⟦after all⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "앞선 예상이나 기대와 반대되는 결과를 나타낸다. the windmill was to be built after all(결국 풍차가 지어지게 되었다)에서 after all은 '반대했던 그 풍차인데도'라는 반전을 품는다. 짧은 두 단어가, Napoleon의 입장이 정반대로 뒤집혔음을 압축한다.", "sid": "c5s041"}, {"word": "change one’s mind", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/tʃeɪndʒ/", "mean": "마음을 바꾸다, 생각을 바꾸다", "ctx": "He did not give any reason for having ⟦changed⟧ his mind, but merely warned the animals that this extra task would mean very hard work, it might even be necessary to reduce their rations. The plans, however, had all been prepared, down to the last detail.", "marked": true, "note": "결정이나 의견을 바꿈을 뜻한다. He did not give any reason for having changed his mind(그는 마음을 바꾼 이유를 전혀 대지 않았다)는 권력의 핵심을 드러낸다. 지도자는 입장을 뒤집으면서도 설명할 의무를 느끼지 않는다. 더구나 뒤에 밝혀지듯, 그것은 애초에 '바꾼' 것도 아니었다.", "sid": "c5s041"}, {"word": "ration", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈræʃn/", "mean": "배급(량), 정해진 몫의 식량", "ctx": "He did not give any reason for having changed his mind, but merely warned the animals that this extra task would mean very hard work, it might even be necessary to reduce their ⟦rations⟧. The plans, however, had all been prepared, down to the last detail.", "marked": true, "note": "한정된 양으로 나눠 주는 식량을 뜻한다. it might even be necessary to reduce their rations(배급을 줄여야 할 수도 있다)는 풍차의 대가가 동물들의 굶주림임을 예고한다. 결정의 부담은 위에서 내리고, 그 희생은 아래가 진다.", "sid": "c5s041"}, {"word": "down to the last detail", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/dɪˈteɪl/", "mean": "마지막 세부까지, 빠짐없이", "ctx": "He did not give any reason for having changed his mind, but merely warned the animals that this extra task would mean very hard work, it might even be necessary to reduce their rations. The plans, however, had all been prepared, ⟦down to the last detail⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "아주 사소한 부분까지 빠짐없음을 뜻한다. The plans... had all been prepared, down to the last detail(설계도가 세부까지 모두 준비되어 있었다)는, 발표가 즉흥이 아니라 오래전부터 비밀리에 준비된 것임을 폭로한다. 공개된 '망설임'과 감춰진 '완비'가 충돌한다.", "sid": "c5s041"}, {"word": "in reality", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/riˈæləti/", "mean": "실제로는, 사실은", "ctx": "That evening Squealer explained privately to the other animals that Napoleon had never ⟦in reality⟧ been opposed to the windmill.", "marked": true, "note": "겉으로 보이는 것과 다른 '진짜 사실'을 가리킬 때 쓴다. Napoleon had never in reality been opposed to the windmill(실제로는 한 번도 반대한 적 없다)에서, '실제로는'이라는 말이 새빨간 거짓을 진실인 양 덧씌운다. 사실을 가리키는 표현이, 사실의 정반대를 떠받친다.", "sid": "c5s042"}, {"word": "on the contrary", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈkɒntrəri/", "mean": "그와 반대로, 오히려", "ctx": "⟦On the contrary⟧, it was he who had advocated it in the beginning, and the plan which Snowball had drawn on the floor of the incubator shed had actually been stolen from among Napoleon’s papers. The windmill was, in fact, Napoleon’s own creation.", "marked": true, "note": "앞말을 부정하고 정반대를 내세울 때 쓴다. On the contrary, it was he who had advocated it(오히려 그것을 주창한 것은 그였다)는, 반대자를 단숨에 창시자로 뒤집는다. 한 표현이 사실관계를 180도 돌려세운다.", "sid": "c5s042"}, {"word": "steal (stolen)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/stiːl/", "mean": "훔치다 (had been stolen 도둑맞았다)", "ctx": "That evening Squealer explained privately to the other animals that Napoleon had never in reality been opposed to the windmill. On the contrary, it was he who had advocated it in the beginning, and the plan which Snowball had drawn on the floor of the incubator shed had actually been stolen from amo…", "marked": false, "note": "남의 것을 몰래 가져감을 뜻한다(steal-stole-stolen). had actually been stolen from among Napoleon’s papers(실은 Napoleon의 서류에서 훔친 것이었다)는, 설계도를 그린 진짜 장본인 Snowball을 도둑으로 둔갑시킨다. 창작자가 절도범으로, 피해자가 가해자로 뒤집힌다.", "sid": "c5s042"}, {"word": "creation", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/kriˈeɪʃn/", "mean": "창작물, 창조한 것", "ctx": "On the contrary, it was he who had advocated it in the beginning, and the plan which Snowball had drawn on the floor of the incubator shed had actually been stolen from among Napoleon’s papers. The windmill was, in fact, Napoleon’s own ⟦creation⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "처음으로 만들어 낸 것을 뜻한다. The windmill was, in fact, Napoleon’s own creation(풍차는 사실 Napoleon 자신의 창작물이었다)는 역사 뒤집기의 결론이다. 반대하던 자가 창시자가 되고, 창시자는 도둑이 된다. 'in fact'(사실은)라는 단언이, 거짓에 진실의 옷을 입힌다.", "sid": "c5s042"}, {"word": "whisking", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈwɪskɪŋ/", "mean": "(꼬리를) 홱홱 휘젓는", "ctx": "Now that Snowball was out of the way, the plan could go forward without his interference. This, said Squealer, was something called tactics. He repeated a number of times, “Tactics, comrades, tactics!” skipping round and ⟦whisking⟧ his tail with a merry laugh.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c5s043", "base": "whisk — (꼬리를) 홱홱 휘젓다"}, {"word": "sly", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/slaɪ/", "mean": "교활한, 능청스러운", "ctx": "Why, then, asked somebody, had he spoken so strongly against it? Here Squealer looked very ⟦sly⟧. That, he said, was Comrade Napoleon’s cunning. He had SEEMED to oppose the windmill, simply as a manoeuvre to get rid of Snowball, who was a dangerous character and a bad influence.", "marked": true, "note": "속을 감춘 채 능청스럽게 구는 태도를 뜻한다. Here Squealer looked very sly(여기서 Squealer는 무척 능청스러운 표정을 지었다)는 그가 지금 거짓 변명을 꾸며 내려 함을 서술자가 살짝 흘리는 신호다. 표정 하나가 말의 진실성을 의심하게 만든다.", "sid": "c5s043"}, {"word": "cunning", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkʌnɪŋ/", "mean": "교활함, 술책", "ctx": "Why, then, asked somebody, had he spoken so strongly against it? Here Squealer looked very sly. That, he said, was Comrade Napoleon’s ⟦cunning⟧. He had SEEMED to oppose the windmill, simply as a manoeuvre to get rid of Snowball, who was a dangerous character and a bad influence.", "marked": true, "note": "목적을 위해 남을 속이는 영리함을 뜻한다. That... was Comrade Napoleon’s cunning(그것은 Napoleon 동무의 교활함이었다)는, 본래 부정적인 '교활함'을 지도자의 미덕인 양 칭송한다. 속임수를 지략으로 둔갑시키는 순간이다.", "sid": "c5s043"}, {"word": "manoeuvre", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/məˈnuːvə/", "mean": "책략, 술책 (미국식 maneuver)", "ctx": "Why, then, asked somebody, had he spoken so strongly against it? Here Squealer looked very sly. That, he said, was Comrade Napoleon’s cunning. He had SEEMED to oppose the windmill, simply as a ⟦manoeuvre⟧ to get rid of Snowball, who was a dangerous character and a bad influence.", "marked": true, "note": "목적을 이루려는 교묘한 술책을 뜻한다. simply as a manoeuvre to get rid of Snowball(단지 Snowball을 제거하기 위한 책략으로)은, Napoleon의 반대를 진심이 아니라 계산된 함정이었다고 설명한다. 정적 제거가 처음부터의 의도였다는 사후 변명이다.", "sid": "c5s043"}, {"word": "tactics", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtæktɪks/", "mean": "전술, 책략", "ctx": "He had SEEMED to oppose the windmill, simply as a manoeuvre to get rid of Snowball, who was a dangerous character and a bad influence. Now that Snowball was out of the way, the plan could go forward without his interference. This, said Squealer, was something called ⟦tactics⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "목적을 이루기 위한 구체적 방책을 뜻한다. something called tactics(전술이라 불리는 무언가)는, 동물들이 알아듣지 못하는 어려운 말로 모순을 덮는다. 뜻 모를 전문 용어 하나가, 따질 수 없게 만드는 방패가 된다. 모든 모순을 덮는 만능어다.", "sid": "c5s043"}, {"word": "persuasively", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/pəˈsweɪsɪvli/", "mean": "설득력 있게", "ctx": "skipping round and whisking his tail with a merry laugh. The animals were not certain what the word meant, but Squealer spoke so ⟦persuasively⟧, and the three dogs who happened to be with him growled so threateningly, that they accepted his explanation without further questions.", "marked": true, "note": "남을 믿게 만드는 힘 있게 말함을 뜻한다. Squealer spoke so persuasively(Squealer가 너무도 설득력 있게 말해서)는, 내용의 진실성과 무관하게 말솜씨만으로 수용을 끌어냄을 보여 준다. 무엇이 옳은가가 아니라, 얼마나 그럴듯하게 들리는가가 받아들임을 결정한다.", "sid": "c5s043"}], "6": [{"word": "work like slaves", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/sleɪvz/", "mean": "노예처럼 (혹사당하듯) 일하다", "ctx": "A ll that year the animals ⟦worked⟧ like slaves. But they were happy in their work; they grudged no effort or sacrifice, well aware that everything that they did was for the benefit of themselves and those of their kind who would come after them, and not for a pack of idle, thieving human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "쉴 틈 없이 몹시 고되게 일함을 뜻하는 직유다. the animals worked like slaves(동물들은 노예처럼 일했다)는 쓰라린 아이러니를 품는다. 그들은 인간이라는 주인에게서 벗어나려 혁명을 일으켰는데, 이제 다시 '노예처럼' 일한다. 다만 스스로를 위해 일한다고 믿을 뿐이다.", "sid": "c6s001"}, {"word": "grudge", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɡrʌdʒ/", "mean": "(주거나 들이기를) 아까워하다, 인색하게 굴다", "ctx": "A ll that year the animals worked like slaves. But they were happy in their work; they ⟦grudged⟧ no effort or sacrifice, well aware that everything that they did was for the benefit of themselves and those of their kind who would come after them, and not for a pack of idle, thieving human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "무언가를 내주기 싫어함을 뜻한다. they grudged no effort or sacrifice(그들은 어떤 노력이나 희생도 아끼지 않았다)에서 'grudged no ~'는 '조금도 아까워하지 않았다'는 뜻이다. 동물들은 기꺼이, 흔쾌히 모든 것을 바친다. 그 자발성이 도리어 비극의 깊이를 더한다.", "sid": "c6s001"}, {"word": "sacrifice", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsækrɪfaɪs/", "mean": "희생, 바침", "ctx": "A ll that year the animals worked like slaves. But they were happy in their work; they grudged no effort or ⟦sacrifice⟧, well aware that everything that they did was for the benefit of themselves and those of their kind who would come after them, and not for a pack of idle, thieving human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "더 큰 목적을 위해 무언가를 포기함을 뜻한다. no effort or sacrifice(어떤 노력이나 희생도)는 동물들이 자신을 아낌없이 내던짐을 보여 준다. 문제는 그 희생의 열매가 정말 그들에게 돌아가는가다. 믿음과 현실의 간극이, 이 한 단어 위에 걸려 있다.", "sid": "c6s001"}, {"word": "well aware", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/əˈweə/", "mean": "잘 알고 있는, 분명히 인식하는", "ctx": "A ll that year the animals worked like slaves. But they were happy in their work; they grudged no effort or sacrifice, ⟦well aware⟧ that everything that they did was for the benefit of themselves and those of their kind who would come after them, and not for a pack of idle, thieving human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 사실을 또렷이 인식하고 있음을 뜻한다. well aware that everything... was for the benefit of themselves(모든 것이 자신들을 위한 것임을 잘 알고서)는 동물들의 확신을 전한다. 그러나 독자는 그 '앎'이 사실은 착각일 수 있음을 안다. 확신에 찬 믿음과 진실 사이의 거리가 아이러니를 낳는다.", "sid": "c6s001"}, {"word": "idle", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈaɪdl/", "mean": "게으른, 빈둥거리는, 일하지 않는", "ctx": "A ll that year the animals worked like slaves. But they were happy in their work; they grudged no effort or sacrifice, well aware that everything that they did was for the benefit of themselves and those of their kind who would come after them, and not for a pack of ⟦idle⟧, thieving human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "일하지 않고 빈둥거림을 뜻한다. a pack of idle, thieving human beings(게으르고 도둑질하는 인간 무리)는 혁명의 자기 정당화를 압축한다. '일하지 않으면서 빼앗아 가는 인간'이라는 대비가, 동물들이 기꺼이 혹사를 견디게 만드는 이념적 동력이다.", "sid": "c6s001"}, {"word": "undone", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌʌnˈdʌn/", "mean": "하지 못한 채 남은, 끝내지 못한", "ctx": "This work was strictly voluntary, but any animal who absented himself from it would have his rations reduced by half. Even so, it was found necessary to leave certain tasks ⟦undone⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "ploughing", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈplaʊɪŋ/", "mean": "쟁기질, 밭갈이", "ctx": "Even so, it was found necessary to leave certain tasks undone. The harvest was a little less successful than in the previous year, and two fields which should have been sown with roots in the early summer were not sown because the ⟦ploughing⟧ had not been completed early enough.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "sixty-hour week", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈsɪksti aʊə wiːk/", "mean": "주 60시간 노동", "ctx": "Throughout the spring and summer they worked a ⟦sixty-hour week⟧, and in August Napoleon announced that there would be work on Sunday afternoons as well. This work was strictly voluntary, but any animal who absented himself from it would have his rations reduced by half.", "marked": true, "note": "한 주에 60시간을 일한다는 뜻으로, 가혹한 노동 강도를 구체적 숫자로 못 박는다. they worked a sixty-hour week(그들은 주 60시간을 일했다)에서 막연한 '혹사'가 측정 가능한 사실로 바뀐다. 숫자의 건조함이 도리어 무게를 더한다.", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "voluntary", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈvɒləntri/", "mean": "자발적인, 자원하는, 강제가 아닌", "ctx": "Throughout the spring and summer they worked a sixty-hour week, and in August Napoleon announced that there would be work on Sunday afternoons as well. This work was strictly ⟦voluntary⟧, but any animal who absented himself from it would have his rations reduced by half.", "marked": true, "note": "스스로 원해서 하는 것을 뜻한다. 그러나 본문에서 strictly voluntary(엄격히 자발적인)는 곧바로 반박된다. 빠지면 배급이 절반으로 깎이니, 이름만 자발이고 실상은 강제다. 단어의 사전적 뜻과 문맥상 작동이 정면으로 어긋나는 자리다.", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "absent oneself", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈæbsənt/", "mean": "(어떤 자리에) 불참하다, 빠지다", "ctx": "Throughout the spring and summer they worked a sixty-hour week, and in August Napoleon announced that there would be work on Sunday afternoons as well. This work was strictly voluntary, but any animal who ⟦absented⟧ himself from it would have his rations reduced by half.", "marked": true, "note": "동사로 쓰인 absent는 '스스로를 어떤 자리에서 빼다', 곧 불참하다는 뜻이다. any animal who absented himself from it(거기서 빠지는 동물은 누구든)는 격식 있는 문어체 표현으로, 일상의 '안 나오다(stay away)'보다 차갑고 관료적인 울림을 준다. 규정을 읽는 듯한 어조가 강제의 성격을 슬쩍 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "ration", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈræʃn/", "mean": "배급(량), 정해진 몫", "ctx": "Throughout the spring and summer they worked a sixty-hour week, and in August Napoleon announced that there would be work on Sunday afternoons as well. This work was strictly voluntary, but any animal who absented himself from it would have his ⟦rations⟧ reduced by half.", "marked": true, "note": "한정된 식량 등을 정해진 양으로 나눠 주는 것, 또는 그 몫을 뜻한다. his rations reduced by half(배급이 절반으로 깎인)에서 배급은 단순한 식량이 아니라 복종을 강제하는 도구가 된다. 먹을 것을 쥔 자가 노동을 명령한다.", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "foresee", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/fɔːˈsiː/", "mean": "예견하다, 미리 내다보다", "ctx": "The harvest was a little less successful than in the previous year, and two fields which should have been sown with roots in the early summer were not sown because the ploughing had not been completed early enough. It was possible to ⟦foresee⟧ that the coming winter would be a hard one.", "marked": true, "note": "앞으로 닥칠 일을 미리 안다는 뜻이다. It was possible to foresee that the coming winter would be a hard one(다가올 겨울이 혹독하리라 예견할 수 있었다)는 서술자가 슬쩍 미래를 비추는 복선이다. 누가 예견했는지는 말하지 않고, 다만 그럴 수 있었다고만 전한다.", "sid": "c6s002"}, {"word": "outhouses", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈaʊthaʊzɪz/", "mean": "헛간, 별채 부속 건물", "ctx": "The windmill presented unexpected difficulties. There was a good quarry of limestone on the farm, and plenty of sand and cement had been found in one of the ⟦outhouses⟧, so that all the materials for building were at hand.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "crowbars", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkrəʊbɑːz/", "mean": "쇠지렛대", "ctx": "But the problem the animals could not at first solve was how to break up the stone into pieces of suitable size. There seemed no way of doing this except with picks and ⟦crowbars⟧, which no animal could use, because no animal could stand on his hind legs.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "boulders", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbəʊldəz/", "mean": "큰 바위, 둥근 돌덩이", "ctx": "Only after weeks of vain effort did the right idea occur to somebody-namely, to utilise the force of gravity. Huge ⟦boulders⟧, far too big to be used as they were, were lying all over the bed of the quarry.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "slowness", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsləʊnəs/", "mean": "느림, 더딤", "ctx": "The animals lashed ropes round these, and then all together, cows, horses, sheep, any animal that could lay hold of the rope — even the pigs sometimes joined in at critical moments — they dragged them with desperate ⟦slowness⟧ up the slope to the top of the quarry, where they were toppled over the edge, to shatter to pieces below.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "quarry", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkwɒri/", "mean": "채석장 (돌을 캐내는 곳)", "ctx": "The windmill presented unexpected difficulties. There was a good ⟦quarry⟧ of limestone on the farm, and plenty of sand and cement had been found in one of the outhouses, so that all the materials for building were at hand.", "marked": true, "note": "건축용 돌을 캐내는 장소다. a good quarry of limestone(질 좋은 석회암 채석장)는 풍차 건설의 원료가 농장 안에 이미 있음을 보여 준다. 재료는 가까이 있으나, 정작 그것을 다룰 방법이 문제다.", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "hind legs", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/haɪnd leɡz/", "mean": "뒷다리", "ctx": "But the problem the animals could not at first solve was how to break up the stone into pieces of suitable size. There seemed no way of doing this except with picks and crowbars, which no animal could use, because no animal could stand on his ⟦hind legs⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "네발짐승의 뒤쪽 두 다리를 가리킨다. no animal could stand on his hind legs(어떤 동물도 뒷다리로 설 수 없었다)는 단순한 신체 한계를 말하는 듯하지만, 작품 전체를 관통하는 중요한 표지다. 뒷다리로 서는 것은 곧 인간의 자세이며, 동물과 인간을 가르는 경계다.", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "vain", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/veɪn/", "mean": "헛된, 보람 없는", "ctx": "There seemed no way of doing this except with picks and crowbars, which no animal could use, because no animal could stand on his hind legs. Only after weeks of ⟦vain⟧ effort did the right idea occur to somebody-namely, to utilise the force of gravity.", "marked": true, "note": "애를 썼으나 결실이 없음을 뜻한다. weeks of vain effort(몇 주에 걸친 헛된 노력)는 해법을 찾기까지의 막막한 시간을 압축한다. 그 헛된 시간이 있었기에, 마침내 떠오른 착상이 더 값지게 느껴진다.", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "utilise", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈjuːtɪlaɪz/", "mean": "활용하다, (효율적으로) 이용하다", "ctx": "There seemed no way of doing this except with picks and crowbars, which no animal could use, because no animal could stand on his hind legs. Only after weeks of vain effort did the right idea occur to somebody-namely, to ⟦utilise⟧ the force of gravity.", "marked": true, "note": "가진 자원을 쓸모 있게 이용함을 뜻한다. to utilise the force of gravity(중력을 활용하는 것)는 도구도 손도 없는 동물들이 자연의 힘 자체를 도구로 삼았음을 보여 준다. 가진 것이 없을 때, 지혜가 결핍을 메운다.", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "lash", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/læʃ/", "mean": "(밧줄로) 단단히 동여매다", "ctx": "The animals ⟦lashed⟧ ropes round these, and then all together, cows, horses, sheep, any animal that could lay hold of the rope — even the pigs sometimes joined in at critical moments — they dragged them with desperate slowness up the slope to the top of the quarry, where they were toppled over the edge, to shatter to pieces below.", "marked": true, "note": "끈이나 밧줄로 무언가를 꽉 묶는 것을 뜻한다. lashed ropes round these(바위들에 밧줄을 동여맸다)는 도구를 못 쥐는 동물들이 몸과 밧줄로 일을 해내는 방식을 그린다. 손 대신 협력이 그들의 연장이다.", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "topple", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈtɒpl/", "mean": "넘어뜨리다, 굴려 떨어뜨리다", "ctx": "The animals lashed ropes round these, and then all together, cows, horses, sheep, any animal that could lay hold of the rope — even the pigs sometimes joined in at critical moments — they dragged them with desperate slowness up the slope to the top of the quarry, where they were ⟦toppled⟧ over the edge, to shatter to pieces below.", "marked": true, "note": "위태롭게 균형을 잃고 넘어지거나, 그렇게 만드는 것을 뜻한다. they were toppled over the edge, to shatter to pieces below(벼랑 너머로 굴려져 아래에서 산산이 부서졌다)에서 바위는 중력의 힘으로 부서진다. topple은 정치적 맥락에서 '체제를 무너뜨리다'로도 쓰여, 이 장면에 묘한 울림을 더한다.", "sid": "c6s003"}, {"word": "governess-cart", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈɡʌvənəs kɑːt/", "mean": "거버니스 카트 (작은 2륜 경마차)", "ctx": "Transporting the stone when it was once broken was comparatively simple. The horses carried it off in cart-loads, the sheep dragged single blocks, even Muriel and Benjamin yoked themselves into an old ⟦governess-cart⟧ and did their share.", "marked": true, "note": "원래 가정교사(governess)가 아이들을 태우고 다니던, 뒤쪽에 마주 보는 좌석이 있는 낮고 작은 마차. 여기선 Muriel과 Benjamin이 끌며 돌을 날랐다.", "sid": "c6s004"}, {"word": "comparatively", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/kəmˈpærətɪvli/", "mean": "비교적, 상대적으로", "ctx": "Transporting the stone when it was once broken was ⟦comparatively⟧ simple. The horses carried it off in cart-loads, the sheep dragged single blocks, even Muriel and Benjamin yoked themselves into an old governess-cart and did their share.", "marked": true, "note": "다른 것과 견주어 보았을 때 그러하다는 뜻이다. comparatively simple(비교적 간단한)은 '간단하다'가 아니라 '돌을 깨는 일에 비하면 간단하다'는 상대적 평가다. 운반조차 결코 쉽지 않았음이, 이 한 단어의 한정 속에 숨어 있다.", "sid": "c6s004"}, {"word": "yoke", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/jəʊk/", "mean": "(멍에를) 메우다, 멍에로 잇다", "ctx": "Transporting the stone when it was once broken was comparatively simple. The horses carried it off in cart-loads, the sheep dragged single blocks, even Muriel and Benjamin ⟦yoked⟧ themselves into an old governess-cart and did their share.", "marked": true, "note": "소나 말의 목에 멍에를 씌워 수레를 끌게 하는 것을 뜻한다. yoked themselves into an old governess-cart(스스로 낡은 마차에 멍에를 메웠다)에서 주목할 것은 yoked themselves, 곧 스스로 멍에를 졌다는 점이다. 명사 yoke는 비유적으로 '억압의 굴레'를 뜻하기도 해, 자발적 노동과 굴레의 이미지가 겹친다.", "sid": "c6s004"}, {"word": "accumulate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈkjuːmjəleɪt/", "mean": "쌓이다, 축적되다, 모으다", "ctx": "The horses carried it off in cart-loads, the sheep dragged single blocks, even Muriel and Benjamin yoked themselves into an old governess-cart and did their share. By late summer a sufficient store of stone had ⟦accumulated⟧, and then the building began, under the superintendence of the pigs.", "marked": true, "note": "조금씩 모여 점점 늘어남을 뜻한다. a sufficient store of stone had accumulated(충분한 양의 돌이 쌓였다)는 더딘 노동이 시간 속에서 결실로 모이는 과정을 담는다. 과거완료가 쓰여, 건설이 시작되기 전에 이미 축적이 끝났음을 알린다.", "sid": "c6s004"}, {"word": "superintendence", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌsuːpərɪnˈtendəns/", "mean": "감독, 관리, 지휘", "ctx": "The horses carried it off in cart-loads, the sheep dragged single blocks, even Muriel and Benjamin yoked themselves into an old governess-cart and did their share. By late summer a sufficient store of stone had accumulated, and then the building began, under the ⟦superintendence⟧ of the pigs.", "marked": true, "note": "일이 잘 되도록 위에서 감독하고 지휘함을 뜻하는 격식어다. under the superintendence of the pigs(돼지들의 감독 아래)는 돼지의 역할을 노동이 아니라 관리로 규정한다. 무거운 한자어 같은 이 격식어가, 돼지들을 일하는 자리에서 한 단 높여 놓는다.", "sid": "c6s004"}, {"word": "boulder", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbəʊldə/", "mean": "(둥글고 큰) 바위, 거석", "ctx": "But it was a slow, laborious process. Frequently it took a whole day of exhausting effort to drag a single ⟦boulder⟧ to the top of the quarry, and sometimes when it was pushed over the edge it failed to break.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "hoofs", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/hʊfs/", "mean": "발굽 (복수, = hooves)", "ctx": "To see him toiling up the slope inch by inch, his breath coming fast, the tips of his ⟦hoofs⟧ clawing at the ground, and his great sides matted with sweat, filled everyone with admiration. Clover warned him sometimes to be careful not to overstrain himself, but Boxer would never listen to her.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "clawing", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈklɔːɪŋ/", "mean": "발톱으로 할퀴는", "ctx": "To see him toiling up the slope inch by inch, his breath coming fast, the tips of his hoofs ⟦clawing⟧ at the ground, and his great sides matted with sweat, filled everyone with admiration. Clover warned him sometimes to be careful not to overstrain himself, but Boxer would never listen to her.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s005", "base": "claw — 발톱으로 할퀴다"}, {"word": "admiration", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌædməˈreɪʃn/", "mean": "감탄, 존경, 흠모", "ctx": "To see him toiling up the slope inch by inch, his breath coming fast, the tips of his hoofs clawing at the ground, and his great sides matted with sweat, filled everyone with ⟦admiration⟧. Clover warned him sometimes to be careful not to overstrain himself, but Boxer would never listen to her.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "laborious", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ləˈbɔːriəs/", "mean": "고된, 힘이 많이 드는", "ctx": "But it was a slow, ⟦laborious⟧ process. Frequently it took a whole day of exhausting effort to drag a single boulder to the top of the quarry, and sometimes when it was pushed over the edge it failed to break.", "marked": true, "note": "많은 노력과 시간이 드는 고된 일을 가리킨다. a slow, laborious process(더디고 고된 과정)는 풍차 건설의 현실을 가감 없이 전한다. 작가는 노동을 미화하지 않는다. 그 고됨을 정직하게 적기에, 그것을 견디는 동물들의 헌신이 더 무겁게 다가온다.", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "toil", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/tɔɪl/", "mean": "고되게 일하다, 힘겹게 나아가다", "ctx": "To see him ⟦toiling⟧ up the slope inch by inch, his breath coming fast, the tips of his hoofs clawing at the ground, and his great sides matted with sweat, filled everyone with admiration. Clover warned him sometimes to be careful not to overstrain himself, but Boxer would never listen to her.", "marked": true, "note": "쉬지 않고 몹시 애써 일함을 뜻하며, 힘겹게 움직여 나아간다는 뜻으로도 쓰인다. To see him toiling up the slope inch by inch(한 치 한 치 비탈을 힘겹게 오르는 그를 보는 것)에서 toil은 Boxer의 노동을 거의 고통에 가까운 분투로 그린다.", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "strain oneself", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/streɪn/", "mean": "(몸에) 무리하다, 힘껏 용을 쓰다", "ctx": "When the boulder began to slip and the animals cried out in despair at finding themselves dragged down the hill, it was always Boxer who ⟦strained⟧ himself against the rope and brought the boulder to a stop.", "marked": true, "note": "근육을 한껏 당겨 힘을 쏟거나, 그러다 몸을 상하게 함을 뜻한다. it was always Boxer who strained himself against the rope(언제나 밧줄에 몸을 던져 버틴 것은 Boxer였다)에서, 그가 매번 자기 몸을 한계까지 밀어붙임을 보여 준다. 이 무리함이 훗날 그의 몸을 무너뜨릴 씨앗이다.", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "matted", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈmætɪd/", "mean": "(털 등이) 엉겨 붙은, 뒤엉킨", "ctx": "To see him toiling up the slope inch by inch, his breath coming fast, the tips of his hoofs clawing at the ground, and his great sides ⟦matted⟧ with sweat, filled everyone with admiration. Clover warned him sometimes to be careful not to overstrain himself, but Boxer would never listen to her.", "marked": true, "note": "땀이나 물기로 털이 한데 엉겨 붙은 상태를 뜻한다. his great sides matted with sweat(땀으로 엉겨 붙은 그 거대한 옆구리)는 Boxer의 분투를 몸에 새겨진 흔적으로 보여 준다. 노동의 대가가 추상적 칭찬이 아니라 젖은 살갗으로 제시된다.", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "overstrain", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌəʊvəˈstreɪn/", "mean": "지나치게 무리하다, 과로하다", "ctx": "To see him toiling up the slope inch by inch, his breath coming fast, the tips of his hoofs clawing at the ground, and his great sides matted with sweat, filled everyone with admiration. Clover warned him sometimes to be careful not to ⟦overstrain⟧ himself, but Boxer would never listen to her.", "marked": true, "note": "접두사 over(지나치게)와 strain(무리하다)이 결합해, 몸이 감당할 한계를 넘어 무리함을 뜻한다. be careful not to overstrain himself(무리하지 않도록 조심하라)는 Clover의 경고다. 그러나 Boxer는 듣지 않는다. 이 한 단어가, 앞으로 그의 몸에 닥칠 비극을 미리 비춘다.", "sid": "c6s005"}, {"word": "slogan", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsləʊɡən/", "mean": "구호, 표어", "ctx": "His two ⟦slogans⟧, “I will work harder” and “Napoleon is always right,” seemed to him a sufficient answer to all problems. He had made arrangements with the cockerel to call him three-quarters of an hour earlier in the mornings instead of half an hour.", "marked": true, "note": "기억하기 쉽게 압축한 짧은 문구로, 신념이나 운동을 한마디로 내세운다. His two slogans(그의 두 구호)는 Boxer가 세상을 대하는 방식 전체를 단 두 문장으로 줄여 놓는다. 구호의 힘은 단순함이지만, 그 단순함이 곧 생각을 대신하기도 한다.", "sid": "c6s006"}, {"word": "sufficient", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/səˈfɪʃnt/", "mean": "충분한, 족한", "ctx": "His two slogans, “I will work harder” and “Napoleon is always right,” seemed to him a ⟦sufficient⟧ answer to all problems. He had made arrangements with the cockerel to call him three-quarters of an hour earlier in the mornings instead of half an hour.", "marked": true, "note": "필요를 채우기에 모자람이 없음을 뜻한다. a sufficient answer to all problems(모든 문제에 대한 충분한 답)에서, 두 구호가 '모든' 문제를 푸는 데 족하다고 여겨진다. 그러나 두 마디가 모든 물음의 답이 될 수 있다는 그 믿음 자체가, 사유의 포기를 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s006"}, {"word": "make arrangements", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/əˈreɪndʒmənts/", "mean": "(미리) 조치하다, 채비를 갖추다", "ctx": "His two slogans, “I will work harder” and “Napoleon is always right,” seemed to him a sufficient answer to all problems. He had made arrangements with the cockerel to call him three-quarters of an hour earlier in the mornings instead of half an hour. And in his spare moments, of which there were not…", "marked": false, "note": "어떤 일이 되도록 미리 준비하거나 약속을 잡음을 뜻한다. He had made arrangements with the cockerel to call him... earlier(더 일찍 깨워 달라고 수탉과 미리 약속해 두었다)는 Boxer가 스스로 자신의 노동을 늘리려 능동적으로 손을 썼음을 보여 준다. 누가 시킨 것이 아니라 그 자신이 한 일이다.", "sid": "c6s006"}, {"word": "cockerel", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkɒkərəl/", "mean": "어린 수탉", "ctx": "His two slogans, “I will work harder” and “Napoleon is always right,” seemed to him a sufficient answer to all problems. He had made arrangements with the ⟦cockerel⟧ to call him three-quarters of an hour earlier in the mornings instead of half an hour.", "marked": true, "note": "아직 다 자라지 않은 젊은 수탉을 가리킨다. made arrangements with the cockerel to call him... earlier에서 수탉은 아침을 알리는 자명종 노릇을 한다. Boxer는 그 알림 시각마저 앞당겨, 잠을 줄이고 노동을 늘린다.", "sid": "c6s006"}, {"word": "unassisted", "pos": "adv./adj.", "pron": "/ˌʌnəˈsɪstɪd/", "mean": "도움 없이, 혼자 힘으로", "ctx": "And in his spare moments, of which there were not many nowadays, he would go alone to the quarry, collect a load of broken stone, and drag it down to the site of the windmill ⟦unassisted⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "접두사 un(없이)과 assisted(도움받는)가 결합해, 아무 도움 없이 홀로 함을 뜻한다. drag it down to the site of the windmill unassisted(혼자 힘으로 풍차 터까지 끌어 내렸다)는 문장의 맨 끝에 놓여, Boxer의 노동이 요구된 몫을 넘어 홀로 이뤄진 것임을 강조한다.", "sid": "c6s006"}, {"word": "hardness", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈhɑːdnəs/", "mean": "고됨, 가혹함; 단단함", "ctx": "The animals were not badly off throughout that summer, in spite of the ⟦hardness⟧ of their work. If they had no more food than they had had in Jones’s day, at least they did not have less.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s007"}, {"word": "badly off", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˌbædli ˈɒf/", "mean": "형편이 어려운, 궁핍한", "ctx": "The animals were not ⟦badly off⟧ throughout that summer, in spite of the hardness of their work. If they had no more food than they had had in Jones’s day, at least they did not have less.", "marked": true, "note": "살림이나 처지가 좋지 못함을 뜻하는 구어 표현으로, 반대는 well off(형편이 넉넉한)다. 본문은 were not badly off(형편이 나쁘지 않았다)처럼 부정으로 써서, '넉넉했다'고 곧장 말하는 대신 '나쁘지는 않았다'고 한발 물러나 표현한다. 이렇게 부정을 부정하는 절제된 말투가 이 문장 전체의 어조를 정한다.", "sid": "c6s007"}, {"word": "in spite of", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ɪn ˈspaɪt əv/", "mean": "~에도 불구하고", "ctx": "The animals were not badly off throughout that summer, ⟦in spite of⟧ the hardness of their work. If they had no more food than they had had in Jones’s day, at least they did not have less.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s007"}, {"word": "extravagant", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɪkˈstrævəɡənt/", "mean": "낭비하는, 사치스러운", "ctx": "If they had no more food than they had had in Jones’s day, at least they did not have less. The advantage of only having to feed themselves, and not having to support five ⟦extravagant⟧ human beings as well, was so great that it would have taken a lot of failures to outweigh it.", "marked": true, "note": "필요 이상으로 쓰고 누림을 뜻한다. 라틴어 extra(밖으로)와 vagari(헤매다)에서 와서, 본래 '정도를 벗어나 떠돈다'는 뜻이었다. five extravagant human beings(다섯의 사치스러운 인간)는 생산은 않고 소비만 하던 옛 주인 가족을 가리키며, 그 한 단어가 부양의 부담을 도덕적 낭비로 물들인다.", "sid": "c6s007"}, {"word": "outweigh", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌaʊtˈweɪ/", "mean": "~보다 더 무겁다, (가치·중요성이) 능가하다", "ctx": "If they had no more food than they had had in Jones’s day, at least they did not have less. The advantage of only having to feed themselves, and not having to support five extravagant human beings as well, was so great that it would have taken a lot of failures to ⟦outweigh⟧ it.", "marked": true, "note": "out(능가하여)과 weigh(무게가 나가다)가 결합해, 저울에 올렸을 때 한쪽이 더 무겁다는 데서 '더 중요하다. 상쇄하고도 남는다'는 뜻으로 쓰인다. it would have taken a lot of failures to outweigh it(그것을 상쇄하려면 숱한 실패가 필요했을 것)에서, 이점이 워낙 무거워 어지간한 실패로는 저울이 기울지 않음을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s007"}, {"word": "efficient", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɪˈfɪʃnt/", "mean": "효율적인, 능률적인", "ctx": "And in many ways the animal method of doing things was more ⟦efficient⟧ and saved labour. Such jobs as weeding, for instance, could be done with a thoroughness impossible to human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "적은 노력·시간·자원으로 더 많은 결과를 내는 것을 뜻한다. the animal method of doing things was more efficient and saved labour(동물식 방식이 더 효율적이고 노동을 덜었다)에서, 효율은 곧 같은 일에 드는 수고가 줄었음을 가리킨다. 앞 블록이 '먹여야 할 입'의 셈이었다면, 여기서는 '들여야 할 노동'의 셈으로 이어진다.", "sid": "c6s008"}, {"word": "thoroughness", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈθʌrənəs/", "mean": "철저함, 꼼꼼함", "ctx": "And in many ways the animal method of doing things was more efficient and saved labour. Such jobs as weeding, for instance, could be done with a ⟦thoroughness⟧ impossible to human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "형용사 thorough(빈틈없는)의 명사형으로, 일을 끝까지 빠짐없이 해내는 성질을 뜻한다. a thoroughness impossible to human beings(인간으로서는 불가능한 철저함)는 김매기 같은 일을 동물이 인간보다 더 꼼꼼히 해낸다고 말하며, 자기 일에 임하는 노동의 질이 달라졌음을 슬쩍 내세운다.", "sid": "c6s008"}, {"word": "fence off", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/fens ɒf/", "mean": "울타리로 막다, 구획을 쳐 분리하다", "ctx": "Such jobs as weeding, for instance, could be done with a thoroughness impossible to human beings. And again, since no animal now stole, it was unnecessary to ⟦fence off⟧ pasture from arable land, which saved a lot of labour on the upkeep of hedges and gates.", "marked": true, "note": "울타리(fence)를 쳐서 한 구역을 다른 구역과 갈라놓음을 뜻한다. it was unnecessary to fence off pasture from arable land(목초지를 경작지와 울타리로 가를 필요가 없었다)에서, 울타리는 본래 가축이 작물을 망치지 못하게, 또 남의 것을 넘보지 못하게 막는 장치다. 그 필요가 사라졌다는 것이 이 문장의 핵심이다.", "sid": "c6s008"}, {"word": "arable / pasture", "pos": "adj. / n.", "pron": "/ˈærəbl/, /ˈpɑːstʃə/", "mean": "경작에 적합한 / 목초지, 방목지", "ctx": "Such jobs as weeding, for instance, could be done with a thoroughness impossible to human beings. And again, since no animal now stole, it was unnecessary to fence off pasture from ⟦arable⟧ land, which saved a lot of labour on the upkeep of hedges and gates.", "marked": true, "note": "농경에서 땅은 크게 둘로 나뉜다. arable land는 쟁기로 갈아 작물을 기르는 경작지이고, pasture는 가축이 풀을 뜯는 방목지다. 본문 fence off pasture from arable land은 이 둘을 가르던 울타리를 말한다. 두 땅을 굳이 나누지 않아도 되는 까닭이 바로 다음에 이어진다.", "sid": "c6s008"}, {"word": "upkeep", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈʌpkiːp/", "mean": "(시설의) 유지, 보수, 관리", "ctx": "Such jobs as weeding, for instance, could be done with a thoroughness impossible to human beings. And again, since no animal now stole, it was unnecessary to fence off pasture from arable land, which saved a lot of labour on the ⟦upkeep⟧ of hedges and gates.", "marked": true, "note": "무언가를 좋은 상태로 계속 지키는 데 드는 손질과 비용을 뜻한다. a lot of labour on the upkeep of hedges and gates(산울타리와 문을 손보는 데 드는 많은 노동)에서, 울타리를 칠 필요가 없어지자 그것을 유지·보수하던 노동까지 함께 사라졌음을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s008"}, {"word": "paraffin", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈpærəfɪn/", "mean": "등유, 등불용 기름", "ctx": "Nevertheless, as the summer wore on, various unforeseen shortages began to make themselves felt. There was need of ⟦paraffin⟧ oil, nails, string, dog biscuits, and iron for the horses’ shoes, none of which could be produced on the farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "procured", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/prəˈkjʊəd/", "mean": "(애써) 조달했다, 구해 왔다", "ctx": "Later there would also be need for seeds and artificial manures, besides various tools and, finally, the machinery for the windmill. How these were to be ⟦procured⟧, no one was able to imagine.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "nevertheless", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˌnevəðəˈles/", "mean": "그럼에도 불구하고", "ctx": "⟦Nevertheless⟧, as the summer wore on, various unforeseen shortages began to make themselves felt. There was need of paraffin oil, nails, string, dog biscuits, and iron for the horses’ shoes, none of which could be produced on the farm.", "marked": true, "note": "앞에 말한 내용과 반대되는 사실을 이끄는 격식 있는 연결어다. 문장 맨 앞에 놓인 Nevertheless는 바로 앞 블록의 흡족한 결산('형편이 나쁘지 않다. 효율적이다')을 단 한 단어로 뒤집어, 그늘진 국면으로 어조를 돌려세운다.", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "wear on", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/weər ɒn/", "mean": "(시간이) 더디게 흘러가다", "ctx": "Nevertheless, as the summer wore on, various unforeseen shortages began to make themselves felt. There was need of paraffin oil, nails, string, dog biscuits, and iron for the horses’ shoes, none of which could be produced on the farm. Later there would also be need for seeds and artificial manures, …", "marked": false, "note": "시간이 천천히, 다소 지루하게 흘러감을 뜻하는 표현이다. as the summer wore on(여름이 깊어 가면서)에서, 그저 '여름이 지나면서'보다 시간이 더디게 흐르는 느낌을 담아, 결핍이 서서히 드러나는 흐름과 잘 어울린다.", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "unforeseen", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌʌnfɔːˈsiːn/", "mean": "예기치 못한, 미처 내다보지 못한", "ctx": "Nevertheless, as the summer wore on, various ⟦unforeseen⟧ shortages began to make themselves felt. There was need of paraffin oil, nails, string, dog biscuits, and iron for the horses’ shoes, none of which could be produced on the farm.", "marked": true, "note": "접두사 un(아니)과 foresee(미리 내다보다)의 과거분사가 결합해, 미리 헤아리지 못한 일을 뜻한다. various unforeseen shortages(여러 예기치 못한 부족)는, 풍요의 셈에 들떠 있던 동물들이 미처 셈에 넣지 못한 결핍이 닥쳐옴을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "shortage", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈʃɔːtɪdʒ/", "mean": "부족, 결핍", "ctx": "Nevertheless, as the summer wore on, various unforeseen ⟦shortages⟧ began to make themselves felt. There was need of paraffin oil, nails, string, dog biscuits, and iron for the horses’ shoes, none of which could be produced on the farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "artificial manures", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌɑːtɪˈfɪʃl məˈnjʊəz/", "mean": "화학 비료, 인공 거름", "ctx": "There was need of paraffin oil, nails, string, dog biscuits, and iron for the horses’ shoes, none of which could be produced on the farm. Later there would also be need for seeds and ⟦artificial manures⟧, besides various tools and, finally, the machinery for the windmill.", "marked": true, "note": "manure는 본래 가축의 똥거름을 뜻하나, artificial manure는 공장에서 만든 화학 비료를 가리키는 옛 표현이다. seeds and artificial manures(씨앗과 화학 비료)는 농장에서 스스로 만들 수 없고 밖에서 들여와야 하는 물자라는 점이 핵심이다.", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "procure", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/prəˈkjʊə/", "mean": "(특히 애써서) 구하다, 조달하다", "ctx": "Later there would also be need for seeds and artificial manures, besides various tools and, finally, the machinery for the windmill. How these were to be ⟦procured⟧, no one was able to imagine.", "marked": true, "note": "필요한 것을 노력과 수단을 들여 손에 넣음을 뜻하는 격식어로, get·obtain보다 '구하기 어려운 것을 애써 마련한다'는 결이 강하다. How these were to be procured, no one was able to imagine(이것들을 어떻게 조달할지 아무도 그려 볼 수 없었다)에서, 이 단어의 무게가 곧 닥칠 난제의 크기를 가늠케 한다.", "sid": "c6s009"}, {"word": "assemble", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈsembl/", "mean": "(한곳에) 모이다, 집합하다", "ctx": "One Sunday morning, when the animals ⟦assembled⟧ to receive their orders, Napoleon announced that he had decided upon a new policy.", "marked": true, "note": "사람·동물이 한 장소에 함께 모임을 뜻하며, 흩어진 부품을 '조립하다'는 뜻도 있다. when the animals assembled to receive their orders(동물들이 명령을 받으러 모였을 때)에서, 이 집회가 더는 토론의 자리가 아니라 '명령을 받는' 자리임이 동사 하나에 담겨 있다.", "sid": "c6s010"}, {"word": "decide upon", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/dɪˈsaɪd əˈpɒn/", "mean": "~으로 정하다, ~을 결정하다", "ctx": "One Sunday morning, when the animals assembled to receive their orders, Napoleon announced that he had ⟦decided⟧ upon a new policy.", "marked": true, "note": "여러 가능성 가운데 하나를 골라 확정함을 뜻하며, decide on과 같다. he had decided upon a new policy(그가 새 정책을 결정해 두었다)에서, 주어가 단수 he이고 이미 결정이 끝난 상태(과거완료)라는 점이 중요하다. 결정은 모임 전에, 한 사람에 의해 이미 내려져 있었다.", "sid": "c6s010"}, {"word": "engage in", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ɪnˈɡeɪdʒ ɪn/", "mean": "~에 종사하다, ~을 (활동으로) 하다", "ctx": "From now onwards Animal Farm would ⟦engage in⟧ trade with the neighbouring farms: not, of course, for any commercial purpose, but simply in order to obtain certain materials which were urgently necessary. The needs of the windmill must override everything else, he said.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 활동에 발을 들여 그것을 행함을 뜻하는 격식 표현이다. Animal Farm would engage in trade with the neighbouring farms(동물 농장이 이웃 농장들과 거래를 하게 될 것)에서, '거래(trade)'라는 한 단어가 그동안의 원칙과 정면으로 부딪친다는 점에 무게가 실린다.", "sid": "c6s010"}, {"word": "commercial", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/kəˈmɜːʃl/", "mean": "상업적인, 이윤을 노리는", "ctx": "From now onwards Animal Farm would engage in trade with the neighbouring farms: not, of course, for any ⟦commercial⟧ purpose, but simply in order to obtain certain materials which were urgently necessary. The needs of the windmill must override everything else, he said.", "marked": true, "note": "사고팔아 이익을 얻는 활동에 관한 것을 뜻한다. not, of course, for any commercial purpose(물론 어떤 상업적 목적도 아니라)에서, 거래를 시작하면서도 그것이 '상업'은 아니라고 미리 잘라 두는 부인이 이 단어를 통해 이뤄진다. 거래하되 상업은 아니라는 묘한 선 긋기다.", "sid": "c6s010"}, {"word": "obtain", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əbˈteɪn/", "mean": "얻다, 입수하다", "ctx": "From now onwards Animal Farm would engage in trade with the neighbouring farms: not, of course, for any commercial purpose, but simply in order to ⟦obtain⟧ certain materials which were urgently necessary. The needs of the windmill must override everything else, he said.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s010"}, {"word": "override", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌəʊvəˈraɪd/", "mean": "~에 우선하다, ~을 제치고 앞서다", "ctx": "From now onwards Animal Farm would engage in trade with the neighbouring farms: not, of course, for any commercial purpose, but simply in order to obtain certain materials which were urgently necessary. The needs of the windmill must ⟦override⟧ everything else, he said.", "marked": true, "note": "over(위로)와 ride(올라타다)가 결합해, 다른 것을 누르고 위에 올라선다는 데서 '~보다 우선시되다, ~을 무효화하다'는 뜻으로 쓰인다. The needs of the windmill must override everything else(풍차의 필요가 다른 모든 것에 우선해야 한다)에서, 하나의 목표가 그 밖의 모든 원칙을 제치고 맨 위에 놓인다는 절대적 우선순위가 선언된다.", "sid": "c6s010"}, {"word": "stack", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/stæk/", "mean": "(건초 등을) 쌓아 올린 더미, 가리", "ctx": "He was therefore making arrangements to sell a ⟦stack⟧ of hay and part of the current year’s wheat crop, and later on, if more money were needed, it would have to be made up by the sale of eggs, for which there was always a market in Willingdon.", "marked": true, "note": "물건을 차곡차곡 쌓아 올린 무더기를 뜻하며, 농장에서는 흔히 건초나 짚을 크게 쌓아 둔 '가리'를 가리킨다. a stack of hay(건초 한 가리)는 농장이 한 해 거둔 사료의 큰 몫으로, 그것을 팔아 치운다는 것은 농장 자신의 양식에 손을 댄다는 뜻이기도 하다.", "sid": "c6s011"}, {"word": "crop", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/krɒp/", "mean": "농작물, (한 철의) 수확량", "ctx": "He was therefore making arrangements to sell a stack of hay and part of the current year’s wheat ⟦crop⟧, and later on, if more money were needed, it would have to be made up by the sale of eggs, for which there was always a market in Willingdon.", "marked": true, "note": "밭에서 길러 거두는 작물, 또는 한 철에 거둔 수확 전체를 뜻한다. part of the current year's wheat crop(그해 밀 수확의 일부)에서, 그해 거둔 밀의 한 몫을 내다 판다는 것은 곧 동물들이 먹을 식량을 덜어 낸다는 의미가 된다.", "sid": "c6s011"}, {"word": "make up", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/meɪk ʌp/", "mean": "(부족분을) 메우다, 채우다, 보충하다", "ctx": "He was therefore making arrangements to sell a stack of hay and part of the current year’s wheat crop, and later on, if more money were needed, it would have to be made up by the sale of eggs, for which there was always a market in Willingdon. The hens, said Napoleon, should welcome this sacrifice a…", "marked": false, "note": "모자란 양을 다른 것으로 채워 맞춤을 뜻한다. it would have to be made up by the sale of eggs(달걀을 팔아 메워야 할 것)에서, 돈이 더 필요해질 때 그 부족분을 달걀 판매로 충당하겠다는 것이다. 수동태로 쓰여, 누가 그 짐을 지우는지는 슬쩍 가려진다.", "sid": "c6s011"}, {"word": "welcome", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈwelkəm/", "mean": "기꺼이 맞이하다, 반기다", "ctx": "The hens, said Napoleon, should ⟦welcome⟧ this sacrifice as their own special contribution towards the building of the windmill.", "marked": true, "note": "무언가를 반갑게 받아들임을 뜻한다. The hens... should welcome this sacrifice(암탉들은 이 희생을 기꺼이 맞아야 한다)에서, 빼앗기는 일을 도리어 반겨야 한다고 요구한다. 본래 기쁨에서 우러나야 할 '환영'이, 여기서는 위에서 내려온 의무가 된다.", "sid": "c6s011"}, {"word": "contribution", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌkɒntrɪˈbjuːʃn/", "mean": "기여, 이바지, 보탬", "ctx": "The hens, said Napoleon, should welcome this sacrifice as their own special ⟦contribution⟧ towards the building of the windmill.", "marked": true, "note": "공동의 목적에 보태는 몫을 뜻한다. their own special contribution towards the building of the windmill(풍차 건설을 위한 그들만의 특별한 기여)에서, 빼앗기는 달걀이 암탉 '자신의' 특별한 보탬으로 둔갑한다. 강제된 부담이 자랑스러운 몫처럼 포장되는 자리다.", "sid": "c6s011"}, {"word": "conscious of", "pos": "adj.phr.", "pron": "/ˈkɒnʃəs əv/", "mean": "~을 의식하는, 알아차리는", "ctx": "Once again the animals were ⟦conscious of⟧ a vague uneasiness. Never to have any dealings with human beings, never to engage in trade, never to make use of money — had not these been among the earliest resolutions passed at that first triumphant Meeting after Jones was expelled?", "marked": true, "note": "무언가를 마음으로 느끼거나 자각하고 있음을 뜻한다. Once again the animals were conscious of a vague uneasiness(다시 한 번 동물들은 막연한 불안을 의식했다)에서, 또렷이 짚어 말하지는 못해도 마음 어딘가가 꺼림칙함을 느끼는 상태를 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s012"}, {"word": "uneasiness", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ʌnˈiːzinəs/", "mean": "불안, 꺼림칙함, 마음 편치 않음", "ctx": "Once again the animals were conscious of a vague ⟦uneasiness⟧. Never to have any dealings with human beings, never to engage in trade, never to make use of money — had not these been among the earliest resolutions passed at that first triumphant Meeting after Jones was expelled?", "marked": true, "note": "un(아닌)과 ease(편안함)에서 나온 말로, 마음이 편하지 않은 상태를 뜻한다. 앞에 붙은 vague(막연한)와 어울려, 무엇 때문인지 콕 집지 못한 채 어렴풋이 감도는 거북함을 나타낸다. 또렷한 항의가 아니라 흐릿한 예감이라는 점이 핵심이다.", "sid": "c6s012"}, {"word": "dealings", "pos": "n.(pl.)", "pron": "/ˈdiːlɪŋz/", "mean": "거래, 왕래, (사람·집단 간의) 교섭", "ctx": "Once again the animals were conscious of a vague uneasiness. Never to have any ⟦dealings⟧ with human beings, never to engage in trade, never to make use of money — had not these been among the earliest resolutions passed at that first triumphant Meeting after Jones was expelled?", "marked": true, "note": "주로 복수형으로 쓰여, 누군가와 주고받는 거래나 관계 전반을 뜻한다. Never to have any dealings with human beings(인간과는 어떤 왕래도 갖지 않을 것)에서, 단순한 매매를 넘어 인간과 엮이는 모든 관계를 끊겠다는 옛 다짐을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s012"}, {"word": "resolution", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌrezəˈluːʃn/", "mean": "결의, 결의안 (공식적으로 정한 다짐)", "ctx": "Once again the animals were conscious of a vague uneasiness. Never to have any dealings with human beings, never to engage in trade, never to make use of money — had not these been among the earliest ⟦resolutions⟧ passed at that first triumphant Meeting after Jones was expelled?", "marked": true, "note": "회의에서 표결로 채택한 공식적 결정을 뜻한다(일상에서는 '결심'). the earliest resolutions passed at that first triumphant Meeting(그 첫 승리의 회의에서 통과된 가장 이른 결의들)에서, 이것은 한 개인의 결심이 아니라 모두가 함께 정한 건국의 원칙임을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s012"}, {"word": "triumphant", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/traɪˈʌmfənt/", "mean": "의기양양한, 승리에 찬", "ctx": "Once again the animals were conscious of a vague uneasiness. Never to have any dealings with human beings, never to engage in trade, never to make use of money — had not these been among the earliest resolutions passed at that first ⟦triumphant⟧ Meeting after Jones was expelled?", "marked": true, "note": "큰 승리를 거두어 기쁨과 자부심에 차 있음을 뜻한다. that first triumphant Meeting after Jones was expelled(Jones가 쫓겨난 뒤의 그 첫 승리의 회의)에서, 혁명 직후의 벅찬 분위기를 환기하며, 그 뜨거운 출발의 다짐과 지금의 흔들림을 은연중 대비시킨다.", "sid": "c6s012"}, {"word": "expel", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɪkˈspel/", "mean": "쫓아내다, 추방하다", "ctx": "Once again the animals were conscious of a vague uneasiness. Never to have any dealings with human beings, never to engage in trade, never to make use of money — had not these been among the earliest resolutions passed at that first triumphant Meeting after Jones was ⟦expelled⟧?", "marked": true, "note": "강제로 밀어내어 내쫓음을 뜻하며, 학교에서 '퇴학시키다'의 뜻으로도 쓰인다. after Jones was expelled(Jones가 쫓겨난 뒤)에서, 혁명으로 옛 주인을 몰아낸 그 출발의 순간을 가리킨다. 수동태로 쓰여 누가 쫓아냈는지보다 '쫓겨남'이라는 사건 자체에 초점이 놓인다.", "sid": "c6s012"}, {"word": "protest", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/prəˈtest/", "mean": "항의하다, 이의를 제기하다", "ctx": "The four young pigs who had ⟦protested⟧ when Napoleon abolished the Meetings raised their voices timidly, but they were promptly silenced by a tremendous growling from the dogs. Then, as usual, the sheep broke into “Four legs good, two legs bad!” and the momentary awkwardness was smoothed over.", "marked": true, "note": "옳지 않다고 여기는 일에 반대의 뜻을 드러냄을 뜻한다. 동사일 때 강세는 뒤(pro-TEST), 명사일 때는 앞(PRO-test)에 온다. The four young pigs who had protested(항의했던 네 어린 돼지)에서, 이들은 앞서 한 번 반대의 목소리를 냈던 자들로 표시된다.", "sid": "c6s013"}, {"word": "abolish", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈbɒlɪʃ/", "mean": "(제도·관습 등을) 폐지하다, 없애다", "ctx": "The four young pigs who had protested when Napoleon ⟦abolished⟧ the Meetings raised their voices timidly, but they were promptly silenced by a tremendous growling from the dogs. Then, as usual, the sheep broke into “Four legs good, two legs bad!” and the momentary awkwardness was smoothed over.", "marked": true, "note": "법·제도·관습처럼 한동안 이어져 온 것을 공식적으로 없앰을 뜻한다. when Napoleon abolished the Meetings(Napoleon이 회의를 폐지했을 때)에서, 함께 모여 의논하던 제도 자체가 사라졌음을 가리킨다. 토론의 장이 없어진 일이 이 항의의 배경이다.", "sid": "c6s013"}, {"word": "timidly", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈtɪmɪdli/", "mean": "겁먹은 듯, 머뭇거리며, 소심하게", "ctx": "The four young pigs who had protested when Napoleon abolished the Meetings raised their voices ⟦timidly⟧, but they were promptly silenced by a tremendous growling from the dogs. Then, as usual, the sheep broke into “Four legs good, two legs bad!” and the momentary awkwardness was smoothed over.", "marked": true, "note": "두려워하며 자신 없이 머뭇거리는 모양을 뜻한다. raised their voices timidly(머뭇거리며 목소리를 높였다)에서, 항의가 당당하지 못하고 이미 위축되어 있음을 드러낸다. 저항의 크기가 처음부터 작게 그려진다는 점이 중요하다.", "sid": "c6s013"}, {"word": "promptly", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈprɒmptli/", "mean": "즉각, 지체 없이", "ctx": "The four young pigs who had protested when Napoleon abolished the Meetings raised their voices timidly, but they were ⟦promptly⟧ silenced by a tremendous growling from the dogs. Then, as usual, the sheep broke into “Four legs good, two legs bad!” and the momentary awkwardness was smoothed over.", "marked": true, "note": "머뭇거림 없이 곧바로 일어남을 뜻한다. they were promptly silenced(그들은 즉각 침묵당했다)에서, 진압이 망설임도 절차도 없이 곧바로 이뤄짐을 가리킨다. 항의의 timidly(머뭇거림)와 진압의 promptly(즉각)가 속도에서 정면으로 대비된다.", "sid": "c6s013"}, {"word": "tremendous", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/trəˈmendəs/", "mean": "엄청난, 굉장한, 어마어마한", "ctx": "The four young pigs who had protested when Napoleon abolished the Meetings raised their voices timidly, but they were promptly silenced by a ⟦tremendous⟧ growling from the dogs. Then, as usual, the sheep broke into “Four legs good, two legs bad!” and the momentary awkwardness was smoothed over.", "marked": true, "note": "크기·강도가 압도적으로 큼을 뜻한다. a tremendous growling from the dogs(개들의 어마어마한 으르렁거림)에서, 머뭇거리는 작은 목소리(timid voices)와 정반대의 거대한 소리를 세워, 저항과 위협의 크기 차이를 소리로 보여 준다.", "sid": "c6s013"}, {"word": "smooth over", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/smuːð ˈəʊvə/", "mean": "(문제·갈등을) 무마하다, 덮어 넘기다", "ctx": "The four young pigs who had protested when Napoleon abolished the Meetings raised their voices timidly, but they were promptly silenced by a tremendous growling from the dogs. Then, as usual, the sheep broke into “Four legs good, two legs bad!” and the momentary awkwardness was ⟦smoothed⟧ over.", "marked": true, "note": "불편하거나 껄끄러운 일을 매끄럽게 덮어 없던 것처럼 넘김을 뜻한다. the momentary awkwardness was smoothed over(잠깐의 어색함이 무마되었다)에서, 방금 벌어진 위협과 침묵을 한갓 '잠깐의 어색함'으로 줄여 매끄럽게 덮어 버린다. 무엇이 덮였는지가 이 표현의 핵심이다.", "sid": "c6s013"}, {"word": "trotter", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtrɒtə(r)/", "mean": "돼지의 발", "ctx": "Finally Napoleon raised his ⟦trotter⟧ for silence and announced that he had already made all the arrangements. There would be no need for any of the animals to come in contact with human beings, which would clearly be most undesirable. He intended to take the whole burden upon his own shoulders.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "come in contact with", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/kʌm ɪn ˈkɒntækt wɪð/", "mean": "~와 접촉하다, 맞닥뜨리다", "ctx": "Finally Napoleon raised his trotter for silence and announced that he had already made all the arrangements. There would be no need for any of the animals to ⟦come in contact with⟧ human beings, which would clearly be most undesirable. He intended to take the whole burden upon his own shoulders.", "marked": true, "note": "누군가·무언가와 직접 맞닿거나 마주치게 됨을 뜻한다. no need for any of the animals to come in contact with human beings(어떤 동물도 인간과 접촉할 필요가 없다)에서, 외부와의 모든 접점을 동물 일반에게서 떼어 놓겠다는 뜻이며, 그 접점을 누가 대신 쥐게 되는지가 다음에 이어진다.", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "undesirable", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌʌndɪˈzaɪərəbl/", "mean": "바람직하지 않은, 달갑지 않은", "ctx": "Finally Napoleon raised his trotter for silence and announced that he had already made all the arrangements. There would be no need for any of the animals to come in contact with human beings, which would clearly be most ⟦undesirable⟧. He intended to take the whole burden upon his own shoulders.", "marked": true, "note": "un(아닌)과 desirable(바람직한)이 결합한 격식어다. which would clearly be most undesirable(그것은 분명 매우 바람직하지 않을 것)에서, 인간과의 접촉을 부정적으로 규정하는 판단이 담긴다. 앞의 clearly(분명히)와 어울려, 다툼의 여지가 있는 주장을 자명한 사실처럼 내세운다.", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "burden", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbɜːdn/", "mean": "짐, 부담, 떠맡은 무게", "ctx": "Finally Napoleon raised his trotter for silence and announced that he had already made all the arrangements. There would be no need for any of the animals to come in contact with human beings, which would clearly be most undesirable. He intended to take the whole ⟦burden⟧ upon his own shoulders.", "marked": true, "note": "짊어져야 할 무거운 책임이나 일을 뜻한다. take the whole burden upon his own shoulders(그 모든 짐을 제 어깨에 짊어지다)에서, 외부와의 접촉을 홀로 떠맡는 일이 '부담'으로 그려진다. 그러나 그 부담을 진다는 것은 동시에 그 통로를 독차지한다는 뜻이기도 하다.", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "intermediary", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌɪntəˈmiːdiəri/", "mean": "중개자, 중재자, 사이를 잇는 사람", "ctx": "He intended to take the whole burden upon his own shoulders. A Mr. Whymper, a solicitor living in Willingdon, had agreed to act as ⟦intermediary⟧ between Animal Farm and the outside world, and would visit the farm every Monday morning to receive his instructions.", "marked": true, "note": "inter(사이)에서 나온 말로, 두 편 사이에 서서 거래나 소통을 잇는 사람을 뜻한다. act as intermediary between Animal Farm and the outside world(동물 농장과 바깥 세계 사이의 중개자 노릇을 하다)에서, 농장과 인간 세계를 잇는 다리 역할을 가리킨다. 이 다리를 통해서만 거래가 오갈 수 있다.", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "solicitor", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/səˈlɪsɪtə/", "mean": "(영국의) 사무 변호사", "ctx": "He intended to take the whole burden upon his own shoulders. A Mr. Whymper, a ⟦solicitor⟧ living in Willingdon, had agreed to act as intermediary between Animal Farm and the outside world, and would visit the farm every Monday morning to receive his instructions.", "marked": true, "note": "영국에서 계약·서류·일상 법률 사무를 다루는 변호사를 가리키는 말이다(법정 변론을 맡는 barrister와 구분된다). a solicitor living in Willingdon(Willingdon에 사는 사무 변호사)에서, 거래와 서류를 매끄럽게 처리할 수 있는 인간 전문가가 농장의 창구로 들어옴을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "dismiss", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/dɪsˈmɪs/", "mean": "해산시키다, 물러가게 하다", "ctx": "Napoleon ended his speech with his usual cry of “Long live Animal Farm!” and after the singing of ‘Beasts of England’ the animals were ⟦dismissed⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "모인 사람들을 흩어 보내거나 자리를 뜨게 함을 뜻한다(생각·의견을 '일축하다'의 뜻도 있다). the animals were dismissed(동물들은 해산되었다)에서, 수동태로 쓰여 동물들이 스스로 흩어진 것이 아니라 위에서 물러가도록 시켜졌음을 드러낸다. 집회의 시작과 끝이 모두 위의 처분에 달려 있다.", "sid": "c6s014"}, {"word": "traceable", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈtreɪsəbl/", "mean": "추적 가능한, 거슬러 갈 수 있는", "ctx": "Afterwards Squealer made a round of the farm and set the animals’ minds at rest. He assured them that the resolution against engaging in trade and using money had never been passed, or even suggested. It was pure imagination, probably ⟦traceable⟧ in the beginning to lies circulated by Snowball.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "comrades", "pos": "n. (pl., vocative)", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪdz/", "mean": "동지들이여", "ctx": "It was pure imagination, probably traceable in the beginning to lies circulated by Snowball. A few animals still felt faintly doubtful, but Squealer asked them shrewdly, “Are you certain that this is not something that you have dreamed, ⟦comrades⟧? Have you any record of such a resolution?", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "assure", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈʃʊə/", "mean": "장담하다, 확언하여 안심시키다", "ctx": "Afterwards Squealer made a round of the farm and set the animals’ minds at rest. He ⟦assured⟧ them that the resolution against engaging in trade and using money had never been passed, or even suggested. It was pure imagination, probably traceable in the beginning to lies circulated by Snowball.", "marked": true, "note": "상대가 의심을 거두도록 '틀림없다'고 확언함을 뜻한다. He assured them that the resolution ... had never been passed(그는 그 결의가 통과된 적이 없다고 확언했다)에서, 안심시킨다는 행위가 곧 거짓을 사실인 양 못 박는 일이 된다. 바로 앞의 set the animals' minds at rest(마음을 가라앉히다)와 짝을 이룬다.", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "circulate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈsɜːkjəleɪt/", "mean": "(소문·정보를) 퍼뜨리다, 나돌게 하다", "ctx": "Afterwards Squealer made a round of the farm and set the animals’ minds at rest. He assured them that the resolution against engaging in trade and using money had never been passed, or even suggested. It was pure imagination, probably traceable in the beginning to lies ⟦circulated⟧ by Snowball.", "marked": true, "note": "circle(원)에서 나온 말로, 무언가가 여기저기 돌아다니게 함을 뜻한다. lies circulated by Snowball(Snowball이 퍼뜨린 거짓말)에서, 동물들의 기억이 사실은 자리에 없는 적이 퍼뜨린 거짓에서 비롯되었다고 몰아간다. 수동태로 쓰여, 거짓의 출처를 한 인물에게 떠넘기는 데 쓰인다.", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "shrewdly", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ʃruːdli/", "mean": "약삭빠르게, 영악하게, 빈틈없이", "ctx": "It was pure imagination, probably traceable in the beginning to lies circulated by Snowball. A few animals still felt faintly doubtful, but Squealer asked them ⟦shrewdly⟧, “Are you certain that this is not something that you have dreamed, comrades? Have you any record of such a resolution?", "marked": true, "note": "상황을 빠르게 읽고 제 잇속에 맞게 영리하게 행동하는 모양을 뜻한다. 긍정적 '현명함'보다 계산적 교활함의 결이 강하다. Squealer asked them shrewdly(Squealer는 약삭빠르게 물었다)에서, 이어지는 물음들이 진실을 찾기 위함이 아니라 상대를 몰아붙이기 위한 계산된 것임을 미리 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "doubtful", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈdaʊtfl/", "mean": "미심쩍어하는, 확신이 안 서는", "ctx": "It was pure imagination, probably traceable in the beginning to lies circulated by Snowball. A few animals still felt faintly ⟦doubtful⟧, but Squealer asked them shrewdly, “Are you certain that this is not something that you have dreamed, comrades? Have you any record of such a resolution?", "marked": true, "note": "무언가를 온전히 믿지 못하고 의심을 품은 상태를 뜻한다. A few animals still felt faintly doubtful(몇몇 동물은 여전히 어렴풋이 미심쩍어했다)에서, 앞의 faintly(어렴풋이)와 어울려, 저항이 또렷한 확신이 아니라 희미하게 남은 의심에 불과함을 드러낸다. 흐릿한 의심은 약삭빠른 물음 앞에서 쉽게 꺾인다.", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "record", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈrekɔːd/", "mean": "기록, 문서로 남긴 증거", "ctx": "It was pure imagination, probably traceable in the beginning to lies circulated by Snowball. A few animals still felt faintly doubtful, but Squealer asked them shrewdly, “Are you certain that this is not something that you have dreamed, comrades? Have you any ⟦record⟧ of such a resolution?", "marked": true, "note": "나중에 확인할 수 있도록 글이나 문서로 남긴 것을 뜻한다(동사일 때는 강세가 뒤로 가 re-CORD '기록하다'). Have you any record of such a resolution?(그런 결의의 기록이 있느냐?)에서, 기억이 아니라 '문서'를 진실의 잣대로 들이댄다. 기록을 쥔 쪽이 무엇을 진실로 삼을지 정하는 자리다.", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "mistaken", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/mɪˈsteɪkən/", "mean": "잘못 안, 착각한", "ctx": "Have you any record of such a resolution? Is it written down anywhere?” And since it was certainly true that nothing of the kind existed in writing, the animals were satisfied that they had been ⟦mistaken⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "사실을 잘못 알거나 오해한 상태를 뜻한다. the animals were satisfied that they had been mistaken(동물들은 자신들이 착각했다고 받아들이며 안심했다)에서, 동물들은 끝내 제 기억이 아니라 자신의 '착각'을 믿기로 한다. 진실보다 안심을 택한 이 결말이, 기억 조작이 완성되는 순간이다.", "sid": "c6s015"}, {"word": "commissions", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/kəˈmɪʃənz/", "mean": "수수료, 중개료", "ctx": "Whymper visited the farm as had been arranged. He was a sly-looking little man with side whiskers, a solicitor in a very small way of business, but sharp enough to have realised earlier than anyone else that Animal Farm would need a broker and that the ⟦commissions⟧ would be worth having.", "marked": true, "note": "여기서는 ‘위원회’가 아니라 중개인(broker)이 거래를 성사시키고 받는 보수. Whymper가 노린 이익.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "sly", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/slaɪ/", "mean": "교활한, 음흉한, 속을 알 수 없는", "ctx": "Whymper visited the farm as had been arranged. He was a ⟦sly⟧-looking little man with side whiskers, a solicitor in a very small way of business, but sharp enough to have realised earlier than anyone else that Animal Farm would need a broker and that the commissions would be worth having.", "marked": true, "note": "속내를 숨기고 남을 슬그머니 이용하려는 교활함을 뜻한다. a sly-looking little man(교활해 보이는 자그마한 사내)에서, 겉모습 묘사 하나로 Whymper의 성격을 미리 일러 준다. 영문학에서 인물의 외양은 흔히 그 됨됨이를 비추는 거울로 쓰인다.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "side whiskers", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/saɪd ˈwɪskəz/", "mean": "구레나룻 (뺨 양옆으로 기른 수염)", "ctx": "Whymper visited the farm as had been arranged. He was a sly-looking little man with ⟦side whiskers⟧, a solicitor in a very small way of business, but sharp enough to have realised earlier than anyone else that Animal Farm would need a broker and that the commissions would be worth having.", "marked": true, "note": "귀밑에서 뺨을 따라 기른 수염을 뜻한다. 19세기 영국 신사·사무원의 전형적 차림으로, a sly-looking little man with side whiskers(구레나룻을 기른 교활해 보이는 사내)에서, 한 시대의 인간 유형을 한눈에 떠올리게 하는 시각적 단서다.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "broker", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbrəʊkə/", "mean": "중개인, 거간꾼", "ctx": "Whymper visited the farm as had been arranged. He was a sly-looking little man with side whiskers, a solicitor in a very small way of business, but sharp enough to have realised earlier than anyone else that Animal Farm would need a ⟦broker⟧ and that the commissions would be worth having.", "marked": true, "note": "사고파는 두 편 사이에서 거래를 붙여 주고 그 대가를 받는 사람을 뜻한다. Animal Farm would need a broker(동물 농장은 중개인이 필요하리라)에서, 바깥 세계와 직접 닿지 않으려는 농장에 거래를 대신 성사시킬 사람이 있어야 함을 가리킨다. 그 자리를 Whymper가 차지한다.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "commission", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/kəˈmɪʃn/", "mean": "(중개) 수수료, 구전", "ctx": "Whymper visited the farm as had been arranged. He was a sly-looking little man with side whiskers, a solicitor in a very small way of business, but sharp enough to have realised earlier than anyone else that Animal Farm would need a broker and that the ⟦commissions⟧ would be worth having.", "marked": true, "note": "거래를 성사시킨 대가로 중개인이 받는 몫을 뜻한다(다른 맥락에서는 '위원회·임무'의 뜻도 있다). the commissions would be worth having(그 수수료는 챙길 만하리라)에서, Whymper가 이 거래에서 무엇을 노리는지가 드러난다. 그의 동기는 이념이 아니라 잇속이다.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "sharp", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ʃɑːp/", "mean": "약삭빠른, 기민한, 이재에 밝은", "ctx": "Whymper visited the farm as had been arranged. He was a sly-looking little man with side whiskers, a solicitor in a very small way of business, but ⟦sharp⟧ enough to have realised earlier than anyone else that Animal Farm would need a broker and that the commissions would be worth having.", "marked": true, "note": "'날카로운'이 본뜻이나, 사람에게 쓰이면 잇속과 기회를 빠르게 알아채는 영민함을 뜻한다. sharp enough to have realised earlier than anyone else(누구보다 먼저 알아챌 만큼 약삭빠른)에서, 자그마하고 보잘것없어 보이는 사내가 실은 돈 냄새를 가장 먼저 맡는 자임을 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "dread", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/dred/", "mean": "(막연한) 두려움, 꺼림칙함", "ctx": "The animals watched his coming and going with a kind of ⟦dread⟧, and avoided him as much as possible.", "marked": true, "note": "앞일을 떠올릴 때 솟는 깊은 불안과 두려움을 뜻한다. watched his coming and going with a kind of dread(일종의 두려움을 품고 그의 드나듦을 지켜보았다)에서, 동물들이 이 인간 방문객을 본능적으로 꺼리면서도 막지는 못함을 드러낸다. a kind of(일종의)가 그 감정의 흐릿함을 더한다.", "sid": "c6s016"}, {"word": "on all fours", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɒn ɔːl ˈfɔːz/", "mean": "네 발로 (엎드린 자세로)", "ctx": "Nevertheless, the sight of Napoleon, ⟦on all fours⟧, delivering orders to Whymper, who stood on two legs, roused their pride and partly reconciled them to the new arrangement. Their relations with the human race were now not quite the same as they had been before.", "marked": true, "note": "두 손과 두 발을 모두 땅에 댄 자세, 곧 동물이 네 다리로 선 모습을 뜻한다. Napoleon, on all fours, delivering orders to Whymper, who stood on two legs(네 발로 선 채 두 발로 선 Whymper에게 명령하는 Napoleon)에서, 네 발(동물)과 두 발(인간)의 자세 대비가 이 장면의 핵심을 이룬다.", "sid": "c6s017"}, {"word": "rouse", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/raʊz/", "mean": "(감정을) 불러일으키다, 분기시키다", "ctx": "Nevertheless, the sight of Napoleon, on all fours, delivering orders to Whymper, who stood on two legs, ⟦roused⟧ their pride and partly reconciled them to the new arrangement. Their relations with the human race were now not quite the same as they had been before.", "marked": true, "note": "잠든 감정이나 기운을 흔들어 깨우거나 솟구치게 함을 뜻한다. roused their pride(그들의 자긍심을 불러일으켰다)에서, 이성적 판단이 아니라 자긍심이라는 감정이 솟구쳐 동물들이 새 체제를 받아들이게 됨을 가리킨다. 동의가 머리가 아니라 가슴에서 끌어내진다.", "sid": "c6s017"}, {"word": "reconcile", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈrekənsaɪl/", "mean": "(마지못해) 받아들이게 하다, 화해시키다", "ctx": "Nevertheless, the sight of Napoleon, on all fours, delivering orders to Whymper, who stood on two legs, roused their pride and partly ⟦reconciled⟧ them to the new arrangement. Their relations with the human race were now not quite the same as they had been before.", "marked": true, "note": "불편하거나 내키지 않는 일을 받아들이고 적응하게 만듦을 뜻한다(reconcile A to B: A가 B를 받아들이게 하다). partly reconciled them to the new arrangement(그들이 새 합의를 부분적으로 받아들이게 했다)에서, 거래라는 꺼림칙한 타협을 동물들이 마지못해 수긍하게 됨을 가리킨다. partly(부분적으로)가 그 수긍이 온전치 않음을 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s017"}, {"word": "prosper", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈprɒspə/", "mean": "번영하다, 번창하다", "ctx": "Their relations with the human race were now not quite the same as they had been before. The human beings did not hate Animal Farm any less now that it was ⟦prospering⟧; indeed, they hated it more than ever.", "marked": true, "note": "살림이나 사업이 잘되어 풍요로워짐을 뜻한다. now that it was prospering(이제 농장이 번영하고 있으므로)에서, 농장이 잘되고 있다는 사실이 인간들의 증오를 줄이기는커녕 오히려 키운다는 역설의 전제가 된다. 성공이 적의를 누그러뜨리지 않고 부추긴다.", "sid": "c6s017"}, {"word": "not ... any less", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/nɒt ˈeni les/", "mean": "조금도 덜 ~하지 않다", "ctx": "Nevertheless, the sight of Napoleon, on all fours, delivering orders to Whymper, who stood on two legs, roused their pride and partly reconciled them to the new arrangement. Their relations with the human race were now ⟦not⟧ quite the same as they had been before.", "marked": true, "note": "'조금도 줄지 않았다'는 뜻으로, 부정을 통해 도리어 그 정도가 여전함을 강조한다. did not hate Animal Farm any less now that it was prospering(번영한다고 해서 미움이 조금도 줄지 않았다)에서, 절제된 부정으로 적의가 그대로임을 말한 뒤, 곧이어 더 강한 표현으로 넘어간다.", "sid": "c6s017"}, {"word": "indeed", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ɪnˈdiːd/", "mean": "실로, (앞말을 받아) 게다가 더욱", "ctx": "Their relations with the human race were now not quite the same as they had been before. The human beings did not hate Animal Farm any less now that it was prospering; ⟦indeed⟧, they hated it more than ever.", "marked": true, "note": "앞서 한 말을 받아 한 단계 더 강한 진술로 밀어 올릴 때 쓴다. indeed, they hated it more than ever(실로, 그 어느 때보다 더 미워했다)에서, '조금도 줄지 않았다'는 절제된 부정을 '그 어느 때보다 더'라는 직접적 단언으로 끌어올린다. 표현의 수위가 한 칸 더 올라간다.", "sid": "c6s017"}, {"word": "article of faith", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ˈɑːtɪkl əv feɪθ/", "mean": "(의심 없이 믿는) 신조, 굳은 믿음", "ctx": "Every human being held it as an ⟦article of faith⟧ that the farm would go bankrupt sooner or later, and, above all, that the windmill would be a failure.", "marked": true, "note": "본디 종교의 '신앙 조항'을 뜻하는 말로, 증거를 따지지 않고 당연히 옳다고 믿는 신념을 가리킨다. held it as an article of faith that the farm would go bankrupt(농장이 파산하리라는 것을 신조처럼 믿었다)에서, 인간들의 확신이 사실이 아니라 신앙에 가깝다는 점, 곧 바라기 때문에 믿는 것임을 꼬집는다.", "sid": "c6s018"}, {"word": "bankrupt", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈbæŋkrʌpt/", "mean": "파산한, 거덜 난", "ctx": "Every human being held it as an article of faith that the farm would go ⟦bankrupt⟧ sooner or later, and, above all, that the windmill would be a failure.", "marked": true, "note": "빚을 갚지 못해 살림이나 사업이 망함을 뜻한다. the farm would go bankrupt sooner or later(농장이 머잖아 파산하리라)에서, 인간들이 농장의 운영 방식 자체가 지속될 수 없다고 믿고(또 바라고) 있음을 가리킨다. go bankrupt는 '파산하다'라는 굳은 표현이다.", "sid": "c6s018"}, {"word": "above all", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/əˈbʌv ɔːl/", "mean": "무엇보다도, 특히", "ctx": "Every human being held it as an article of faith that the farm would go bankrupt sooner or later, and, ⟦above all⟧, that the windmill would be a failure.", "marked": true, "note": "여러 가지 가운데 하나를 가장 앞세워 강조할 때 쓴다. and, above all, that the windmill would be a failure(그리고 무엇보다도, 풍차가 실패하리라는 것)에서, 인간들의 여러 바람 가운데 풍차의 실패를 으뜸으로 꼽는다. 풍차가 곧 혁명의 성패를 가르는 상징임을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s018"}, {"word": "public-house", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈpʌblɪk haʊs/", "mean": "(영국의) 선술집, 펍(pub)", "ctx": "They would meet in the ⟦public-houses⟧ and prove to one another by means of diagrams that the windmill was bound to fall down, or that if it did stand up, then that it would never work.", "marked": true, "note": "영국에서 술과 음식을 파는 동네 사교 장소로, 흔히 'pub'으로 줄여 부른다. They would meet in the public-houses(그들은 선술집에서 모이곤 했다)에서, 인간들의 '논증'이 학문의 자리가 아니라 술자리에서 이뤄짐을 가리켜, 그 진지함을 은근히 깎아내린다.", "sid": "c6s018"}, {"word": "by means of", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/baɪ ˈmiːnz əv/", "mean": "~을 수단으로 하여, ~을 써서", "ctx": "They would meet in the public-houses and prove to one another ⟦by means of⟧ diagrams that the windmill was bound to fall down, or that if it did stand up, then that it would never work.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 일을 이루는 도구나 방법을 가리키는 격식 표현이다. prove to one another by means of diagrams(도표를 써서 서로에게 증명하다)에서, 도표라는 그럴듯한 수단을 동원해 결론을 '증명'하려는 모습을 그린다. 그러나 수단이 그럴듯할수록, 결론이 미리 정해져 있다는 풍자는 더 날카로워진다.", "sid": "c6s018"}, {"word": "be bound to", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/biː baʊnd tuː/", "mean": "반드시 ~하게 마련이다, 틀림없이 ~할 것이다", "ctx": "Every human being held it as an article of faith that the farm would go bankrupt sooner or later, and, above all, that the windmill would be a failure. They would meet in the public-houses and prove to one another by means of diagrams that the windmill was bound to fall down, or that if it did stand…", "marked": false, "note": "필연이나 확신을 담아 어떤 일이 반드시 일어나리라고 말할 때 쓴다. the windmill was bound to fall down(풍차는 반드시 무너지게 마련이었다)에서, 인간들이 풍차의 붕괴를 한 치의 의심도 없는 필연으로 단정함을 드러낸다. 바라는 바를 필연으로 못 박는, 동기에 휘둘린 확신이다.", "sid": "c6s018"}, {"word": "against one's will", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/əˈɡenst wʌnz wɪl/", "mean": "본의 아니게, 마음과는 달리", "ctx": "And yet, ⟦against⟧ their will, they had developed a certain respect for the efficiency with which the animals were managing their own affairs. One symptom of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name and ceased to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "스스로 원하지 않는데도 어쩔 수 없이 그렇게 됨을 뜻한다. against their will, they had developed a certain respect(본의 아니게 그들은 어떤 존중을 품게 되었다)에서, 미워하면서도 인정하지 않을 수 없는 모순된 마음을 가리킨다. 적의와 존중이 한 가슴 안에서 부딪치는 자리다.", "sid": "c6s019"}, {"word": "efficiency", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ɪˈfɪʃnsi/", "mean": "효율, 능률 (적은 들임으로 큰 성과를 냄)", "ctx": "And yet, against their will, they had developed a certain respect for the ⟦efficiency⟧ with which the animals were managing their own affairs. One symptom of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name and ceased to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "낭비 없이 일을 잘 처리해 내는 능력을 뜻한다. the efficiency with which the animals were managing their own affairs(동물들이 제 일을 꾸려 가는 효율)에서, 인간들이 마지못해 인정한 것이 바로 이 운영의 능률임을 가리킨다. 미움의 대상이 도리어 잘 굴러간다는 사실이 적의를 더 곤혹스럽게 한다.", "sid": "c6s019"}, {"word": "symptom", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsɪmptəm/", "mean": "징후, 조짐 (속의 변화가 겉으로 드러난 표시)", "ctx": "And yet, against their will, they had developed a certain respect for the efficiency with which the animals were managing their own affairs. One ⟦symptom⟧ of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name and ceased to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "본디 병의 '증상'을 뜻하나, 널리 어떤 변화가 겉으로 드러난 표시를 가리킨다. One symptom of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name(이것의 한 징후는 그들이 농장을 제 이름으로 부르기 시작했다는 것)에서, 마음속 존중이 겉으로 새어 나온 표시로 '호칭의 변화'를 든다.", "sid": "c6s019"}, {"word": "cease", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/siːs/", "mean": "그만두다, 멈추다 (격식체)", "ctx": "And yet, against their will, they had developed a certain respect for the efficiency with which the animals were managing their own affairs. One symptom of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name and ⟦ceased⟧ to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "하던 일을 그치거나 어떤 상태가 끝남을 뜻하는 격식어다(stop보다 무게 있는 표현). ceased to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm(그것이 Manor Farm으로 불린다고 꾸미기를 그만두었다)에서, 옛 이름을 고집하던 척을 더는 하지 않게 됨을 가리킨다. 그만둔 것이 곧 인정의 시작이다.", "sid": "c6s019"}, {"word": "championship", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtʃæmpiənʃɪp/", "mean": "옹호, 지지 (어떤 사람·대의를 편들어 줌)", "ctx": "One symptom of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name and ceased to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm. They had also dropped their ⟦championship⟧ of Jones, who had given up hope of getting his farm back and gone to live in another part of the county.", "marked": true, "note": "흔히 '우승'으로 알려졌으나, 여기서는 champion(편들다·옹호하다)의 명사형으로 '어떤 이나 대의를 적극 지지함'을 뜻한다. dropped their championship of Jones(Jones에 대한 옹호를 거두었다)에서, 인간들이 더는 Jones를 편들지 않게 됨을 가리킨다. 같은 단어의 덜 익은 뜻을 익혀 둘 자리다.", "sid": "c6s019"}, {"word": "give up hope", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɡɪv ʌp həʊp/", "mean": "희망을 버리다, 단념하다", "ctx": "One symptom of this was that they had begun to call Animal Farm by its proper name and ceased to pretend that it was called the Manor Farm. They had also dropped their championship of Jones, who had ⟦given⟧ up hope of getting his farm back and gone to live in another part of the county.", "marked": true, "note": "바라던 일을 더는 기대하지 않고 포기함을 뜻한다. Jones, who had given up hope of getting his farm back(농장을 되찾을 희망을 버린 Jones)에서, 옛 주인이 복귀를 단념하고 무대 밖으로 사라짐을 가리킨다. 그의 퇴장은 복고의 가망이 끝났음을 조용히 알린다.", "sid": "c6s019"}, {"word": "as yet", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/æz ˈjet/", "mean": "아직까지는, 현재로서는", "ctx": "Except through Whymper, there was ⟦as yet⟧ no contact between Animal Farm and the outside world, but there were constant rumours that Napoleon was about to enter into a definite business agreement either with Mr. Pilkington of Foxwood or with Mr.", "marked": true, "note": "'지금 이 시점까지는 (아직)'이라는 뜻으로, 주로 부정문과 함께 쓰여 상황이 앞으로 바뀔 여지를 남긴다. there was as yet no contact between Animal Farm and the outside world(아직까지는 농장과 바깥 세계 사이에 접촉이 없었다)에서, '아직'이라는 한마디가 이 단절이 곧 깨질 수 있음을 은근히 일러 둔다.", "sid": "c6s020"}, {"word": "constant", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈkɒnstənt/", "mean": "끊임없는, 거듭되는", "ctx": "Except through Whymper, there was as yet no contact between Animal Farm and the outside world, but there were ⟦constant⟧ rumours that Napoleon was about to enter into a definite business agreement either with Mr. Pilkington of Foxwood or with Mr.", "marked": true, "note": "멈추지 않고 계속되거나 자꾸 되풀이됨을 뜻한다. there were constant rumours(끊임없는 소문이 돌았다)에서, 확실한 사실이 아니라 거듭 떠도는 소문이 동물들이 가진 정보의 전부임을 가리킨다. 소문이 끊이지 않는다는 것은, 정작 진실은 알 수 없다는 뜻이기도 하다.", "sid": "c6s020"}, {"word": "rumour", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈruːmə/", "mean": "소문, 풍문 (rumor의 영국식 철자)", "ctx": "Except through Whymper, there was as yet no contact between Animal Farm and the outside world, but there were constant ⟦rumours⟧ that Napoleon was about to enter into a definite business agreement either with Mr. Pilkington of Foxwood or with Mr.", "marked": true, "note": "사실인지 확인되지 않은 채 사람들 사이에 떠도는 이야기를 뜻한다. rumours that Napoleon was about to enter into a definite business agreement(Napoleon이 확실한 거래를 맺으려 한다는 소문)에서, 거래의 통로가 독점된 탓에 대중에게는 진상이 아니라 소문만이 닿음을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s020"}, {"word": "be about to", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/biː əˈbaʊt tuː/", "mean": "막 ~하려 하다, ~하기 직전이다", "ctx": "Except through Whymper, there was as yet no contact between Animal Farm and the outside world, but there were constant rumours that Napoleon was about to enter into a definite business agreement either with Mr. Pilkington of Foxwood or with Mr. Frederick of Pinchfield — but never, it was noticed, wi…", "marked": false, "note": "아주 가까운 미래에 어떤 일이 곧 일어나려 함을 뜻한다. was about to enter into a ... agreement(막 거래를 맺으려 하고 있었다)에서, 거래가 아직 성사되지는 않았으나 임박했다는 긴장을 만든다. 소문 속의 일이 '곧' 닥칠 듯한 느낌이 불확실성을 키운다.", "sid": "c6s020"}, {"word": "enter into", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ˈentər ˈɪntuː/", "mean": "(협정·계약을) 맺다, 체결하다", "ctx": "Except through Whymper, there was as yet no contact between Animal Farm and the outside world, but there were constant rumours that Napoleon was about to ⟦enter into⟧ a definite business agreement either with Mr. Pilkington of Foxwood or with Mr.", "marked": true, "note": "단순히 '들어가다'가 아니라, 협정·계약·논의 따위를 정식으로 맺거나 시작함을 뜻하는 구동사다. enter into a definite business agreement(확실한 거래 협정을 맺다)에서, 한때 인간과의 모든 거래를 금했던 농장이 이제 정식 협정을 논하는 데까지 이르렀음을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s020"}, {"word": "simultaneously", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˌsɪmlˈteɪniəsli/", "mean": "동시에, 한꺼번에", "ctx": "Pilkington of Foxwood or with Mr. Frederick of Pinchfield — but never, it was noticed, with both ⟦simultaneously⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "두 가지 일이 같은 때에 함께 일어남을 뜻한다. but never ... with both simultaneously(그러나 결코 양쪽과 동시에는 아니었다)에서, Napoleon이 두 이웃 농장주 가운데 어느 한쪽과만 거래하고 결코 둘 다와 동시에 손잡지 않는다는, 계산된 저울질을 드러내는 핵심어다.", "sid": "c6s020"}, {"word": "take up residence", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/teɪk ʌp ˈrezɪdəns/", "mean": "거처를 정하다, 들어가 살기 시작하다", "ctx": "It was absolutely necessary, he said, that the pigs, who were the brains of the farm, should have a quiet place to work in. It was also more suited to the dignity of the Leader (for of late he had ⟦taken⟧ to speaking of Napoleon under the title of “Leader”) to live in a house than in a mere sty.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 곳을 새 거처로 삼아 살기 시작함을 뜻하는 격식 표현이다. moved into the farmhouse and took up their residence there(농가로 옮겨 들어가 거기 거처를 정했다)에서, 돼지들이 옛 주인의 집을 차지하고 눌러앉음을 가리킨다. 격식 있는 표현이 도리어 그 행위의 자리바꿈을 묵직하게 부각한다.", "sid": "c6s021"}, {"word": "convince", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kənˈvɪns/", "mean": "납득시키다, 믿게 만들다", "ctx": "It was about this time that the pigs suddenly moved into the farmhouse and took up their residence there. Again the animals seemed to remember that a resolution against this had been passed in the early days, and again Squealer was able to ⟦convince⟧ them that this was not the case.", "marked": true, "note": "상대가 어떤 것을 사실이라고 믿게 만듦을 뜻한다. Squealer was able to convince them that this was not the case(Squealer는 그것이 사실이 아니라고 그들을 납득시킬 수 있었다)에서, '납득시켰다'는 말이 진실을 밝혔다는 뜻이 아니라, 거짓을 믿게 만드는 데 성공했다는 뜻으로 쓰임에 주의해야 한다.", "sid": "c6s021"}, {"word": "the brains of", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ðə breɪnz əv/", "mean": "~의 두뇌, 핵심 머리 (일을 꾸리는 지적 중심)", "ctx": "It was absolutely necessary, he said, that the pigs, who were ⟦the brains of⟧ the farm, should have a quiet place to work in. It was also more suited to the dignity of the Leader (for of late he had taken to speaking of Napoleon under the title of “Leader”) to live in a house than in a mere sty.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 집단에서 머리를 써서 일을 꾸려 가는 핵심 인물을 가리키는 표현이다. the pigs, who were the brains of the farm(농장의 두뇌인 돼지들)에서, 돼지들이 스스로를 농장의 지적 중심으로 규정함을 보여 준다. 이 자기 규정이 곧 특권을 정당화하는 논리가 된다.", "sid": "c6s021"}, {"word": "dignity", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdɪɡnəti/", "mean": "위엄, 품격, 지위에 걸맞은 격", "ctx": "It was absolutely necessary, he said, that the pigs, who were the brains of the farm, should have a quiet place to work in. It was also more suited to the ⟦dignity⟧ of the Leader (for of late he had taken to speaking of Napoleon under the title of “Leader”) to live in a house than in a mere sty.", "marked": true, "note": "함부로 대할 수 없는 무게나 지위에 걸맞은 격조를 뜻한다. more suited to the dignity of the Leader(지도자의 위엄에 더 어울리는)에서, 좋은 거처가 '필요'가 아니라 '위엄'의 문제로 제시된다. 평등한 동지 사이에 '위엄'이라는 잣대가 끼어드는 순간, 위계가 슬그머니 정당화된다.", "sid": "c6s021"}, {"word": "title", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtaɪtl/", "mean": "칭호, 직함 (이름 앞뒤에 붙이는 격식 호칭)", "ctx": "It was absolutely necessary, he said, that the pigs, who were the brains of the farm, should have a quiet place to work in. It was also more suited to the dignity of the Leader (for of late he had taken to speaking of Napoleon under the ⟦title⟧ of “Leader”) to live in a house than in a mere sty.", "marked": true, "note": "지위나 신분을 나타내기 위해 이름에 붙이는 호칭을 뜻한다. speaking of Napoleon under the title of \"Leader\"(Napoleon을 '지도자'라는 칭호로 부르며)에서, 한낱 동지였던 이름에 특별한 칭호가 붙기 시작함을 가리킨다. 칭호의 부여는 개인숭배가 언어에 새겨지는 첫 표지다.", "sid": "c6s021"}, {"word": "sty", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/staɪ/", "mean": "돼지우리", "ctx": "It was absolutely necessary, he said, that the pigs, who were the brains of the farm, should have a quiet place to work in. It was also more suited to the dignity of the Leader (for of late he had taken to speaking of Napoleon under the title of “Leader”) to live in a house than in a mere ⟦sty⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "돼지를 가두어 기르는 우리를 뜻한다. to live in a house than in a mere sty(한낱 돼지우리보다 집에서 사는 것)에서, mere(한낱)와 함께 쓰여 돼지우리를 낮잡고 집을 격상한다. 본디 돼지가 머물 곳을 스스로 '한낱'이라 부르는 데서, 돼지들이 이미 다른 동물과 자신을 가르고 있음이 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s021"}, {"word": "inscribed", "pos": "v. (past part.)", "pron": "/ɪnˈskraɪbd/", "mean": "(글자를) 새겼다", "ctx": "Boxer passed it off as usual with “Napoleon is always right!”, but Clover, who thought she remembered a definite ruling against beds, went to the end of the barn and tried to puzzle out the Seven Commandments which were ⟦inscribed⟧ there.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s022", "base": "inscribe — (글자를) 새기다"}, {"word": "disturbed", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/dɪˈstɜːbd/", "mean": "불안해하는, 마음이 어지러운", "ctx": "Nevertheless, some of the animals were ⟦disturbed⟧ when they heard that the pigs not only took their meals in the kitchen and used the drawing-room as a recreation room, but also slept in the beds.", "marked": true, "note": "평온하던 마음이 흔들려 동요하고 걱정스러운 상태를 뜻한다. some of the animals were disturbed when they heard ...(몇몇 동물은 ~을 듣고 동요했다)에서, 돼지들의 특권 소식에 일부 동물이 불안을 느낌을 가리킨다. all이 아니라 some(몇몇)이라는 점이, 그 동요가 아직 일부에 그침을 일러 둔다.", "sid": "c6s022"}, {"word": "not only ... but also", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/nɒt ˈəʊnli bʌt ˈɔːlsəʊ/", "mean": "~뿐만 아니라 …도", "ctx": "Nevertheless, some of the animals were disturbed when they heard that the pigs ⟦not⟧ only took their meals in the kitchen and used the drawing-room as a recreation room, but also slept in the beds.", "marked": true, "note": "두 가지를 잇되 뒤의 것에 무게를 싣는 상관구문이다. not only took their meals in the kitchen ... but also slept in the beds(부엌에서 식사할 뿐 아니라 침대에서 잠까지 잤다)에서, 여러 특권을 차례로 늘어놓다가 'but also' 뒤에 가장 문제적인 행위(침대 취침)를 두어 절정에 놓는다.", "sid": "c6s022"}, {"word": "drawing-room", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdrɔːɪŋ ruːm/", "mean": "응접실 (손님을 맞는 격식 있는 방)", "ctx": "Nevertheless, some of the animals were disturbed when they heard that the pigs not only took their meals in the kitchen and used the ⟦drawing-room⟧ as a recreation room, but also slept in the beds.", "marked": true, "note": "draw(물러나다)에서 나온 말로, 본디 식사 뒤 손님이 물러나 쉬던 격식 있는 거실을 뜻한다. used the drawing-room as a recreation room(응접실을 오락실로 썼다)에서, 인간 상류층의 공간을 돼지들이 차지해 누림을 가리킨다. 인간의 격식 있는 방이 돼지들의 놀이방이 되는 데서 위계의 역전이 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s022"}, {"word": "pass off", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/pɑːs ɒf/", "mean": "대수롭지 않게 넘기다, 얼버무려 넘기다", "ctx": "Boxer ⟦passed⟧ it off as usual with “Napoleon is always right!”, but Clover, who thought she remembered a definite ruling against beds, went to the end of the barn and tried to puzzle out the Seven Commandments which were inscribed there.", "marked": true, "note": "문제 될 만한 일을 심각하게 따지지 않고 가볍게 넘겨 버림을 뜻한다. Boxer passed it off as usual with \"Napoleon is always right!\"(Boxer는 여느 때처럼 \"Napoleon은 늘 옳다!\"로 대수롭지 않게 넘겼다)에서, Boxer가 의심이 들 만한 상황을 구호 하나로 덮어 버림을 가리킨다. 따지기를 그만두는 것이 곧 그의 충성 방식이다.", "sid": "c6s022"}, {"word": "ruling", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈruːlɪŋ/", "mean": "(공식적인) 규정, 결정, 판결", "ctx": "Boxer passed it off as usual with “Napoleon is always right!”, but Clover, who thought she remembered a definite ⟦ruling⟧ against beds, went to the end of the barn and tried to puzzle out the Seven Commandments which were inscribed there.", "marked": true, "note": "권위 있는 쪽이 내린 공식적 결정이나 규정을 뜻한다. a definite ruling against beds(침대를 금하는 분명한 규정)에서, Clover가 침대에 관한 또렷한 규정이 있었다고 기억함을 가리킨다. 이 '규정'에 대한 기억이, 벽에 적힌 계명을 확인하러 가게 만드는 실마리가 된다.", "sid": "c6s022"}, {"word": "puzzle out", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ˈpʌzl aʊt/", "mean": "(애써) 알아내다, 풀어내다", "ctx": "Boxer passed it off as usual with “Napoleon is always right!”, but Clover, who thought she remembered a definite ruling against beds, went to the end of the barn and tried to ⟦puzzle out⟧ the Seven Commandments which were inscribed there.", "marked": true, "note": "어렵거나 헷갈리는 것을 곰곰이 따져 풀어냄을 뜻한다. tried to puzzle out the Seven Commandments(일곱 계명을 애써 풀어내려 했다)에서, 글을 잘 읽지 못하는 Clover가 벽에 적힌 계명을 힘겹게 더듬어 읽으려 함을 가리킨다. '애써 풀어내다'라는 표현이 그 읽기가 결코 수월치 않음을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s022"}, {"word": "individual", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌɪndɪˈvɪdʒuəl/", "mean": "낱낱의, 하나하나의, 개별의", "ctx": "Finding herself unable to read more than ⟦individual⟧ letters, she fetched Muriel.“Muriel,” she said, “read me the Fourth Commandment.", "marked": true, "note": "전체가 아니라 하나하나 따로 떨어진 것을 가리킨다. unable to read more than individual letters(낱낱의 글자 이상은 읽지 못하여)에서, Clover가 알파벳 한 자 한 자는 알아보아도 그것을 단어로 엮어 읽지는 못함을 가리킨다. 글자는 보되 뜻은 닿지 않는, 절반의 문해력이다.", "sid": "c6s023"}, {"word": "fetch", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/fetʃ/", "mean": "가서 데려오다, 가서 가져오다", "ctx": "Finding herself unable to read more than individual letters, she ⟦fetched⟧ Muriel.“Muriel,” she said, “read me the Fourth Commandment.", "marked": true, "note": "어딘가로 가서 사람이나 물건을 데리고/가지고 옴을 뜻한다(가는 동작과 오는 동작을 함께 담는다). she fetched Muriel(그녀는 Muriel을 데려왔다)에서, 스스로 읽지 못하는 Clover가 그나마 글을 더 아는 Muriel에게 의존할 수밖에 없음을 가리킨다.", "sid": "c6s023"}, {"word": "spell out", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/spel aʊt/", "mean": "한 자 한 자 읽어 내다, 또박또박 풀어 읽다", "ctx": "Does it not say something about never sleeping in a bed?”With some difficulty Muriel ⟦spelt⟧ it out.“It says, ‘No animal shall sleep in a bed with sheets,”’ she announced finally.Curiously enough, Clover had not remembered that the Fourth Commandment mentioned sheets; but as it was there on the wall, it must have done so.", "marked": true, "note": "글자를 하나하나 짚어 가며 힘겹게 읽거나, 뜻을 낱낱이 풀어 설명함을 뜻한다. With some difficulty Muriel spelt it out(Muriel은 다소 힘겹게 한 자 한 자 읽어 냈다)에서, Muriel조차 그 글을 수월히 읽지 못함을 드러낸다. 글을 가장 잘 안다는 이들마저 읽기가 버겁다는 사실이, 대중의 문해력이 얼마나 빈약한지를 보여 준다.", "sid": "c6s023"}, {"word": "commandment", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/kəˈmɑːndmənt/", "mean": "계명, (반드시 지켜야 할) 율법 조항", "ctx": "Finding herself unable to read more than individual letters, she fetched Muriel.“Muriel,” she said, “read me the Fourth ⟦Commandment⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "command(명령)에서 나온 말로, 종교의 '십계명'처럼 반드시 지켜야 할 신성한 규율을 뜻한다. read me the Fourth Commandment(제4계명을 읽어 다오)에서, 농장의 일곱 계명이 종교의 율법처럼 떠받들어지는 신성한 원칙임을 환기한다. 그 신성함 때문에, 계명의 변조는 곧 원칙의 배반이 된다.", "sid": "c6s023"}, {"word": "curiously enough", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ˈkjʊəriəsli ɪˈnʌf/", "mean": "이상하게도, 묘하게도", "ctx": "Does it not say something about never sleeping in a bed?”With some difficulty Muriel spelt it out.“It says, ‘No animal shall sleep in a bed with sheets,”’ she announced finally.⟦Curiously enough⟧, Clover had not remembered that the Fourth Commandment mentioned sheets; but as it was there on the wall, it must have done so.", "marked": true, "note": "뜻밖이거나 석연치 않은 일을 가리킬 때 문장 앞에 두는 표현이다. Curiously enough, Clover had not remembered that the Fourth Commandment mentioned sheets(이상하게도, Clover는 제4계명에 시트 이야기가 있던 것을 기억하지 못했다)에서, 서술자는 무언가 어긋났음을 이 한마디로만 슬쩍 짚고, 그 진상은 독자가 알아채도록 남겨 둔다.", "sid": "c6s023"}, {"word": "mention", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈmenʃn/", "mean": "언급하다, (말·글에) 담아 두다", "ctx": "Does it not say something about never sleeping in a bed?”With some difficulty Muriel spelt it out.“It says, ‘No animal shall sleep in a bed with sheets,”’ she announced finally.Curiously enough, Clover had not remembered that the Fourth Commandment ⟦mentioned⟧ sheets; but as it was there on the wall, it must have done so.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 것을 말이나 글에서 짧게 다룸을 뜻한다. the Fourth Commandment mentioned sheets(제4계명이 시트를 언급했다)에서, 계명에 '시트'라는 말이 들어 있다는 것을 가리킨다. 바로 이 'sheets'가, Clover의 기억에는 없으나 벽에는 적혀 있는, 어긋남의 한가운데에 놓인 단어다.", "sid": "c6s023"}, {"word": "attended by", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/əˈtendɪd baɪ/", "mean": "~을 거느린, ~을 대동한", "ctx": "And Squealer, who happened to be passing at this moment, ⟦attended by⟧ two or three dogs, was able to put the whole matter in its proper perspective.“You have heard then, comrades,” he said, “that we pigs now sleep in the beds of the farmhouse? And why not?", "marked": true, "note": "attend(시중들다·수행하다)의 수동으로, 누군가가 곁에서 수행하거나 호위함을 뜻한다. attended by two or three dogs(두세 마리 개를 거느린 채)에서, Squealer가 늘 개들을 데리고 나타남을 가리킨다. 말로 설득하기 전에, 곁의 폭력 장치가 먼저 분위기를 누른다.", "sid": "c6s024"}, {"word": "perspective", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/pəˈspektɪv/", "mean": "시각, 관점 (put in perspective: 제대로 보다)", "ctx": "And Squealer, who happened to be passing at this moment, attended by two or three dogs, was able to put the whole matter in its proper ⟦perspective⟧.“You have heard then, comrades,” he said, “that we pigs now sleep in the beds of the farmhouse? And why not?", "marked": true, "note": "사물을 바라보는 관점이나 균형 잡힌 시각을 뜻한다. put the whole matter in its proper perspective(그 일 전체를 올바른 시각으로 정리하다)에서, Squealer가 자기 해석을 '올바른 시각(proper perspective)'이라 칭함이 핵심이다. 진실을 밝히는 척하지만, 실은 자기에게 유리한 틀로 사실을 다시 짜 맞추는 것이다.", "sid": "c6s024"}, {"word": "repose", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/rɪˈpəʊz/", "mean": "휴식, 안식 (격식체)", "ctx": "We have removed the sheets from the farmhouse beds, and sleep between blankets. And very comfortable beds they are too! But not more comfortable than we need, I can tell you, comrades, with all the brainwork we have to do nowadays. You would not rob us of our ⟦repose⟧, would you, comrades?", "marked": true, "note": "편안한 쉼이나 안식을 뜻하는 격식어다(rest보다 우아한 어감). You would not rob us of our repose, would you?(설마 우리에게서 안식을 빼앗으려는 건 아니겠지요?)에서, 돼지들의 안락을 단순한 '잠'이 아니라 격조 있는 '안식'으로 높여 부른다. 어휘의 격상이 특권을 마땅한 권리처럼 들리게 한다.", "sid": "c6s024"}, {"word": "rob ... of", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/rɒb əv/", "mean": "~에게서 (~을) 빼앗다", "ctx": "We have removed the sheets from the farmhouse beds, and sleep between blankets. And very comfortable beds they are too! But not more comfortable than we need, I can tell you, comrades, with all the brainwork we have to do nowadays. You would not ⟦rob⟧ us of our repose, would you, comrades?", "marked": true, "note": "'rob 사람 of 사물' 꼴로, 누군가에게서 무언가를 강제로 앗아 감을 뜻한다. rob us of our repose(우리에게서 안식을 빼앗다)에서, Squealer는 돼지의 특권을 문제 삼는 일을 도리어 '빼앗음(rob)'이라는 가해의 언어로 뒤집는다. 누리는 자가 도리어 피해자처럼 말하는 전도가 일어난다.", "sid": "c6s024"}, {"word": "brainwork", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbreɪnwɜːk/", "mean": "두뇌 노동, 머리 쓰는 일", "ctx": "The rule was against sheets, which are a human invention. We have removed the sheets from the farmhouse beds, and sleep between blankets. And very comfortable beds they are too! But not more comfortable than we need, I can tell you, comrades, with all the ⟦brainwork⟧ we have to do nowadays.", "marked": true, "note": "몸이 아니라 머리를 써서 하는 일을 뜻한다. with all the brainwork we have to do nowadays(요즘 우리가 해야 하는 그 모든 두뇌 노동을 생각하면)에서, 돼지들이 자신을 '머리 쓰는 계급'으로 규정해 특권을 정당화한다. Boxer 같은 이의 고된 육체노동과 대비되며, 노동의 종류를 위계의 근거로 삼는다.", "sid": "c6s024"}, {"word": "surely", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈʃʊəli/", "mean": "분명히, 설마 (~겠지요)", "ctx": "he said, “that we pigs now sleep in the beds of the farmhouse? And why not? You did not suppose, ⟦surely⟧, that there was ever a ruling against beds? A bed merely means a place to sleep in. A pile of straw in a stall is a bed, properly regarded.", "marked": true, "note": "'분명히 그렇겠지'라며 상대의 동의를 미리 끌어들일 때 쓴다. Surely none of you wishes to see Jones back?(설마 여러분 가운데 Jones가 돌아오기를 바라는 이는 없겠지요?)에서, surely가 반론을 미리 봉쇄한다. '설마 ~는 아니겠지'라는 어법이, 다른 답을 입에 올리기 어렵게 만드는 압박으로 작동한다.", "sid": "c6s024"}, {"word": "reassure", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌriːəˈʃʊə/", "mean": "안심시키다, (걱정 말라고) 확언해 주다", "ctx": "The animals ⟦reassured⟧ him on this point immediately, and no more was said about the pigs sleeping in the farmhouse beds.", "marked": true, "note": "re(다시)+assure(확언하다)로, 불안해하는 상대를 거듭 다독여 안심시킴을 뜻한다. The animals reassured him on this point immediately(동물들은 즉시 이 점에 대해 그를 안심시켰다)에서, 주목할 점은 안심시키는 쪽이 동물들이고 안심받는 쪽이 Squealer라는 전도다. 위협에 떠밀린 피해자가 도리어 가해자를 다독이는 셈이다.", "sid": "c6s025"}, {"word": "immediately", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ɪˈmiːdiətli/", "mean": "즉시, 곧바로", "ctx": "The animals reassured him on this point ⟦immediately⟧, and no more was said about the pigs sleeping in the farmhouse beds.", "marked": true, "note": "조금의 지체도 없이 곧바로 일어남을 뜻한다. reassured him on this point immediately(즉시 그를 안심시켰다)에서, 동물들이 따져 보거나 망설이지 않고 곧바로 굴복함을 가리킨다. 그 즉각성이, 'Jones의 귀환'이라는 위협 앞에서 저항이 얼마나 무력하게 무너지는지를 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s025"}, {"word": "no more was said", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/nəʊ mɔː wəz sed/", "mean": "더는 (그 일에 대해) 말이 나오지 않았다", "ctx": "The animals reassured him on this point immediately, and ⟦no more was said⟧ about the pigs sleeping in the farmhouse beds.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 화제가 더 거론되지 않고 그대로 묻힘을 뜻하는 수동 표현이다. no more was said about the pigs sleeping in the farmhouse beds(돼지들의 침대 취침에 대해 더는 말이 나오지 않았다)에서, 문제 제기가 흐지부지 가라앉아 침묵 속에 덮임을 가리킨다. 행위자를 지운 수동이, 누가 입을 다물게 했는지를 흐린다.", "sid": "c6s025"}, {"word": "from now on", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/frəm naʊ ɒn/", "mean": "이제부터, 앞으로는", "ctx": "And when, some days afterwards, it was announced that ⟦from now on⟧ the pigs would get up an hour later in the mornings than the other animals, no complaint was made about that either.", "marked": true, "note": "지금 이 시점을 기준으로 앞으로 죽 그러함을 뜻한다. that from now on the pigs would get up an hour later(이제부터 돼지들은 한 시간 늦게 일어나리라는 것)에서, 한 번의 예외가 아니라 항구적인 새 규칙이 정해짐을 가리킨다. 특권이 일시적 양보가 아니라 굳어진 제도가 되는 순간이다.", "sid": "c6s025"}, {"word": "complaint", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/kəmˈpleɪnt/", "mean": "불평, 항의", "ctx": "And when, some days afterwards, it was announced that from now on the pigs would get up an hour later in the mornings than the other animals, no ⟦complaint⟧ was made about that either.", "marked": true, "note": "못마땅함이나 부당함을 드러내어 말하는 항의를 뜻한다. no complaint was made about that either(그것에 대해서도 아무 항의가 없었다)에서, 새 특권에 대해 이번에는 아예 문제 제기조차 없음을 가리킨다. 침대 때는 그래도 일부가 동요했으나, 이번엔 그조차 사라진다.", "sid": "c6s025"}, {"word": "either", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈaɪðə/", "mean": "(부정문에서) ~도 또한 (…않다)", "ctx": "And when, some days afterwards, it was announced that from now on the pigs would get up an hour later in the mornings than the other animals, no complaint was made about that ⟦either⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "부정문 끝에 붙어 '앞의 것과 마찬가지로 이것도 ~않다'는 뜻을 더한다. no complaint was made about that either(그것에 대해서도 또한 아무 항의가 없었다)에서, either가 이번 침묵을 앞선 침묵(침대 건)과 한 줄로 잇는다. 묵인이 한 번이 아니라 거듭됨을, 이 작은 부사 하나가 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s025"}, {"word": "none too", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/nʌn ˈtuː/", "mean": "별로 ~하지 않은, 그다지 ~지 못한", "ctx": "By the autumn the animals were tired but happy. They had had a hard year, and after the sale of part of the hay and corn, the stores of food for the winter were ⟦none too⟧ plentiful, but the windmill compensated for everything. It was almost half built now.", "marked": true, "note": "형용사·부사 앞에 붙어 '그다지 ~하지 않다'는 절제된 부정을 만든다. the stores of food for the winter were none too plentiful(겨울 식량 저장은 그다지 넉넉지 못했다)에서, '부족했다'고 곧장 말하는 대신 '넉넉지는 못했다'고 에둘러, 모자람을 담담히 인정한다. 결핍을 직설하지 않는 어조가 도리어 그 형편을 차분히 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s026"}, {"word": "compensate for", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ˈkɒmpenseɪt fɔː/", "mean": "~을 보상하다, 메우다, 상쇄하다", "ctx": "By the autumn the animals were tired but happy. They had had a hard year, and after the sale of part of the hay and corn, the stores of food for the winter were none too plentiful, but the windmill ⟦compensated⟧ for everything. It was almost half built now.", "marked": true, "note": "부족하거나 잃은 것을 다른 것으로 메우거나 상쇄함을 뜻한다. but the windmill compensated for everything(그러나 풍차가 모든 것을 보상했다)에서, 풍차라는 목표 하나가 식량 부족과 고된 노동을 모두 견딜 만하게 만든다. 거대한 상징이 눈앞의 결핍을 정당화하는 심리를 압축한 표현이다.", "sid": "c6s026"}, {"word": "worth while", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌwɜːθ ˈwaɪl/", "mean": "할 만한 가치가 있는 (오늘날 worthwhile)", "ctx": "It was almost half built now. After the harvest there was a stretch of clear dry weather, and the animals toiled harder than ever, thinking it well ⟦worth while⟧ to plod to and fro all day with blocks of stone if by doing so they could raise the walls another foot.", "marked": true, "note": "들인 시간과 노력이 아깝지 않을 만큼 가치 있음을 뜻한다(현대 철자는 worthwhile). thinking it well worth while to plod ... all day(온종일 터벅터벅 나르는 것이 충분히 할 만한 가치가 있다고 여기며)에서, 동물들이 그 고된 일을 스스로 보람 있다고 믿음을 가리킨다. 강제가 아니라 자발적 확신이라는 점이 중요하다.", "sid": "c6s026"}, {"word": "plod", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/plɒd/", "mean": "터벅터벅 걷다, 뚜벅뚜벅 꾸준히 해내다", "ctx": "It was almost half built now. After the harvest there was a stretch of clear dry weather, and the animals toiled harder than ever, thinking it well worth while to ⟦plod⟧ to and fro all day with blocks of stone if by doing so they could raise the walls another foot.", "marked": true, "note": "무거운 걸음으로 느리지만 꾸준히 나아감을 뜻한다. to plod to and fro all day with blocks of stone(온종일 돌덩이를 지고 이리저리 터벅터벅 나르는 것)에서, 화려하지 않은 묵묵한 노동의 고됨과 끈기를 동시에 담는다. Boxer로 대표되는 우직한 노동의 결을 그대로 비춘다.", "sid": "c6s026"}, {"word": "to and fro", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ˌtuː ən ˈfrəʊ/", "mean": "이리저리, 왔다 갔다", "ctx": "It was almost half built now. After the harvest there was a stretch of clear dry weather, and the animals toiled harder than ever, thinking it well worth while to plod ⟦to and fro⟧ all day with blocks of stone if by doing so they could raise the walls another foot.", "marked": true, "note": "같은 길을 오가며 되풀이해 움직임을 뜻하는 관용구다. to plod to and fro all day(온종일 이리저리 터벅터벅 오가다)에서, 돌을 나르느라 같은 길을 끝없이 왕복하는 단조롭고 고된 노동을 그린다. 반복의 리듬이 노동의 지루한 무게를 소리로도 전한다.", "sid": "c6s026"}, {"word": "spare moments", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/speə ˈməʊmənts/", "mean": "짬, 틈나는 시간, 여가", "ctx": "In their ⟦spare moments⟧ the animals would walk round and round the half-finished mill, admiring the strength and perpendicularity of its walls and marvelling that they should ever have been able to build anything so imposing.", "marked": true, "note": "spare(남는)와 moments(순간)가 합쳐져, 일하고 남은 짧은 여유 시간을 뜻한다. In their spare moments the animals would walk round and round(짬이 날 때면 동물들은 빙빙 돌며 거닐곤 했다)에서, 쉬어야 할 그 짬마저 동물들이 풍차 곁에서 보냄을 가리킨다. 쉬는 시간조차 풍차에 바쳐진다는 데서 그 몰입의 깊이가 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s027"}, {"word": "perpendicularity", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌpɜːpəndɪkjuˈlærəti/", "mean": "수직(임), 똑바로 곧추섬", "ctx": "In their spare moments the animals would walk round and round the half-finished mill, admiring the strength and ⟦perpendicularity⟧ of its walls and marvelling that they should ever have been able to build anything so imposing.", "marked": true, "note": "땅과 직각을 이루며 똑바로 서 있는 성질을 뜻하는 다소 딱딱한 명사다. admiring the strength and perpendicularity of its walls(벽의 견고함과 수직을 찬탄하며)에서, 동물들이 풍차 벽이 튼튼하고 똑바로 섰음을 자랑스레 바라봄을 가리킨다. 바로 그 '견고함'에 대한 믿음이, 곧 닥칠 붕괴와 대비되어 아이러니를 빚는다.", "sid": "c6s027"}, {"word": "marvel", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈmɑːvl/", "mean": "경탄하다, 놀라워하다", "ctx": "In their spare moments the animals would walk round and round the half-finished mill, admiring the strength and perpendicularity of its walls and ⟦marvelling⟧ that they should ever have been able to build anything so imposing.", "marked": true, "note": "믿기 어려울 만큼 놀랍고 대단한 일에 감탄함을 뜻한다. marvelling that they should ever have been able to build anything so imposing(자신들이 그토록 위풍당당한 것을 지을 수 있었다는 데 경탄하며)에서, 동물들이 제 손으로 이룬 성취에 스스로 놀라워함을 가리킨다. 그 벅찬 자부심이 이 장면의 정서를 채운다.", "sid": "c6s027"}, {"word": "imposing", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɪmˈpəʊzɪŋ/", "mean": "위풍당당한, 인상적인, 웅장한", "ctx": "In their spare moments the animals would walk round and round the half-finished mill, admiring the strength and perpendicularity of its walls and marvelling that they should ever have been able to build anything so ⟦imposing⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "크기나 위용으로 깊은 인상을 주어 보는 이를 압도함을 뜻한다. anything so imposing(그토록 위풍당당한 것)에서, 반쯤 선 풍차가 동물들에게 얼마나 웅장하게 비쳤는지를 드러낸다. 그 웅장함에 대한 자부심이 클수록, 그것이 무너질 때의 충격도 그만큼 커진다.", "sid": "c6s027"}, {"word": "enthusiastic", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɪnˌθjuːziˈæstɪk/", "mean": "열광적인, 열의에 찬", "ctx": "Only old Benjamin refused to grow ⟦enthusiastic⟧ about the windmill, though, as usual, he would utter nothing beyond the cryptic remark that donkeys live a long time.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 일에 큰 열의와 흥분을 느낌을 뜻한다. Only old Benjamin refused to grow enthusiastic(오직 늙은 Benjamin만은 열광하기를 거부했다)에서, 모두가 들뜬 가운데 홀로 그 열기에 휩쓸리지 않는 Benjamin을 도드라지게 한다. refuse to grow(되기를 거부하다)가 그것이 무지가 아니라 의식적 거리 두기임을 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s027"}, {"word": "cryptic", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈkrɪptɪk/", "mean": "수수께끼 같은, 아리송한, 뜻을 숨긴", "ctx": "Only old Benjamin refused to grow enthusiastic about the windmill, though, as usual, he would utter nothing beyond the ⟦cryptic⟧ remark that donkeys live a long time.", "marked": true, "note": "뜻이 분명히 드러나지 않아 헤아리기 어려운 말이나 글을 가리킨다. the cryptic remark that donkeys live a long time(당나귀는 오래 산다는 수수께끼 같은 말)에서, Benjamin이 속내를 다 드러내지 않고 아리송한 한마디만 흘림을 가리킨다. 그 모호함 속에, 길게 보아 다 안다는 냉소가 숨어 있다.", "sid": "c6s027"}, {"word": "raging", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈreɪdʒɪŋ/", "mean": "몰아치는, 맹렬한, 사납게 휘몰아치는", "ctx": "November came, with ⟦raging⟧ south-west winds. Building had to stop because it was now too wet to mix the cement. Finally there came a night when the gale was so violent that the farm buildings rocked on their foundations and several tiles were blown off the roof of the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "rage(격노하다·맹위를 떨치다)에서 나온 말로, 바람·불·바다 따위가 사납게 휘몰아침을 뜻한다. November came, with raging south-west winds(11월이 몰아치는 남서풍과 함께 왔다)에서, 자연이 분노하듯 거세게 일어남을 그린다. 마치 날씨에 감정이 실린 듯한 이 표현이, 다가올 재앙의 분위기를 미리 깐다.", "sid": "c6s028"}, {"word": "gale", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ɡeɪl/", "mean": "강풍, 돌풍 (세찬 바람)", "ctx": "November came, with raging south-west winds. Building had to stop because it was now too wet to mix the cement. Finally there came a night when the ⟦gale⟧ was so violent that the farm buildings rocked on their foundations and several tiles were blown off the roof of the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "건물을 흔들고 나무를 쓰러뜨릴 만큼 세찬 바람을 뜻한다(단순한 wind보다 훨씬 거세다). the gale was so violent that the farm buildings rocked(강풍이 너무 거세어 농장 건물들이 흔들렸다)에서, 그 위력이 토대까지 뒤흔들 정도임을 가리킨다. 풍차의 운명을 가를 자연의 힘이 이 한 단어에 응축된다.", "sid": "c6s028"}, {"word": "violent", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈvaɪələnt/", "mean": "격렬한, 사나운, (힘이) 맹렬한", "ctx": "November came, with raging south-west winds. Building had to stop because it was now too wet to mix the cement. Finally there came a night when the gale was so ⟦violent⟧ that the farm buildings rocked on their foundations and several tiles were blown off the roof of the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "사람의 폭력만이 아니라, 자연 현상이 거칠고 맹렬함을 뜻하기도 한다. the gale was so violent that ...(강풍이 너무 격렬해서 ~)에서, so ... that 구문과 맞물려 그 거셈이 어떤 결과를 낳았는지로 이어진다. violent라는 단어가 자연의 파괴력에 거의 의도적 폭력의 어감을 입힌다.", "sid": "c6s028"}, {"word": "rock", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/rɒk/", "mean": "뒤흔들다, 좌우로 크게 흔들다", "ctx": "November came, with raging south-west winds. Building had to stop because it was now too wet to mix the cement. Finally there came a night when the gale was so violent that the farm buildings ⟦rocked⟧ on their foundations and several tiles were blown off the roof of the barn.", "marked": true, "note": "명사 '바위'가 아니라 동사로 쓰여, 무언가를 크게 흔들어 댐을 뜻한다. the farm buildings rocked on their foundations(농장 건물들이 토대째 흔들렸다)에서, 바람이 건물을 그 밑바탕까지 뒤흔듦을 가리킨다. on their foundations(토대 위에서)가 더해져, 흔들림이 표면이 아니라 근본에 이르렀음을 강조한다.", "sid": "c6s028"}, {"word": "squawk", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/skwɔːk/", "mean": "(새가) 꽥꽥 울다, 깩깩거리다", "ctx": "Finally there came a night when the gale was so violent that the farm buildings rocked on their foundations and several tiles were blown off the roof of the barn. The hens woke up ⟦squawking⟧ with terror because they had all dreamed simultaneously of hearing a gun go off in the distance.", "marked": true, "note": "새가 놀라거나 겁에 질려 거칠게 울부짖는 소리를 뜻하는 의성어적 동사다. The hens woke up squawking with terror(암탉들이 공포에 질려 꽥꽥거리며 깨어났다)에서, 닭들이 악몽에 놀라 내지르는 날카로운 비명을 생생히 들려준다. 그 소리가 평온한 밤을 찢으며 불길한 분위기를 한층 돋운다.", "sid": "c6s028"}, {"word": "go off", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ɡəʊ ɒf/", "mean": "(총·폭탄이) 발사되다, 터지다", "ctx": "Finally there came a night when the gale was so violent that the farm buildings rocked on their foundations and several tiles were blown off the roof of the barn. The hens woke up squawking with terror because they had all dreamed simultaneously of hearing a gun ⟦go off⟧ in the distance.", "marked": true, "note": "총·폭탄 따위가 발사되거나 터짐을 뜻하는 구동사다(알람이 '울리다'의 뜻도 있다). hearing a gun go off in the distance(멀리서 총이 발사되는 소리를 듣는 것)에서, 암탉들이 꿈에서 들은 그 총소리를 가리킨다. 총소리라는 폭력의 환청이 다가올 파국의 불길한 전조로 작동한다.", "sid": "c6s028"}, {"word": "orchard", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈɔːtʃəd/", "mean": "과수원", "ctx": "In the morning the animals came out of their stalls to find that the flagstaff had been blown down and an elm tree at the foot of the ⟦orchard⟧ had been plucked up like a radish. They had just noticed this when a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "flagstaff", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈflæɡstɑːf/", "mean": "깃대 (깃발을 다는 기둥)", "ctx": "In the morning the animals came out of their stalls to find that the ⟦flagstaff⟧ had been blown down and an elm tree at the foot of the orchard had been plucked up like a radish. They had just noticed this when a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "깃발을 매다는 기둥을 뜻한다. the flagstaff had been blown down(깃대가 바람에 쓰러져 있었다)에서, 동물들이 일요일마다 녹색 깃발을 올리던 그 깃대가 폭풍에 넘어졌음을 가리킨다. 혁명의 상징이 걸리던 기둥이 쓰러진 모습이, 단순한 피해를 넘어 대의(大義) 자체에 가해진 타격처럼 읽히게 한다.", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "elm", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/elm/", "mean": "느릅나무 (크고 단단한 나무)", "ctx": "In the morning the animals came out of their stalls to find that the flagstaff had been blown down and an ⟦elm⟧ tree at the foot of the orchard had been plucked up like a radish. They had just noticed this when a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "크고 굵게 자라는 활엽수로, 뿌리가 깊고 단단하기로 이름난 나무다. an elm tree ... had been plucked up like a radish(느릅나무 한 그루가 무처럼 뽑혀 있었다)에서, 그 거대한 나무조차 바람에 통째로 뽑혔음을 보여 준다. 가장 굳건해야 할 것이 뿌리째 뽑힌 모습이, 폭풍의 위력을 한눈에 가늠하게 한다.", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "pluck up", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/plʌk ʌp/", "mean": "뽑아 올리다, 뿌리째 잡아 뽑다", "ctx": "In the morning the animals came out of their stalls to find that the flagstaff had been blown down and an elm tree at the foot of the orchard had been ⟦plucked⟧ up like a radish. They had just noticed this when a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "땅에 박힌 것을 잡아당겨 뿌리째 뽑아냄을 뜻한다(작은 풀이나 무를 뽑을 때 흔히 쓰는 말이다). an elm tree ... had been plucked up like a radish에서, 거대한 느릅나무를 마치 텃밭의 무 한 뿌리 뽑듯 뽑아냈다고 함으로써, 자연의 힘이 그 일을 얼마나 손쉽게 해치웠는지를 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "radish", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈrædɪʃ/", "mean": "무, 래디시 (텃밭의 작은 뿌리채소)", "ctx": "In the morning the animals came out of their stalls to find that the flagstaff had been blown down and an elm tree at the foot of the orchard had been plucked up like a ⟦radish⟧. They had just noticed this when a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "손가락 끝으로도 쑥 뽑히는 작은 뿌리채소다. plucked up like a radish(무처럼 뽑혀)라는 직유에서, 거대한 느릅나무와 자그마한 무의 극단적 크기 대비가 핵심이다. 엄청난 폭력을 텃밭의 사소한 동작으로 견줌으로써, 자연의 무심하고도 압도적인 힘을 역설적으로 더 크게 느끼게 한다.", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "despair", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/dɪˈspeə/", "mean": "절망, 희망이 사라진 상태", "ctx": "In the morning the animals came out of their stalls to find that the flagstaff had been blown down and an elm tree at the foot of the orchard had been plucked up like a radish. They had just noticed this when a cry of ⟦despair⟧ broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "모든 희망이 무너진 깊은 좌절을 뜻한다. a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat(절망의 비명이 모든 동물의 목구멍에서 터져 나왔다)에서, 1년 가까운 노고가 한순간에 무너진 충격을 담는다. 개개의 탄식이 아니라 'every animal'의 동시다발적 비명으로 그려져, 절망이 공동체 전체의 것임을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "in ruins", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ɪn ˈruːɪnz/", "mean": "폐허가 된, 완전히 무너진", "ctx": "They had just noticed this when a cry of despair broke from every animal’s throat. A terrible sight had met their eyes. The windmill was ⟦in ruins⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "건물이나 계획 따위가 완전히 무너져 잔해만 남은 상태를 뜻한다. The windmill was in ruins(풍차는 폐허가 되어 있었다)라는 단 네 단어의 짧은 문장이, 앞선 긴장의 고조를 한칼에 끊어 낸다. 군더더기 없는 이 짧음이 충격을 가장 날것 그대로 전한다.", "sid": "c6s029"}, {"word": "seldom", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈseldəm/", "mean": "거의 ~하지 않다. 드물게", "ctx": "With one accord they dashed down to the spot. Napoleon, who ⟦seldom⟧ moved out of a walk, raced ahead of them all. Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, levelled to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously scattered all around.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "with one accord", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/wɪð wʌn əˈkɔːd/", "mean": "일제히, 한마음으로 (모두가 동시에)", "ctx": "⟦With one accord⟧ they dashed down to the spot. Napoleon, who seldom moved out of a walk, raced ahead of them all. Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, levelled to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously scattered all around.", "marked": true, "note": "미리 의논하지 않았는데도 모두가 한꺼번에 같은 행동을 함을 뜻하는 관용구다. With one accord they dashed down to the spot(그들은 일제히 그 자리로 달려 내려갔다)에서, 절망에 빠진 동물들이 약속이라도 한 듯 한꺼번에 움직임을 그린다. 앞 장면의 '한 몸처럼 터진 비명'에 이어, 행동마저 한 덩어리로 묶인 집단의 모습을 강조한다.", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "dash", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/dæʃ/", "mean": "(다급히) 내달리다, 돌진하다", "ctx": "With one accord they ⟦dashed⟧ down to the spot. Napoleon, who seldom moved out of a walk, raced ahead of them all. Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, levelled to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously scattered all around.", "marked": true, "note": "급한 마음에 황급히 달려감을 뜻한다(run보다 다급함이 강하다). they dashed down to the spot(그들은 그 자리로 황급히 달려 내려갔다)에서, 충격을 확인하려는 동물들의 절박함을 담는다. 평소 느릿하던 무리가 일제히 내달리는 모습이, 사태의 비상함을 동작만으로 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "level", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈlevl/", "mean": "평평하게 무너뜨리다, 완전히 허물다", "ctx": "With one accord they dashed down to the spot. Napoleon, who seldom moved out of a walk, raced ahead of them all. Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, ⟦levelled⟧ to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously scattered all around.", "marked": true, "note": "건물 따위를 땅바닥과 같은 높이로 깡그리 허물어 버림을 뜻한다. levelled to its foundations(토대까지 깡그리 무너져)에서, 풍차가 일부가 아니라 밑바탕까지 완전히 무너졌음을 가리킨다. '평평하게 만든다'는 말의 어감이, 우뚝 솟았던 것이 흔적도 없이 바닥과 같아진 참담함을 강조한다.", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "laboriously", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ləˈbɔːriəsli/", "mean": "힘들여, 고되게, 애써 가며", "ctx": "With one accord they dashed down to the spot. Napoleon, who seldom moved out of a walk, raced ahead of them all. Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, levelled to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so ⟦laboriously⟧ scattered all around.", "marked": true, "note": "많은 노력과 수고를 들여 힘겹게 함을 뜻한다(labour=노동에서 나온 말이다). the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously(그토록 힘들여 깨고 날랐던 돌들)에서, 동물들이 풍차에 쏟은 고된 노동을 한 단어로 환기한다. 그 수고로움을 강조할수록, 사방에 흩어진 돌더미의 허무함이 더 크게 다가온다.", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "mournfully", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈmɔːnfəli/", "mean": "슬픔에 잠겨, 애도하듯", "ctx": "Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, levelled to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously scattered all around. Unable at first to speak, they stood gazing ⟦mournfully⟧ at the litter of fallen stone.", "marked": true, "note": "깊은 슬픔에 잠겨 무언가를 잃은 듯 애도함을 뜻한다(mourn=애도하다에서 나왔다). they stood gazing mournfully at the litter of fallen stone(그들은 무너진 돌더미를 슬픔에 잠겨 바라보며 서 있었다)에서, 말을 잃은 동물들의 정적인 비탄을 그린다. 마치 죽은 이를 애도하듯, 무너진 풍차를 바라보는 그 시선이 상실의 깊이를 전한다.", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "litter", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈlɪtə/", "mean": "어지러이 흩어진 것들, 잡동사니 더미", "ctx": "Yes, there it lay, the fruit of all their struggles, levelled to its foundations, the stones they had broken and carried so laboriously scattered all around. Unable at first to speak, they stood gazing mournfully at the ⟦litter⟧ of fallen stone.", "marked": true, "note": "여기저기 어지러이 널브러진 쓰레기·잔해를 뜻한다. the litter of fallen stone(무너져 흩어진 돌더미)에서, 우뚝 솟았던 풍차가 한낱 어수선한 돌 쓰레기로 전락했음을 가리킨다. 자부심의 결정체를 'litter(잡동사니)'라 부르는 데서, 영광이 폐기물로 추락한 낙차가 고스란히 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s030"}, {"word": "pace", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/peɪs/", "mean": "(초조하게) 왔다 갔다 거닐다", "ctx": "Napoleon ⟦paced⟧ to and fro in silence, occasionally snuffing at the ground. His tail had grown rigid and twitched sharply from side to side, a sign in him of intense mental activity. Suddenly he halted as though his mind were made up.", "marked": true, "note": "생각에 잠기거나 초조할 때 같은 자리를 오가며 걷는 모습을 뜻한다. Napoleon paced to and fro in silence(Napoleon은 말없이 이리저리 거닐었다)에서, 골똘히 무언가를 궁리하는 그의 내면을 동작으로 드러낸다. 슬픔에 잠긴 다른 동물들과 달리, 그만은 머릿속으로 계산을 굴리고 있음을 이 거닒이 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s031"}, {"word": "snuff", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/snʌf/", "mean": "코를 킁킁거리다, 냄새를 맡다", "ctx": "Napoleon paced to and fro in silence, occasionally ⟦snuffing⟧ at the ground. His tail had grown rigid and twitched sharply from side to side, a sign in him of intense mental activity. Suddenly he halted as though his mind were made up.", "marked": true, "note": "코로 냄새를 맡으려 킁킁거림을 뜻한다. occasionally snuffing at the ground(이따금 땅을 킁킁거리며)에서, 무언가 단서를 찾는 듯한 그의 몸짓을 그린다. 이 '냄새 맡기'는 곧 뒤에서 '발자국 냄새를 맡아' 범인을 지목하는 장면으로 이어지는 복선처럼 작동하여, 그가 이미 무언가를 꾸미고 있음을 넌지시 흘린다.", "sid": "c6s031"}, {"word": "rigid", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈrɪdʒɪd/", "mean": "뻣뻣한, 빳빳하게 굳은", "ctx": "Napoleon paced to and fro in silence, occasionally snuffing at the ground. His tail had grown ⟦rigid⟧ and twitched sharply from side to side, a sign in him of intense mental activity. Suddenly he halted as though his mind were made up.", "marked": true, "note": "유연하게 휘지 않고 빳빳하게 굳은 상태를 뜻한다. His tail had grown rigid(그의 꼬리가 빳빳하게 굳어 있었다)에서, 긴장과 집중으로 몸이 굳은 모습을 가리킨다. 부드럽게 흔들려야 할 꼬리가 굳어 버렸다는 데서, 겉으로 드러나지 않는 내면의 팽팽한 긴장이 몸으로 새어 나옴을 읽을 수 있다.", "sid": "c6s031"}, {"word": "twitch", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/twɪtʃ/", "mean": "씰룩거리다, 경련하듯 움찔거리다", "ctx": "Napoleon paced to and fro in silence, occasionally snuffing at the ground. His tail had grown rigid and ⟦twitched⟧ sharply from side to side, a sign in him of intense mental activity. Suddenly he halted as though his mind were made up.", "marked": true, "note": "근육이나 몸의 일부가 짧고 갑작스럽게 움찔거림을 뜻한다. twitched sharply from side to side(좌우로 날카롭게 씰룩였다)에서, 의지로 통제되지 않는 긴장의 신호를 그린다. 작가가 곧 'a sign of intense mental activity(격렬한 사고의 신호)'라고 풀어 주듯, 이 씰룩임은 그의 머릿속에서 무언가가 빠르게 돌아가고 있음을 몸 밖으로 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s031"}, {"word": "halt", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/hɔːlt/", "mean": "멈춰 서다, 딱 멈추다", "ctx": "Napoleon paced to and fro in silence, occasionally snuffing at the ground. His tail had grown rigid and twitched sharply from side to side, a sign in him of intense mental activity. Suddenly he ⟦halted⟧ as though his mind were made up.", "marked": true, "note": "움직이던 것이 갑자기 멈춰 섬을 뜻한다. Suddenly he halted as though his mind were made up(마치 결심이 선 듯 그는 갑자기 멈춰 섰다)에서, 이리저리 거닐던 동작이 한 점에 딱 멈추는 순간을 그린다. 끊임없던 거닒이 멈춘다는 것은 곧 궁리가 끝나 결론에 이르렀다는 신호이며, 다음 순간 터질 그의 말에 긴장을 싣는다.", "sid": "c6s031"}, {"word": "comrade", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪd/", "mean": "동지, 동무 (뜻을 같이하는 벗)", "ctx": "“⟦Comrades⟧,” he said quietly, “do you know who is responsible for this? Do you know the enemy who has come in the night and overthrown our windmill? SNOWBALL!” he suddenly roared in a voice of thunder.", "marked": true, "note": "뜻과 운명을 함께하는 동지를 부르는 말로, 혁명·운동의 어휘에서 평등한 연대를 강조할 때 쓰인다. “Comrades,” he said quietly(“동지들이여,” 그가 조용히 말했다)에서, Napoleon은 평등의 호칭으로 운을 뗀다. 그러나 곧 그 다정한 호칭이 무리를 한 방향으로 몰아가는 연설의 도입부였음이 드러나, 평등의 언어가 통제의 도구로 쓰이는 아이러니를 품는다.", "sid": "c6s032"}, {"word": "responsible", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/rɪˈspɒnsəbl/", "mean": "책임이 있는, ~의 원인이 되는", "ctx": "“Comrades,” he said quietly, “do you know who is ⟦responsible⟧ for this? Do you know the enemy who has come in the night and overthrown our windmill? SNOWBALL!” he suddenly roared in a voice of thunder.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 일의 원인이거나 그에 대한 책임을 진다는 뜻이다(be responsible for ~). who is responsible for this?(누가 이 일에 책임이 있는가?)에서, 폭풍이라는 자연의 결과를 누군가의 '책임'으로 바꿔치기하는 첫걸음을 내딛는다. 책임질 '주체'가 있다고 전제하는 이 물음 자체가, 재난을 인격적 적의 소행으로 몰아가는 함정이다.", "sid": "c6s032"}, {"word": "enemy", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈenəmi/", "mean": "적, 원수", "ctx": "“Comrades,” he said quietly, “do you know who is responsible for this? Do you know the ⟦enemy⟧ who has come in the night and overthrown our windmill? SNOWBALL!” he suddenly roared in a voice of thunder.", "marked": true, "note": "맞서 싸워야 할 상대를 뜻한다. Do you know the enemy who has come in the night(밤에 찾아온 그 적이 누군지 아는가)에서, '적'이라는 단어가 아직 이름도 대기 전에 이미 그 존재를 기정사실로 만든다. 폭풍이 '적'으로 둔갑하는 순간, 동물들의 분노는 자연이 아니라 가상의 인물을 향하도록 설계된다.", "sid": "c6s032"}, {"word": "overthrow", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌəʊvəˈθrəʊ/", "mean": "뒤엎다, 무너뜨리다, 전복하다", "ctx": "“Comrades,” he said quietly, “do you know who is responsible for this? Do you know the enemy who has come in the night and ⟦overthrown⟧ our windmill? SNOWBALL!” he suddenly roared in a voice of thunder.", "marked": true, "note": "권력이나 구조물을 힘으로 뒤엎어 무너뜨림을 뜻한다(정권을 '전복하다'에도 쓴다). overthrown our windmill(우리 풍차를 무너뜨렸다)에서, 바람이 쓰러뜨린 풍차를 누군가가 '뒤엎은' 것으로 둔갑시킨다. 자연 현상에 정치적 전복의 어감을 입힘으로써, 사고를 의도적 공격으로, 폭풍을 음모로 바꿔 놓는다.", "sid": "c6s032"}, {"word": "roar", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/rɔː/", "mean": "우렁차게 외치다, 포효하다", "ctx": "“Comrades,” he said quietly, “do you know who is responsible for this? Do you know the enemy who has come in the night and overthrown our windmill? SNOWBALL!” he suddenly ⟦roared⟧ in a voice of thunder.", "marked": true, "note": "사자가 으르렁대듯, 또는 사람이 분노·격정으로 우렁차게 내지름을 뜻한다. SNOWBALL!” he suddenly roared(“스노볼!” 그가 갑자기 포효했다)에서, 조용하던 목소리가 돌연 포효로 폭발한다. 'said quietly(조용히 말했다)'와의 극단적 음량 대비가, 그 이름 하나에 벼락 같은 무게를 실어 충격으로 각인시킨다.", "sid": "c6s032"}, {"word": "thunder", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈθʌndə/", "mean": "천둥, 우레", "ctx": "“Comrades,” he said quietly, “do you know who is responsible for this? Do you know the enemy who has come in the night and overthrown our windmill? SNOWBALL!” he suddenly roared in a voice of ⟦thunder⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "하늘을 가르는 천둥을 뜻한다. in a voice of thunder(우레 같은 목소리로)에서, 그의 외침을 천둥에 빗대어 거의 초자연적 위력을 입힌다. 마침 풍차를 무너뜨린 것도 천둥을 동반한 폭풍이었기에, 그 자연의 위력이 이제 지도자의 목소리로 옮겨 붙은 듯한 인상을 준다. 권력의 말이 자연의 힘처럼 군림하는 순간이다.", "sid": "c6s032"}, {"word": "malignity", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/məˈlɪɡnəti/", "mean": "악의, 깊은 적의 (해치려는 마음)", "ctx": "“Snowball has done this thing! In sheer ⟦malignity⟧, thinking to set back our plans and avenge himself for his ignominious expulsion, this traitor has crept here under cover of night and destroyed our work of nearly a year.", "marked": true, "note": "남을 해치려는 뿌리 깊은 악의를 뜻하는 격식어다. In sheer malignity(순전한 악의에서)에서, sheer(순전한)와 맞물려 그 동기에 한 점 변명의 여지도 두지 않는다. 풍차 붕괴를 '악의'의 소산으로 규정함으로써, 원인 규명을 건너뛴 채 곧장 도덕적 단죄로 직행한다. 증거 대신 동기를 단정하는 첫 단추다.", "sid": "c6s033"}, {"word": "avenge", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈvendʒ/", "mean": "복수하다, 앙갚음하다", "ctx": "“Snowball has done this thing! In sheer malignity, thinking to set back our plans and ⟦avenge⟧ himself for his ignominious expulsion, this traitor has crept here under cover of night and destroyed our work of nearly a year.", "marked": true, "note": "받은 해를 되갚으려 복수함을 뜻한다(avenge oneself = 스스로 원수를 갚다). avenge himself for his ignominious expulsion(치욕스러운 추방에 앙갚음하려고)에서, Snowball에게 '복수심'이라는 그럴듯한 동기를 입힌다. 그 자리에 없어 변론할 수 없는 자의 속마음을 제멋대로 읽어, 빈틈없는 악당의 서사를 지어낸다.", "sid": "c6s033"}, {"word": "ignominious", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌɪɡnəˈmɪniəs/", "mean": "치욕스러운, 불명예스러운", "ctx": "“Snowball has done this thing! In sheer malignity, thinking to set back our plans and avenge himself for his ⟦ignominious⟧ expulsion, this traitor has crept here under cover of night and destroyed our work of nearly a year.", "marked": true, "note": "남부끄럽고 수치스러움을 뜻하는 격식어다. his ignominious expulsion(그의 치욕스러운 추방)에서, Snowball이 쫓겨난 일을 '치욕'으로 규정한다. 그러나 그 추방은 실은 Napoleon이 개들을 풀어 강제로 몰아낸 권력 찬탈이었다. 가해를 피해자의 '수치'로 둔갑시키는 이 한 단어에, 역사를 다시 쓰는 권력의 솜씨가 응축돼 있다.", "sid": "c6s033"}, {"word": "expulsion", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ɪkˈspʌlʃn/", "mean": "추방, 쫓아냄, 제명", "ctx": "“Snowball has done this thing! In sheer malignity, thinking to set back our plans and avenge himself for his ignominious ⟦expulsion⟧, this traitor has crept here under cover of night and destroyed our work of nearly a year.", "marked": true, "note": "조직이나 장소에서 강제로 내쫓음을 뜻한다(동사 expel의 명사형). his ignominious expulsion(그의 치욕스러운 추방)에서, 한때 동지였던 자가 폭력으로 축출된 사건을 가리킨다. 그 추방의 책임자가 바로 지금 그를 단죄하는 Napoleon이라는 점에서, 자기가 저지른 일을 상대의 '복수 동기'로 되돌려 쓰는 전도(顚倒)가 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s033"}, {"word": "traitor", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtreɪtə/", "mean": "배신자, 반역자", "ctx": "“Snowball has done this thing! In sheer malignity, thinking to set back our plans and avenge himself for his ignominious expulsion, this ⟦traitor⟧ has crept here under cover of night and destroyed our work of nearly a year.", "marked": true, "note": "신의를 저버리고 자기편을 배반한 자를 뜻한다. this traitor has crept here(이 배신자가 여기 기어들어 왔다)에서, 이름 대신 'this traitor(이 배신자)'라는 평가어로 Snowball을 다시 부른다. 사실의 호명이 아니라 낙인의 호명이라, 듣는 순간 이미 유죄가 전제된다. 한때의 영웅을 단 한 단어로 반역자로 굳히는 명명의 폭력이다.", "sid": "c6s033"}, {"word": "creep", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kriːp/", "mean": "살금살금 기어들다, 몰래 다가오다", "ctx": "“Snowball has done this thing! In sheer malignity, thinking to set back our plans and avenge himself for his ignominious expulsion, this traitor has crept here under cover of night and destroyed our work of nearly a year.", "marked": false, "note": "들키지 않으려 몸을 낮춰 살금살금 움직임을 뜻한다(과거형 crept). this traitor has crept here under cover of night(이 배신자가 밤을 틈타 여기 기어들어 왔다)에서, 'crept(기어들었다)'가 비겁하고 음험한 잠입의 그림을 그린다. 폭풍이라는 거대한 자연 현상을, 한 마리가 어둠 속을 기어 다닌 좀스러운 범행으로 축소·왜곡하는 동사 선택이다.", "sid": "c6s033"}, {"word": "pronounce", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/prəˈnaʊns/", "mean": "(공식적으로) 선고하다, 단언하다", "ctx": "Comrades, here and now I ⟦pronounce⟧ the death sentence upon Snowball. ‘Animal Hero, Second Class,’ and half a bushel of apples to any animal who brings him to justice. A full bushel to anyone who captures him alive!”", "marked": true, "note": "단순히 '발음하다'가 아니라, 판결·선고 따위를 공식적으로 내림을 뜻한다(법정의 어휘다). I pronounce the death sentence upon Snowball(나는 스노볼에게 사형을 선고한다)에서, Napoleon이 마치 재판관처럼 형을 '선고'한다. 재판도 변론도 없이 한 개체가 입을 여는 것만으로 판결이 완성되는, 사법 권력의 사적 독점이 이 동사 하나에 응축된다.", "sid": "c6s034"}, {"word": "death sentence", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdeθ ˌsentəns/", "mean": "사형 선고, 사형 판결", "ctx": "Comrades, here and now I pronounce the ⟦death sentence⟧ upon Snowball. ‘Animal Hero, Second Class,’ and half a bushel of apples to any animal who brings him to justice. A full bushel to anyone who captures him alive!”", "marked": true, "note": "목숨을 거두는 형벌의 선고를 뜻한다. the death sentence upon Snowball(스노볼에 대한 사형 선고)에서, 증거도 재판도 없이 추방된 자에게 곧장 사형이 떨어진다. 한때 동물 농장에는 '어떤 동물도 다른 동물을 죽이지 않는다'는 계명이 있었음을 떠올리면, 이 선고는 혁명의 원칙이 권력의 편의에 따라 얼마나 멀리 비틀렸는지를 가늠하게 한다.", "sid": "c6s034"}, {"word": "bushel", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbʊʃl/", "mean": "부셸 (곡물·과일의 부피 단위)", "ctx": "Comrades, here and now I pronounce the death sentence upon Snowball. ‘Animal Hero, Second Class,’ and half a ⟦bushel⟧ of apples to any animal who brings him to justice. A full bushel to anyone who captures him alive!”", "marked": true, "note": "곡물이나 과일의 양을 재는 옛 부피 단위다(한 부셸은 대략 35리터쯤이다). half a bushel of apples ... A full bushel(반 부셸의 사과 ... 한 부셸 가득)에서, 현상금이 '사과'로 매겨진다. 일찍이 사과와 우유가 돼지들의 몫으로 독점됐던 일을 떠올리면, 그 귀한 사과를 상금으로 내거는 데서 보상의 위계와 통제가 함께 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s034"}, {"word": "bring to justice", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/brɪŋ tə ˈdʒʌstɪs/", "mean": "법의 심판을 받게 하다, 처벌받게 하다", "ctx": "Comrades, here and now I pronounce the death sentence upon Snowball. ‘Animal Hero, Second Class,’ and half a bushel of apples to any animal who ⟦brings⟧ him to justice. A full bushel to anyone who captures him alive!”", "marked": true, "note": "죄지은 자를 붙잡아 마땅한 처벌을 받게 함을 뜻하는 관용구다. any animal who brings him to justice(그를 심판대에 세우는 어떤 동물에게든)에서, '정의(justice)'라는 말이 동원된다. 그러나 그 정의란 공정한 재판이 아니라 이미 내려진 사형 선고의 집행일 뿐이라, 숭고한 단어가 사적 처단을 포장하는 데 쓰이는 모순이 엿보인다.", "sid": "c6s034"}, {"word": "capture", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈkæptʃə/", "mean": "사로잡다, 붙잡다, 생포하다", "ctx": "Comrades, here and now I pronounce the death sentence upon Snowball. ‘Animal Hero, Second Class,’ and half a bushel of apples to any animal who brings him to justice. A full bushel to anyone who ⟦captures⟧ him alive!”", "marked": true, "note": "달아나는 대상을 붙잡아 가둠을 뜻한다. anyone who captures him alive(그를 산 채로 사로잡는 누구에게든)에서, 죽여 데려오는 것보다 '생포'에 더 큰 상을 건다. 산 채로 잡는 편이 더 값지다는 이 셈은, 본보기로 삼을 처벌이나 공개적 단죄의 무대가 필요함을 넌지시 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s034"}, {"word": "alive", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/əˈlaɪv/", "mean": "살아 있는, 산 채로", "ctx": "Comrades, here and now I pronounce the death sentence upon Snowball. ‘Animal Hero, Second Class,’ and half a bushel of apples to any animal who brings him to justice. A full bushel to anyone who captures him ⟦alive⟧!”", "marked": true, "note": "죽지 않고 살아 있는 상태를 뜻한다. captures him alive(그를 산 채로 사로잡다)에서, 문장 끝에 놓인 alive가 현상금의 절정을 찍는다. 사형을 선고해 놓고도 '산 채로'에 더 큰 값을 매기는 까닭은, 그를 끌어다 공개적으로 단죄하는 본보기의 무대가 더 요긴하기 때문이다. 단어 하나가 처벌의 목적이 응징을 넘어 '구경거리'에 있음을 일러 준다.", "sid": "c6s034"}, {"word": "beyond measure", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/bɪˈjɒnd ˈmeʒə/", "mean": "이루 헤아릴 수 없을 만큼, 한없이", "ctx": "The animals were shocked ⟦beyond measure⟧ to learn that even Snowball could be guilty of such an action. There was a cry of indignation, and everyone began thinking out ways of catching Snowball if he should ever come back.", "marked": true, "note": "잴 수 없을 정도로 지나침을 뜻하는 관용구다(measure=잼·측정). shocked beyond measure(이루 말할 수 없이 충격을 받은)에서, 동물들의 놀라움이 가늠할 수 없을 만큼 컸음을 강조한다. 그러나 그토록 충격을 받았다는 것은 곧 그 주장을 사실로 받아들였다는 뜻이기도 하여, 과장된 놀라움이 도리어 그들이 이미 믿어 버렸음을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c6s035"}, {"word": "guilty", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈɡɪlti/", "mean": "유죄의, 죄를 지은", "ctx": "The animals were shocked beyond measure to learn that even Snowball could be ⟦guilty⟧ of such an action. There was a cry of indignation, and everyone began thinking out ways of catching Snowball if he should ever come back.", "marked": true, "note": "잘못이나 범죄에 책임이 있음을 뜻한다(be guilty of ~). even Snowball could be guilty of such an action(스노볼마저 그런 짓에 유죄일 수 있다니)에서, 동물들이 그의 '유죄'를 이미 전제로 받아들이고 있음이 드러난다. 증거는 아직 한 조각도 없지만, 그들의 충격은 '그가 정말 그랬을까'가 아니라 '그가 그럴 수 있다니'에 머문다. 의심의 단계는 이미 건너뛴 것이다.", "sid": "c6s035"}, {"word": "indignation", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌɪndɪɡˈneɪʃn/", "mean": "(부당함에 대한) 분개, 의분", "ctx": "The animals were shocked beyond measure to learn that even Snowball could be guilty of such an action. There was a cry of ⟦indignation⟧, and everyone began thinking out ways of catching Snowball if he should ever come back.", "marked": true, "note": "부당하거나 옳지 못한 일에 대해 끓어오르는 분노를 뜻한다. There was a cry of indignation(분개의 외침이 터져 나왔다)에서, 앞선 '절망의 비명(a cry of despair)'이 이제 '분개의 외침'으로 바뀐다. 같은 집단의 외침이되 그 방향이 달라진 것이다. 통제 불가능한 폭풍을 향하던 절망이, 처단 가능한 '적'을 향한 분노로 말끔히 갈아 끼워진다.", "sid": "c6s035"}, {"word": "think out", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/θɪŋk aʊt/", "mean": "(방법 따위를) 궁리해 내다, 짜내다", "ctx": "The animals were shocked beyond measure to learn that even Snowball could be guilty of such an action. There was a cry of indignation, and everyone began ⟦thinking⟧ out ways of catching Snowball if he should ever come back.", "marked": true, "note": "하나하나 따져 가며 방법이나 계획을 궁리해 냄을 뜻한다. everyone began thinking out ways of catching Snowball(모두가 스노볼을 붙잡을 방법을 궁리하기 시작했다)에서, 동물들이 그 주장의 진위를 따지는 대신 곧장 '잡을 방법'으로 머리를 돌린다. 의심해야 할 자리에서 실행을 궁리하는 이 전환이, 선동이 얼마나 매끄럽게 받아들여졌는지를 보여 준다.", "sid": "c6s035"}, {"word": "come back", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/kʌm bæk/", "mean": "돌아오다, 되돌아오다", "ctx": "The animals were shocked beyond measure to learn that even Snowball could be guilty of such an action. There was a cry of indignation, and everyone began thinking out ways of catching Snowball if he should ever ⟦come back⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "떠났던 곳으로 다시 옴을 뜻한다. if he should ever come back(혹시라도 그가 돌아온다면)에서, 이미 쫓겨난 Snowball이 언제든 다시 나타날지 모른다는 경계를 심는다. 적이 '돌아올' 가능성을 열어 둠으로써, 그는 사라진 과거의 인물이 아니라 늘 도사린 현재의 위협으로 남는다. 상존하는 적은 끝없는 경계와 동원의 명분이 된다.", "sid": "c6s035"}, {"word": "snuffed", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/snʌft/", "mean": "킁킁 냄새 맡았다", "ctx": "Almost immediately the footprints of a pig were discovered in the grass at a little distance from the knoll. They could only be traced for a few yards, but appeared to lead to a hole in the hedge. Napoleon ⟦snuffed⟧ deeply at them and pronounced them to be Snowball’s.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s036"}, {"word": "footprint", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈfʊtprɪnt/", "mean": "발자국, 발자취", "ctx": "Almost immediately the ⟦footprints⟧ of a pig were discovered in the grass at a little distance from the knoll. They could only be traced for a few yards, but appeared to lead to a hole in the hedge. Napoleon snuffed deeply at them and pronounced them to be Snowball’s.", "marked": true, "note": "땅에 찍힌 발의 자국을 뜻한다. the footprints of a pig were discovered(돼지의 발자국이 발견되었다)에서, 이 발자국이 곧 Snowball을 범인으로 못 박는 '물증'으로 제시된다. 그러나 농장의 돼지는 한둘이 아니므로 '돼지의 발자국'이 곧 Snowball의 것일 수는 없다. 증거의 외형만 갖춘 채 결론이 미리 정해진, 조작된 단서의 핵심 소품이다.", "sid": "c6s036"}, {"word": "trace", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/treɪs/", "mean": "(자취를) 따라가다, 추적하다", "ctx": "Almost immediately the footprints of a pig were discovered in the grass at a little distance from the knoll. They could only be ⟦traced⟧ for a few yards, but appeared to lead to a hole in the hedge. Napoleon snuffed deeply at them and pronounced them to be Snowball’s.", "marked": true, "note": "남은 흔적을 따라 경로를 좇음을 뜻한다. They could only be traced for a few yards(그것은 겨우 몇 야드밖에 좇을 수 없었다)에서, 그 발자국이 얼마나 빈약한 단서인지가 드러난다. 'only ... a few yards(겨우 몇 야드)'라는 한계가, 곧이어 내려질 단정적 결론과 날카롭게 어긋난다. 증거는 빈약한데 결론은 확고한, 그 틈이 조작을 누설한다.", "sid": "c6s036"}, {"word": "knoll", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/nəʊl/", "mean": "작은 언덕, 둔덕", "ctx": "Almost immediately the footprints of a pig were discovered in the grass at a little distance from the ⟦knoll⟧. They could only be traced for a few yards, but appeared to lead to a hole in the hedge. Napoleon snuffed deeply at them and pronounced them to be Snowball’s.", "marked": true, "note": "완만하게 솟은 자그마한 언덕을 뜻한다. at a little distance from the knoll(그 둔덕에서 조금 떨어진 곳에서)에서, 발자국이 발견된 위치를 가리킨다. 이 둔덕은 다름 아닌 풍차가 서 있던 바로 그 자리다. 무너진 현장 가까이에서 '마침' 발자국이 나왔다는 설정이, 증거가 사건에 맞춰 등장한 듯한 작위적 인상을 더한다.", "sid": "c6s036"}, {"word": "hedge", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/hedʒ/", "mean": "산울타리, 생울타리", "ctx": "Almost immediately the footprints of a pig were discovered in the grass at a little distance from the knoll. They could only be traced for a few yards, but appeared to lead to a hole in the ⟦hedge⟧. Napoleon snuffed deeply at them and pronounced them to be Snowball’s.", "marked": true, "note": "나무나 관목을 심어 만든 경계용 울타리를 뜻한다. appeared to lead to a hole in the hedge(산울타리의 구멍으로 이어지는 듯했다)에서, 발자국이 농장 경계 밖으로 빠져나간 양 그려진다. 울타리의 구멍은 곧 외부와의 통로이며, 범인이 농장 밖에서 들어왔다는 서사를 뒷받침하는 장치다. 이 '바깥으로 난 길'이 Snowball을 외부의 적과 잇는 다음 단정으로 이어진다.", "sid": "c6s036"}, {"word": "opinion", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/əˈpɪnjən/", "mean": "의견, 견해", "ctx": "They could only be traced for a few yards, but appeared to lead to a hole in the hedge. Napoleon snuffed deeply at them and pronounced them to be Snowball’s. He gave it as his ⟦opinion⟧ that Snowball had probably come from the direction of Foxwood Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "확증된 사실이 아니라 한 사람의 판단·견해를 뜻한다. He gave it as his opinion that Snowball had probably come from ...(그는 스노볼이 ~에서 왔을 것이라는 의견을 내놓았다)에서, Napoleon의 말이 '의견(opinion)'이자 'probably(아마)'라는 추측임을 작가가 또렷이 밝힌다. 그러나 권력자의 입에서 나온 추측은 곧 사실처럼 통용된다. '의견'과 '단정' 사이의 경계가 권력 앞에서 지워지는 것이다.", "sid": "c6s036"}, {"word": "footprints", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈfʊtprɪnts/", "mean": "발자국", "ctx": "“No more delays, comrades!” cried Napoleon when the ⟦footprints⟧ had been examined. “There is work to be done. This very morning we begin rebuilding the windmill, and we will build all through the winter, rain or shine. We will teach this miserable traitor that he cannot undo our work so easily.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c6s037"}, {"word": "delay", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/dɪˈleɪ/", "mean": "지체, 지연, 미룸", "ctx": "“No more ⟦delays⟧, comrades!” cried Napoleon when the footprints had been examined. “There is work to be done. This very morning we begin rebuilding the windmill, and we will build all through the winter, rain or shine. We will teach this miserable traitor that he cannot undo our work so easily.", "marked": true, "note": "해야 할 일을 늦추거나 미룸을 뜻한다. No more delays, comrades!(더는 지체 말라, 동지들이여!)에서, 슬픔에 잠길 틈도 없이 곧장 일로 내모는 외침이다. 폐허를 애도하거나 원인을 따질 시간을 'delay(지체)'로 규정해 차단함으로써, 동물들이 멈춰 서서 생각할 여지를 없앤다. 비탄에서 노동으로의 전환을 재촉하는 첫마디다.", "sid": "c6s037"}, {"word": "rebuild", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌriːˈbɪld/", "mean": "다시 짓다, 재건하다", "ctx": "“No more delays, comrades!” cried Napoleon when the footprints had been examined. “There is work to be done. This very morning we begin ⟦rebuilding⟧ the windmill, and we will build all through the winter, rain or shine. We will teach this miserable traitor that he cannot undo our work so easily.", "marked": true, "note": "무너진 것을 다시 세움을 뜻한다(re- '다시' + build '짓다'). This very morning we begin rebuilding the windmill(바로 오늘 아침 우리는 풍차 재건을 시작한다)에서, 무너진 그날 아침에 곧바로 재건을 선포한다. 'this very morning(바로 오늘 아침)'의 즉시성이 비장한 결의처럼 들리지만, 동시에 동물들에게 또다시 끝없는 노동이 부과됨을 뜻하기도 한다.", "sid": "c6s037"}, {"word": "rain or shine", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/ˌreɪn ɔː ˈʃaɪn/", "mean": "비가 오나 해가 뜨나, 어떤 일이 있어도", "ctx": "“No more delays, comrades!” cried Napoleon when the footprints had been examined. “There is work to be done. This very morning we begin rebuilding the windmill, and we will build all through the winter, ⟦rain or shine⟧. We will teach this miserable traitor that he cannot undo our work so easily.", "marked": true, "note": "날씨가 어떻든, 무슨 일이 있어도 한결같이 함을 뜻하는 관용구다. we will build all through the winter, rain or shine(우리는 비가 오나 해가 뜨나 겨우내 지을 것이다)에서, 어떤 악조건에도 굴하지 않겠다는 결의를 표한다. 그러나 정작 풍차를 무너뜨린 것이 바로 그 '날씨'였음을 떠올리면, 날씨에 굴하지 않겠다는 이 다짐에는 씁쓸한 아이러니가 깃든다.", "sid": "c6s037"}, {"word": "undo", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ʌnˈduː/", "mean": "(한 일을) 원상태로 돌리다, 망쳐 놓다, 무위로 돌리다", "ctx": "“No more delays, comrades!” cried Napoleon when the footprints had been examined. “There is work to be done. This very morning we begin rebuilding the windmill, and we will build all through the winter, rain or shine. We will teach this miserable traitor that he cannot ⟦undo⟧ our work so easily.", "marked": true, "note": "이미 이룬 것을 도로 무너뜨려 없던 일로 만듦을 뜻한다(un- '반대로' + do '하다'). he cannot undo our work so easily(그가 우리의 노고를 그리 쉽게 무위로 돌리지는 못한다)에서, Snowball이 풍차를 무너뜨려 노동을 헛되게 만들었다는 전제를 깐다. 재건을 그 '적'에 대한 항거로 규정함으로써, 노동 자체를 복수의 행위로 둔갑시킨다.", "sid": "c6s037"}, {"word": "miserable", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈmɪzrəbl/", "mean": "비참한; (사람을 낮춰) 한심한, 가증스러운", "ctx": "“No more delays, comrades!” cried Napoleon when the footprints had been examined. “There is work to be done. This very morning we begin rebuilding the windmill, and we will build all through the winter, rain or shine. We will teach this ⟦miserable⟧ traitor that he cannot undo our work so easily.", "marked": true, "note": "본디 '비참한'이지만, 사람 앞에 붙으면 '한심한·가증스러운'이라는 경멸의 뜻을 띤다. this miserable traitor(이 가증스러운 배신자)에서, traitor에 miserable을 더해 경멸의 강도를 한층 높인다. 이미 'traitor(배신자)'로 낙인찍힌 대상에 멸시의 형용사를 거듭 입힘으로써, 청중의 적개심을 한 번 더 부추기는 감정적 수식이다.", "sid": "c6s037"}, {"word": "alteration", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌɔːltəˈreɪʃn/", "mean": "변경, 수정, 바꿈", "ctx": "Remember, comrades, there must be no ⟦alteration⟧ in our plans: they shall be carried out to the day. Forward, comrades! Long live the windmill! Long live Animal Farm!”", "marked": true, "note": "이미 정해진 것을 고치거나 바꿈을 뜻한다(동사 alter의 명사형). there must be no alteration in our plans(우리 계획에 어떤 변경도 있어선 안 된다)에서, 계획을 한 치도 바꿀 수 없는 신성한 것으로 못 박는다. 그러나 정작 풍차 계획은 그동안 Napoleon에 의해 거듭 뒤집혀 왔기에, '변경 불가'를 외치는 이 단언에는 스스로를 배반하는 아이러니가 깃든다.", "sid": "c6s038"}, {"word": "carry out", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/ˌkæri ˈaʊt/", "mean": "(계획·명령을) 실행하다, 수행하다", "ctx": "Remember, comrades, there must be no alteration in our plans: they shall be ⟦carried⟧ out to the day. Forward, comrades! Long live the windmill! Long live Animal Farm!”", "marked": true, "note": "계획이나 명령을 끝까지 이행함을 뜻한다. they shall be carried out to the day(그것은 예정된 날까지 어김없이 실행될 것이다)에서, 수동태로 쓰여 계획이 '반드시 실행되어야 함'을 강조하되 그 노동의 주체는 가린다. 누가 그 고된 실행을 떠맡을지는 흐려진 채, 계획의 완수만이 절대 명령으로 선포된다.", "sid": "c6s038"}, {"word": "to the day", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/tə ðə deɪ/", "mean": "날짜까지 정확히, 예정된 그날에 어김없이", "ctx": "Remember, comrades, there must be no alteration in our plans: they shall be carried out ⟦to the day⟧. Forward, comrades! Long live the windmill! Long live Animal Farm!”", "marked": true, "note": "정해진 날짜에 한 치의 어긋남도 없이 들어맞음을 뜻하는 관용구다. they shall be carried out to the day(예정된 날까지 어김없이 실행될 것이다)에서, 계획의 완수를 날짜 단위까지 못 박는다. 이 빈틈없는 정확성의 요구는, 현실의 온갖 변수를 무시한 채 오직 일정 준수만을 절대시하는 경직된 명령이다. 인간적 형편보다 계획표가 우선시되는 것이다.", "sid": "c6s038"}, {"word": "forward", "pos": "adv./interj.", "pron": "/ˈfɔːwəd/", "mean": "앞으로! (전진을 외치는 구령)", "ctx": "Remember, comrades, there must be no alteration in our plans: they shall be carried out to the day. ⟦Forward⟧, comrades! Long live the windmill! Long live Animal Farm!”", "marked": true, "note": "앞을 향한 전진을 뜻하며, 감탄사로 '앞으로!'라는 진군의 구령으로도 쓰인다. Forward, comrades!(앞으로, 동지들이여!)에서, 군대의 진군 구령 같은 어조로 무리를 몰아세운다. 폐허를 등지고 오직 '앞'만을 가리키는 이 외침은, 지나간 실패와 그 책임을 돌아보지 못하게 막고 시선을 약속된 미래에만 붙들어 둔다.", "sid": "c6s038"}, {"word": "long live", "pos": "expression", "pron": "/ˌlɒŋ ˈlɪv/", "mean": "~여 영원하라, ~만세", "ctx": "Remember, comrades, there must be no alteration in our plans: they shall be carried out to the day. Forward, comrades! ⟦Long live⟧ the windmill! Long live Animal Farm!”", "marked": true, "note": "'~가 오래 살기를(영원하기를)'이라는 기원의 외침으로, 흔히 군주나 국가를 향한 '만세' 구호다. Long live the windmill! Long live Animal Farm!(풍차여 영원하라! 동물 농장이여 영원하라!)에서, 같은 구호를 반복해 군중을 한목소리의 환호로 묶는다. 방금 무너진 풍차를 향해 '영원하라'를 외치게 하는 데서, 생각을 대신하는 구호의 힘이 또렷이 드러난다.", "sid": "c6s038"}], "7": [{"word": "stormy", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈstɔːmi/", "mean": "격렬한, 폭풍 같은", "ctx": "I t was a bitter winter. The ⟦stormy⟧ weather was followed by sleet and snow, and then by a hard frost which did not break till well into February.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "sleet", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/sliːt/", "mean": "진눈깨비", "ctx": "I t was a bitter winter. The stormy weather was followed by ⟦sleet⟧ and snow, and then by a hard frost which did not break till well into February.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "frost", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/frɒst/", "mean": "서리, (강한) 결빙·혹한", "ctx": "I t was a bitter winter. The stormy weather was followed by sleet and snow, and then by a hard ⟦frost⟧ which did not break till well into February.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "quarry", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkwɒri/", "mean": "채석장 (돌을 캐내는 곳)", "ctx": "The animals knew that this was not the case. Still, it had been decided to build the walls three feet thick this time instead of eighteen inches as before, which meant collecting much larger quantities of stone. For a long time the ⟦quarry⟧ was full of snowdrifts and nothing could be done.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "snowdrifts", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsnəʊdrɪfts/", "mean": "(바람에 쌓인) 눈더미", "ctx": "The animals knew that this was not the case. Still, it had been decided to build the walls three feet thick this time instead of eighteen inches as before, which meant collecting much larger quantities of stone. For a long time the quarry was full of ⟦snowdrifts⟧ and nothing could be done.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "frosty", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈfrɒsti/", "mean": "서리 내린, 꽁꽁 언", "ctx": "For a long time the quarry was full of snowdrifts and nothing could be done. Some progress was made in the dry ⟦frosty⟧ weather that followed, but it was cruel work, and the animals could not feel so hopeful about it as they had felt before. They were always cold, and usually hungry as well.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "bitter", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈbɪtə/", "mean": "(추위가) 맹렬한, 살을 에는; (맛이) 쓴; (감정이) 쓰라린", "ctx": "I t was a ⟦bitter⟧ winter. The stormy weather was followed by sleet and snow, and then by a hard frost which did not break till well into February.", "marked": true, "note": "살을 엘 듯이 혹독한 추위를 뜻한다. a bitter winter(맹렬한 겨울)는 단순한 날씨 묘사를 넘어, 이 장 전체의 알레고리적 겨울, 곧 굶주림과 공포의 계절을 여는 열쇠말이다. bitter는 맛·감정에도 쓰여 '쓴', '원통한'을 뜻한다.", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "out of spite", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/spaɪt/", "mean": "앙심으로, 심술궂게, 악의로", "ctx": "The animals carried on as best they could with the rebuilding of the windmill, well knowing that the outside world was watching them and that the envious human beings would rejoice and triumph if the mill were not finished on time.⟦Out of spite⟧, the human beings pretended not to believe that it was Snowball who had destroyer the windmill: they said that it had fallen down because the walls were too thin.", "marked": true, "note": "상대를 해치거나 괴롭히려는 앙심에서 하는 행동을 가리킨다. Out of spite, the human beings pretended not to believe...(앙심으로, 인간들은 믿지 않는 체했다)에서 인간의 거짓말이 이해타산이 아니라 순수한 악의에서 나온다고 못 박는다.", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "envious", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈenviəs/", "mean": "시기하는, 질투하는, 부러워하는", "ctx": "The animals carried on as best they could with the rebuilding of the windmill, well knowing that the outside world was watching them and that the ⟦envious⟧ human beings would rejoice and triumph if the mill were not finished on time.Out of spite, the human beings pretended not to believe that it was Snowball who had destroyer the windmill: they said that it had fallen down because the walls were too thin.", "marked": true, "note": "남이 가진 것을 시샘하고 탐내는 마음을 뜻한다. the envious human beings would rejoice and triumph에서 인간은 동물들의 자립을 '시기하는' 존재로 그려진다. 이 프레임은 동물들이 고통을 견디게 만드는 이념적 동력이다.", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "lose heart", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/luːz hɑːt/", "mean": "낙담하다, 용기를 잃다, 기가 꺾이다", "ctx": "I t was a bitter winter. The stormy weather was followed by sleet and snow, and then by a hard frost which did not break till well into February. The animals carried on as best they could with the rebuilding of the windmill, well knowing that the outside world was watching them and that the envious …", "marked": false, "note": "희망이나 의욕을 잃는다는 뜻이다. Only Boxer and Clover never lost heart(오직 Boxer와 Clover만은 결코 낙담하지 않았다)에서, 가장 많이 착취당하는 두 존재가 역설적으로 가장 적게 낙담한다. 충실한 자의 희망이 체제를 지탱한다.", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "the dignity of labour", "pos": "phrase", "pron": "/ˈdɪɡnəti/", "mean": "노동의 존엄(가치)", "ctx": "They were always cold, and usually hungry as well. Only Boxer and Clover never lost heart. Squealer made excellent speeches on the joy of service and ⟦the dignity of labour⟧, but the other animals found more inspiration in Boxer’s strength and his never-failing cry of “I will work harder!”", "marked": true, "note": "노동 그 자체가 고귀하고 가치 있다는 구호다. excellent speeches on the joy of service and the dignity of labour에서는, 그럴듯한 구호가 굶주림을 덮는 말잔치로 쓰인다. 웅변(speech)과 실제로 일하는 힘(Boxer) 사이의 대비가 선명하다.", "sid": "c7s001"}, {"word": "ration", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈræʃn/", "mean": "배급(량), 정해진 몫", "ctx": "In January food fell short. The corn ⟦ration⟧ was drastically reduced, and it was announced that an extra potato ration would be issued to make up for it. Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough.", "marked": true, "note": "부족한 식량을 일정량씩 나눠 주는 것, 또는 그렇게 정해진 분량. ‘the corn ration was drastically reduced’ = 곡물 배급이 크게 줄었다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "clamp", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/klæmp/", "mean": "(감자·뿌리채소) 겨울 저장 더미", "ctx": "In January food fell short. The corn ration was drastically reduced, and it was announced that an extra potato ration would be issued to make up for it. Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the ⟦clamps⟧, which had not been covered thickly enough.", "marked": true, "note": "감자나 순무를 쌓아 올리고 짚과 흙으로 덮어 두는 저장 더미. 흔한 ‘죔쇠/클램프’ 뜻이 아님에 주의. ‘frosted in the clamps’ = 저장 더미 속에서 얼어 버렸다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "discoloured", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/dɪsˈkʌləd/", "mean": "변색된, 색이 바랜", "ctx": "Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough. The potatoes had become soft and ⟦discoloured⟧, and only a few were edible. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but chaff and mangels.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "chaff", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/tʃɑːf/", "mean": "왕겨, 쭉정이", "ctx": "Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough. The potatoes had become soft and discoloured, and only a few were edible. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but ⟦chaff⟧ and mangels.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "mangels", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈmæŋɡəlz/", "mean": "사료용 사탕무", "ctx": "Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough. The potatoes had become soft and discoloured, and only a few were edible. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but chaff and ⟦mangels⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "vitally", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈvaɪtəli/", "mean": "대단히, 절대적으로 (중요하게)", "ctx": "The potatoes had become soft and discoloured, and only a few were edible. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but chaff and mangels. Starvation seemed to stare them in the face.It was ⟦vitally⟧ necessary to conceal this fact from the outside world.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "conceal", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kənˈsiːl/", "mean": "감추다. 숨기다", "ctx": "The potatoes had become soft and discoloured, and only a few were edible. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but chaff and mangels. Starvation seemed to stare them in the face.It was vitally necessary to ⟦conceal⟧ this fact from the outside world.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "fall short", "pos": "phr. v.", "pron": "/fɔːl ʃɔːt/", "mean": "부족해지다, 모자라다, 미치지 못하다", "ctx": "In January food fell short. The corn ration was drastically reduced, and it was announced that an extra potato ration would be issued to make up for it. Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough. The pota…", "marked": false, "note": "필요한 양에 못 미친다는 뜻이다. In January food fell short(1월에 식량이 부족해졌다)는 짧고 단호한 선언으로, 풍요를 약속하던 체제가 정작 굶주림에 들어섰음을 건조하게 알린다. fall short of(~에 미치지 못하다)의 형태로도 자주 쓰인다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "drastically", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈdræstɪkli/", "mean": "급격하게, 과감하게, 대폭", "ctx": "In January food fell short. The corn ration was ⟦drastically⟧ reduced, and it was announced that an extra potato ration would be issued to make up for it. Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough.", "marked": true, "note": "변화의 폭이 매우 크고 거칠다는 뜻이다. The corn ration was drastically reduced(곡물 배급이 대폭 줄었다)에서, Ch.9의 완곡어 'readjustment(재조정)'와 달리 여기서는 서술자가 'drastically'라고 솔직히 적는다. 같은 사실을 누가 어떻게 부르는가가, 곧 누구의 언어인가를 가른다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "frosted", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈfrɒstɪd/", "mean": "서리에 상한, 얼어 버린", "ctx": "In January food fell short. The corn ration was drastically reduced, and it was announced that an extra potato ration would be issued to make up for it. Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been ⟦frosted⟧ in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough.", "marked": true, "note": "서리·냉해로 작물이 얼어 망가진 상태를 뜻한다. the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps(감자 대부분이 저장 더미 안에서 얼어 버렸다)는, 부실한 관리(덮개를 충분히 두껍게 덮지 않음)가 부른 인재(人災)다. 자연재해처럼 보이지만, 그 뿌리는 운영의 실패다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "edible", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈedəbl/", "mean": "먹을 수 있는, 식용의", "ctx": "Then it was discovered that the greater part of the potato crop had been frosted in the clamps, which had not been covered thickly enough. The potatoes had become soft and discoloured, and only a few were ⟦edible⟧. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but chaff and mangels.", "marked": true, "note": "먹어도 되는, 먹을 만한 상태를 뜻한다. only a few were edible(먹을 수 있는 것은 몇 개뿐이었다)에서, 감자가 물러 변색되어 대부분 못 먹게 된 참상이 절제된 한마디로 요약된다. 반대말은 inedible(먹을 수 없는)이다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "stare (sb) in the face", "pos": "idiom", "pron": "/steə/", "mean": "(위험·죽음 등이) 코앞에 닥치다, 빤히 노려보다", "ctx": "The potatoes had become soft and discoloured, and only a few were edible. For days at a time the animals had nothing to eat but chaff and mangels. Starvation seemed to ⟦stare⟧ them in the face.It was vitally necessary to conceal this fact from the outside world.", "marked": true, "note": "위험이나 파국이 피할 수 없이 눈앞에 와 있음을 뜻하는 관용구다. Starvation seemed to stare them in the face(굶주림이 그들을 빤히 노려보는 듯했다)에서, 추상명사 starvation이 마치 살아 있는 적처럼 동물들을 마주 본다. 의인화가 공포를 생생하게 만든다.", "sid": "c7s002"}, {"word": "inventing", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ɪnˈventɪŋ/", "mean": "발명하는, 지어내는", "ctx": "Emboldened by the collapse of the windmill, the human beings were ⟦inventing⟧ fresh lies about Animal Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s003", "base": "invent — 발명하다, 지어내다"}, {"word": "cannibalism", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkænɪbəlɪzəm/", "mean": "동족을 잡아먹음, 식인", "ctx": "Once again it was being put about that all the animals were dying of famine and disease, and that they were continually fighting among themselves and had resorted to ⟦cannibalism⟧ and infanticide.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "infanticide", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ɪnˈfæntɪsaɪd/", "mean": "영아 살해", "ctx": "Once again it was being put about that all the animals were dying of famine and disease, and that they were continually fighting among themselves and had resorted to cannibalism and ⟦infanticide⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "remark", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/rɪˈmɑːk/", "mean": "발언, 논평", "ctx": "Whymper to spread a contrary impression. Hitherto the animals had had little or no contact with Whymper on his weekly visits: now, however, a few selected animals, mostly sheep, were instructed to ⟦remark⟧ casually in his hearing that rations had been increased.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "rations", "pos": "n. (pl.)", "pron": "/ˈræʃnz/ (영) / ˈreɪʃnz/ (미)", "mean": "배급, 할당된 식량", "ctx": "Whymper to spread a contrary impression. Hitherto the animals had had little or no contact with Whymper on his weekly visits: now, however, a few selected animals, mostly sheep, were instructed to remark casually in his hearing that ⟦rations⟧ had been increased.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "deceived", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/dɪˈsiːvd/", "mean": "속였다, 기만했다", "ctx": "On some suitable pretext Whymper was led through the store-shed and allowed to catch a glimpse of the bins. He was ⟦deceived⟧, and continued to report to the outside world that there was no food shortage on Animal Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "emboldened", "pos": "adj. (pp.)", "pron": "/ɪmˈbəʊldənd/", "mean": "대담해진, 기세가 오른", "ctx": "⟦Emboldened⟧ by the collapse of the windmill, the human beings were inventing fresh lies about Animal Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "embolden(대담하게 만들다)의 과거분사로, 무언가에 힘입어 더 과감해진 상태를 뜻한다. Emboldened by the collapse of the windmill(풍차의 붕괴에 기세가 올라)에서, 인간들은 풍차가 무너진 것을 기회로 삼아 더 뻔뻔하게 거짓말을 지어낸다. 분사구문이 문장 맨 앞에 놓여 '무엇이 그들을 대담하게 했는지'를 먼저 짚는다.", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "put about", "pos": "phr. v.", "pron": "/pʊt əˈbaʊt/", "mean": "(소문을) 퍼뜨리다, 유포하다", "ctx": "Once again it was being ⟦put about⟧ that all the animals were dying of famine and disease, and that they were continually fighting among themselves and had resorted to cannibalism and infanticide.", "marked": true, "note": "소문이나 이야기를 널리 퍼뜨린다는 뜻이다. it was being put about that all the animals were dying of famine(모든 동물이 굶주림으로 죽어 간다는 말이 퍼지고 있었다)에서, 행위자 없는 수동으로 쓰여 '누가' 퍼뜨리는지는 흐려지고 소문만 떠도는 분위기를 만든다.", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "hitherto", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˌhɪðəˈtuː/", "mean": "지금까지, 이제까지", "ctx": "Whymper to spread a contrary impression. ⟦Hitherto⟧ the animals had had little or no contact with Whymper on his weekly visits: now, however, a few selected animals, mostly sheep, were instructed to remark casually in his hearing that rations had been increased.", "marked": true, "note": "과거의 어느 시점까지를 가리키는 격식 있는 부사다. Hitherto the animals had had little or no contact with Whymper(이제까지 동물들은 Whymper와 거의 접촉이 없었다)에서, 'now, however(그러나 이제)'와 짝을 이루어 상황이 한 시점을 기준으로 바뀌었음을 또렷이 한다.", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "pretext", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈpriːtekst/", "mean": "구실, 핑계", "ctx": "In addition, Napoleon ordered the almost empty bins in the store-shed to be filled nearly to the brim with sand, which was then covered up with what remained of the grain and meal. On some suitable ⟦pretext⟧ Whymper was led through the store-shed and allowed to catch a glimpse of the bins.", "marked": true, "note": "진짜 목적을 감추려고 내세우는 그럴듯한 이유를 뜻한다. On some suitable pretext Whymper was led through the store-shed(적당한 구실로 Whymper는 곳간을 지나가게 되었다)에서, 모래 채운 통을 '우연히' 보게 하려는 연출이 '구실'이라는 한 단어에 담긴다. 자연스러운 척하지만 모두 짜인 각본이다.", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "brim", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/brɪm/", "mean": "(그릇·통의) 가장자리, 위쪽 끝", "ctx": "In addition, Napoleon ordered the almost empty bins in the store-shed to be filled nearly to the ⟦brim⟧ with sand, which was then covered up with what remained of the grain and meal. On some suitable pretext Whymper was led through the store-shed and allowed to catch a glimpse of the bins.", "marked": true, "note": "통이나 잔의 맨 윗부분을 가리킨다. filled nearly to the brim with sand(모래로 거의 가장자리까지 채워)에서, '가득 찬 것처럼' 보이게 하는 속임수가 to the brim(끝까지)이라는 표현으로 강조된다. 곡식인 척 위만 곡물로 덮은 통이다.", "sid": "c7s003"}, {"word": "procure", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/prəˈkjʊə/", "mean": "(어렵게) 구하다, 조달하다", "ctx": "Nevertheless, towards the end of January it became obvious that it would be necessary to ⟦procure⟧ some more grain from somewhere. In these days Napoleon rarely appeared in public, but spent all his time in the farmhouse, which was guarded at each door by fierce-looking dogs.", "marked": true, "note": "노력이나 수단을 들여 무언가를 손에 넣는다는 격식 있는 동사다. it would be necessary to procure some more grain from somewhere(어디선가 곡물을 더 조달해야 한다)에서, 'from somewhere(어디선가)'의 막연함이 다급함을 드러낸다. 풍요를 외치던 농장이 정작 곡물을 어디서든 끌어와야 하는 처지가 된 것이다.", "sid": "c7s004"}, {"word": "ceremonial", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌserɪˈməʊniəl/", "mean": "의례적인, 격식을 갖춘", "ctx": "In these days Napoleon rarely appeared in public, but spent all his time in the farmhouse, which was guarded at each door by fierce-looking dogs. When he did emerge, it was in a ⟦ceremonial⟧ manner, with an escort of six dogs who closely surrounded him and growled if anyone came too near.", "marked": true, "note": "격식과 절차를 갖춘 의식 같은 모양새를 뜻한다. it was in a ceremonial manner, with an escort of six dogs(여섯 마리 개를 호위로 거느린 의례적인 방식으로)에서, 평범한 등장이 군주의 행차처럼 연출된다. Napoleon이 더는 동료가 아니라 떠받들어지는 권력자가 되었음을 보여 주는 단어다.", "sid": "c7s004"}, {"word": "escort", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈeskɔːt/", "mean": "호위(대), 수행원", "ctx": "In these days Napoleon rarely appeared in public, but spent all his time in the farmhouse, which was guarded at each door by fierce-looking dogs. When he did emerge, it was in a ceremonial manner, with an ⟦escort⟧ of six dogs who closely surrounded him and growled if anyone came too near.", "marked": true, "note": "누군가를 보호하거나 격식을 위해 따라붙는 무리를 뜻한다. with an escort of six dogs who closely surrounded him(그를 바짝 둘러싼 여섯 마리 개의 호위와 함께)에서, 호위는 보호인 동시에 위협이다. 가까이 오면 으르렁대는 개들은, 지도자와 동물들 사이를 갈라놓는 살아 있는 장벽이다.", "sid": "c7s004"}, {"word": "surrender", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/səˈrendə/", "mean": "내놓다, 넘겨주다, 항복하다", "ctx": "Frequently he did not even appear on Sunday mornings, but issued his orders through one of the other pigs, usually Squealer.One Sunday morning Squealer announced that the hens, who had just come in to lay again, must ⟦surrender⟧ their eggs.", "marked": true, "note": "가진 것을 내주거나 항복한다는 뜻이다. the hens ... must surrender their eggs(암탉들은 알을 내놓아야 한다)에서, '빼앗다'가 아니라 '내놓다'라는 완곡한 표현이 쓰였다. 강제 징발을 마치 자발적 양도처럼 보이게 하는 언어의 포장이다.", "sid": "c7s004"}, {"word": "contract", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkɒntrækt/", "mean": "계약", "ctx": "Napoleon had accepted, through Whymper, a ⟦contract⟧ for four hundred eggs a week. The price of these would pay for enough grain and meal to keep the farm going till summer came on and conditions were easier.", "marked": true, "note": "법적·상업적 약정을 뜻한다. a contract for four hundred eggs a week(주당 400개의 알을 대는 계약)에서, 동물들의 노동과 산물이 인간 세계의 상거래 대상이 된다. 인간을 몰아낸 혁명이, 이제 인간과 계약을 맺어 제 식구의 알을 팔아넘기는 역설이 담긴 단어다.", "sid": "c7s004"}, {"word": "expulsion", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ɪkˈspʌlʃn/", "mean": "추방, 쫓아냄, 제명", "ctx": "They were just getting their clutches ready for the spring sitting, and they protested that to take the eggs away now was murder. For the first time since the ⟦expulsion⟧ of Jones, there was something resembling a rebellion.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "resembling", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/rɪˈzemblɪŋ/", "mean": "닮은, ~와 비슷한", "ctx": "They were just getting their clutches ready for the spring sitting, and they protested that to take the eggs away now was murder. For the first time since the expulsion of Jones, there was something ⟦resembling⟧ a rebellion.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s005", "base": "resemble — 닮다, ~와 비슷하다"}, {"word": "rafters", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈrɑːftəz/", "mean": "서까래 (지붕 골조)", "ctx": "Led by three young Black Minorca pullets, the hens made a determined effort to thwart Napoleon’s wishes. Their method was to fly up to the ⟦rafters⟧ and there lay their eggs, which smashed to pieces on the floor. Napoleon acted swiftly and ruthlessly.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "orchard", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈɔːtʃəd/", "mean": "과수원", "ctx": "The dogs saw to it that these orders were carried out. For five days the hens held out, then they capitulated and went back to their nesting boxes. Nine hens had died in the meantime. Their bodies were buried in the ⟦orchard⟧, and it was given out that they had died of coccidiosis.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "grocer", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈɡrəʊsə/", "mean": "식료품·잡화 상인", "ctx": "Nine hens had died in the meantime. Their bodies were buried in the orchard, and it was given out that they had died of coccidiosis. Whymper heard nothing of this affair, and the eggs were duly delivered, a ⟦grocer⟧’s van driving up to the farm once a week to take them away.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "pullets", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈpʊlɪts/", "mean": "어린 암탉", "ctx": "For the first time since the expulsion of Jones, there was something resembling a rebellion. Led by three young Black Minorca ⟦pullets⟧, the hens made a determined effort to thwart Napoleon’s wishes.", "marked": true, "note": "보통 한 살 미만으로 갓 알을 낳기 시작한 암탉. ‘Black Minorca pullets’ = 검은 미노르카종 어린 암탉들.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "coccidiosis", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌkɒksɪdiˈəʊsɪs/", "mean": "콕시듐증 (가금의 장 질환)", "ctx": "The dogs saw to it that these orders were carried out. For five days the hens held out, then they capitulated and went back to their nesting boxes. Nine hens had died in the meantime. Their bodies were buried in the orchard, and it was given out that they had died of ⟦coccidiosis⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "닭에게 흔한 기생충성 장병. 굶겨 죽인 암탉들의 사인으로 둘러댄 거짓 핑계.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "outcry", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈaʊtkraɪ/", "mean": "강한 항의, 격렬한 반발, 부르짖음", "ctx": "When the hens heard this, they raised a terrible ⟦outcry⟧. They had been warned earlier that this sacrifice might be necessary, but had not believed that it would really happen.", "marked": true, "note": "분노나 항의가 터져 나오는 외침을 뜻한다. they raised a terrible outcry(그들은 끔찍한 항의를 터뜨렸다)에서, 알을 빼앗기게 된 암탉들의 절박한 분노가 담긴다. 이것은 Jones 추방 이후 농장에서 처음 일어난, 권력을 향한 정면 저항의 신호다.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "clutch", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/klʌtʃ/", "mean": "한 배에 낳은 알, 한배 알", "ctx": "They had been warned earlier that this sacrifice might be necessary, but had not believed that it would really happen. They were just getting their ⟦clutches⟧ ready for the spring sitting, and they protested that to take the eggs away now was murder.", "marked": true, "note": "암탉이 한 번에 품는 알 무더기를 뜻한다. They were just getting their clutches ready for the spring sitting(그들은 막 봄에 품을 한배 알을 준비하던 참이었다)에서, 알은 상품이 아니라 새끼가 될 생명이다. 그것을 빼앗기는 일을 암탉들이 murder라 부르는 이유가 여기 있다.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "thwart", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/θwɔːt/", "mean": "좌절시키다, 저지하다", "ctx": "For the first time since the expulsion of Jones, there was something resembling a rebellion. Led by three young Black Minorca pullets, the hens made a determined effort to ⟦thwart⟧ Napoleon’s wishes.", "marked": true, "note": "남의 계획이나 뜻을 가로막아 무산시킨다는 뜻이다. made a determined effort to thwart Napoleon's wishes(Napoleon의 뜻을 꺾으려 단호히 애썼다)에서, 암탉들이 권력의 명령에 정면으로 맞서는 의지가 드러난다. 그러나 이 저항은 곧 잔혹하게 분쇄된다.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "ruthlessly", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈruːθləsli/", "mean": "무자비하게, 가차 없이", "ctx": "Led by three young Black Minorca pullets, the hens made a determined effort to thwart Napoleon’s wishes. Their method was to fly up to the rafters and there lay their eggs, which smashed to pieces on the floor. Napoleon acted swiftly and ⟦ruthlessly⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "자비나 동정 없이 냉혹하게라는 뜻이다. Napoleon acted swiftly and ruthlessly(Napoleon은 신속하고 무자비하게 움직였다)에서, swiftly와 짝을 이루어 망설임 없는 폭력을 압축한다. 굶주림을 무기로 삼아 제 식구를 굴복시키는, 권력의 차가운 효율이 이 부사에 담긴다.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "capitulate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kəˈpɪtʃuleɪt/", "mean": "항복하다, 굴복하다", "ctx": "He ordered the hens’ rations to be stopped, and decreed that any animal giving so much as a grain of corn to a hen should be punished by death. The dogs saw to it that these orders were carried out. For five days the hens held out, then they ⟦capitulated⟧ and went back to their nesting boxes.", "marked": true, "note": "저항을 그만두고 조건에 굴복한다는 뜻이다. then they capitulated and went back to their nesting boxes(그러다 그들은 굴복하여 둥지로 돌아갔다)에서, 닷새의 저항이 결국 무너진 순간을 담는다. 그 사이 아홉 마리가 죽었고, 그 죽음마저 'coccidiosis(병)'로 위장된다.", "sid": "c7s005"}, {"word": "beech", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/biːtʃ/", "mean": "너도밤나무", "ctx": "Napoleon was by this time on slightly better terms with the other farmers than before. It happened that there was in the yard a pile of timber which had been stacked there ten years earlier when a ⟦beech⟧ spinney was cleared.", "marked": true, "note": "단단한 목재로 쓰이는 활엽수. ‘beech spinney’ = 너도밤나무 잡목숲.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "spinney", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈspɪni/", "mean": "작은 잡목 숲, 덤불숲", "ctx": "Napoleon was by this time on slightly better terms with the other farmers than before. It happened that there was in the yard a pile of timber which had been stacked there ten years earlier when a beech ⟦spinney⟧ was cleared.", "marked": true, "note": "英 시골 표현으로, 작은 나무와 관목이 자란 좁은 숲.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "rumoured", "pos": "v. (passive)", "pron": "/ˈruːməd/", "mean": "~라는 소문이 돌다", "ctx": "All this while no more had been seen of Snowball. He was ⟦rumoured⟧ to be hiding on one of the neighbouring farms, either Foxwood or Pinchfield. Napoleon was by this time on slightly better terms with the other farmers than before.", "marked": true, "note": "주로 'be rumoured to ~'의 수동으로 쓰여 '~라는 소문이 있다'는 뜻이다. He was rumoured to be hiding on one of the neighbouring farms(그가 이웃 농장 어딘가에 숨어 있다는 소문이 돌았다)에서, 소문의 출처는 지워지고 떠도는 말만 남는다. Snowball의 '위치'는 사실이 아니라 소문으로만 존재한다.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "seasoned", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈsiːzənd/", "mean": "(목재가) 잘 건조된, 숙성된", "ctx": "It happened that there was in the yard a pile of timber which had been stacked there ten years earlier when a beech spinney was cleared. It was well ⟦seasoned⟧, and Whymper had advised Napoleon to sell it; both Mr. Pilkington and Mr. Frederick were anxious to buy it.", "marked": true, "note": "목재를 충분히 말려 쓸 수 있게 된 상태를 뜻한다. It was well seasoned, and Whymper had advised Napoleon to sell it(그 목재는 잘 말라 있었고, Whymper는 팔라고 조언했다)에서, 잘 마른 목재는 값나가는 상품이다. 이 목재 더미가 이후 Pilkington과 Frederick 사이의 거래를 두고 Snowball의 '위치'를 흔드는 축이 된다.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "anxious (to)", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈæŋkʃəs/", "mean": "~하고 싶어 안달하는, 간절히 바라는", "ctx": "It happened that there was in the yard a pile of timber which had been stacked there ten years earlier when a beech spinney was cleared. It was well seasoned, and Whymper had advised Napoleon to sell it; both Mr. Pilkington and Mr. Frederick were ⟦anxious⟧ to buy it.", "marked": true, "note": "'anxious to + 동사'는 '~하고 싶어 안달이 난'이라는 뜻이다(걱정과는 다른 용법). both Mr. Pilkington and Mr. Frederick were anxious to buy it(Pilkington과 Frederick 둘 다 그것을 사고 싶어 했다)에서, 두 인간 농장주의 경쟁심이 드러난다. Napoleon은 이 경쟁을 이용해 흥정을 저울질한다.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "hesitate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈhezɪteɪt/", "mean": "망설이다, 주저하다", "ctx": "It was well seasoned, and Whymper had advised Napoleon to sell it; both Mr. Pilkington and Mr. Frederick were anxious to buy it. Napoleon was ⟦hesitating⟧ between the two, unable to make up his mind.", "marked": true, "note": "결정을 못 하고 머뭇거린다는 뜻이다. Napoleon was hesitating between the two, unable to make up his mind(Napoleon은 둘 사이에서 망설이며 마음을 정하지 못했다)에서, 그의 흥정 줄다리기가 곧바로 Snowball에 관한 소문을 바꾼다. 거래의 향방에 따라 적의 '소재지'가 옮겨 다닌다.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "incline (toward)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɪnˈklaɪn/", "mean": "~쪽으로 기울다, 마음이 쏠리다", "ctx": "Napoleon was hesitating between the two, unable to make up his mind. It was noticed that whenever he seemed on the point of coming to an agreement with Frederick, Snowball was declared to be in hiding at Foxwood, while, when he ⟦inclined⟧ toward Pilkington, Snowball was said to be at Pinchfield.", "marked": true, "note": "한쪽으로 마음이 기운다는 뜻이다. when he inclined toward Pilkington, Snowball was said to be at Pinchfield(그가 Pilkington 쪽으로 기울면, Snowball은 Pinchfield에 있다고 했다)에서, Napoleon의 기울기와 Snowball의 소재가 반대로 맞물린다. 적은 늘 '거래하지 않는 쪽'에 숨어 있다고 선전된다.", "sid": "c7s006"}, {"word": "trampled", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/ˈtræmpld/", "mean": "짓밟았다", "ctx": "Every night, it was said, he came creeping in under cover of darkness and performed all kinds of mischief. He stole the corn, he upset the milk-pails, he broke the eggs, he ⟦trampled⟧ the seedbeds, he gnawed the bark off the fruit trees.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "seedbeds", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsiːdbedz/", "mean": "모판, 씨 뿌린 밭", "ctx": "Every night, it was said, he came creeping in under cover of darkness and performed all kinds of mischief. He stole the corn, he upset the milk-pails, he broke the eggs, he trampled the ⟦seedbeds⟧, he gnawed the bark off the fruit trees.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "mislaid", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌmɪsˈleɪd/", "mean": "어디 둔지 몰라 잃어버렸다", "ctx": "Curiously enough, they went on believing this even after the ⟦mislaid⟧ key was found under a sack of meal. The cows declared unanimously that Snowball crept into their stalls and milked them in their sleep.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "troublesome", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈtrʌblsəm/", "mean": "성가신, 말썽을 부리는", "ctx": "The cows declared unanimously that Snowball crept into their stalls and milked them in their sleep. The rats, which had been ⟦troublesome⟧ that winter, were also said to be in league with Snowball.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "frequent", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/frɪˈkwent/", "mean": "자주 드나들다, 출몰하다", "ctx": "Suddenly, early in the spring, an alarming thing was discovered. Snowball was secretly ⟦frequenting⟧ the farm by night! The animals were so disturbed that they could hardly sleep in their stalls.", "marked": true, "note": "동사로 쓰이면 '어떤 곳을 자주 찾다·드나들다'라는 뜻이다(형용사 frequent과 강세 위치가 다르다). Snowball was secretly frequenting the farm by night(Snowball이 밤마다 몰래 농장에 드나든다)에서, 추방된 자가 유령처럼 밤에 출몰한다는 공포가 만들어진다. 증거는 없지만 '드나든다'는 말만으로 분위기가 잡힌다.", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "mischief", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈmɪstʃɪf/", "mean": "해코지, 못된 짓, 피해", "ctx": "Snowball was secretly frequenting the farm by night! The animals were so disturbed that they could hardly sleep in their stalls. Every night, it was said, he came creeping in under cover of darkness and performed all kinds of ⟦mischief⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "남에게 해를 끼치는 짓을 뜻한다. performed all kinds of mischief(온갖 해코지를 저질렀다)에서, 곡식을 훔치고 우유통을 엎고 알을 깨는 등 농장의 모든 사고가 Snowball 한 사람의 소행으로 돌려진다. 추상적인 '해코지'가 구체적 사건 목록으로 이어지며 죄목이 불어난다.", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "attribute (to)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈtrɪbjuːt/", "mean": "~의 탓으로 돌리다, ~의 소행으로 보다", "ctx": "He stole the corn, he upset the milk-pails, he broke the eggs, he trampled the seedbeds, he gnawed the bark off the fruit trees. Whenever anything went wrong it became usual to ⟦attribute⟧ it to Snowball.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 일의 원인·책임을 누구·무엇에게 돌린다는 뜻이다. it became usual to attribute it to Snowball(그것을 Snowball의 탓으로 돌리는 것이 으레 그러했다)에서, 원인을 따지지 않고 모든 잘못을 한 사람에게 떠넘기는 습관이 자리 잡는다. 이것이 희생양 만들기의 작동 방식이다.", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "gnaw", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/nɔː/", "mean": "(이로) 갉다, 쏠다", "ctx": "Every night, it was said, he came creeping in under cover of darkness and performed all kinds of mischief. He stole the corn, he upset the milk-pails, he broke the eggs, he trampled the seedbeds, he ⟦gnawed⟧ the bark off the fruit trees.", "marked": true, "note": "이로 조금씩 갉아 낸다는 뜻이다(g는 묵음). he gnawed the bark off the fruit trees(그가 과일나무 껍질을 갉아 벗겼다)에서, 사소하고 잡다한 피해까지 모두 Snowball의 죄목에 더해진다. 동사들의 나열이 길어질수록, 한 사람에게 씌워진 혐의는 비현실적으로 부풀어 오른다.", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "unanimously", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/juˈnænɪməsli/", "mean": "만장일치로, 이구동성으로", "ctx": "Curiously enough, they went on believing this even after the mislaid key was found under a sack of meal. The cows declared ⟦unanimously⟧ that Snowball crept into their stalls and milked them in their sleep.", "marked": true, "note": "모두가 한목소리로라는 뜻이다. The cows declared unanimously that Snowball crept into their stalls and milked them in their sleep(소들은 Snowball이 자기들 우리에 기어들어 잠든 새 젖을 짜 갔다고 이구동성으로 단언했다)에서, '만장일치'가 진실을 보증하기는커녕 집단의 망상이 얼마나 견고해질 수 있는지를 보여 준다.", "sid": "c7s007"}, {"word": "respectful", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/rɪˈspektfl/", "mean": "공손한, 경의를 표하는", "ctx": "Napoleon decreed that there should be a full investigation into Snowball’s activities. With his dogs in attendance he set out and made a careful tour of inspection of the farm buildings, the other animals following at a ⟦respectful⟧ distance.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "henhouses", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈhenhaʊzɪz/", "mean": "닭장 (복수)", "ctx": "At every few steps Napoleon stopped and snuffed the ground for traces of Snowball’s footsteps, which, he said, he could detect by the smell. He snuffed in every corner, in the barn, in the cow-shed, in the ⟦henhouses⟧, in the vegetable garden, and found traces of Snowball almost everywhere.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "snout", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/snaʊt/", "mean": "(돼지 등의) 주둥이, 코", "ctx": "He snuffed in every corner, in the barn, in the cow-shed, in the henhouses, in the vegetable garden, and found traces of Snowball almost everywhere. He would put his ⟦snout⟧ to the ground, give several deep sniffs, ad exclaim in a terrible voice, “Snowball! He has been here!", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "frightened", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈfraɪtnd/", "mean": "겁먹은, 놀란", "ctx": "He would put his snout to the ground, give several deep sniffs, ad exclaim in a terrible voice, “Snowball! He has been here! I can smell him distinctly!” and at the word “Snowball” all the dogs let out blood-curdling growls and showed their side teeth.The animals were thoroughly ⟦frightened⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "decree", "pos": "v./n.", "pron": "/dɪˈkriː/", "mean": "(공식적으로) 명령하다, 포고하다; 칙령", "ctx": "Napoleon ⟦decreed⟧ that there should be a full investigation into Snowball’s activities. With his dogs in attendance he set out and made a careful tour of inspection of the farm buildings, the other animals following at a respectful distance.", "marked": true, "note": "위에서 일방적으로 내리는 공식 명령을 뜻한다. Napoleon decreed that there should be a full investigation(Napoleon은 전면 조사가 있어야 한다고 포고했다)에서, 토론이나 표결이 아니라 단 한 사람의 '명령'으로 절차가 시작된다. decree라는 단어 자체가 권력이 한 곳에 집중되었음을 알려 준다.", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "snuff", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/snʌf/", "mean": "코로 킁킁 냄새 맡다", "ctx": "With his dogs in attendance he set out and made a careful tour of inspection of the farm buildings, the other animals following at a respectful distance. At every few steps Napoleon stopped and ⟦snuffed⟧ the ground for traces of Snowball’s footsteps, which, he said, he could detect by the smell.", "marked": true, "note": "코를 들이대고 냄새를 맡는다는 뜻이다. Napoleon stopped and snuffed the ground for traces of Snowball's footsteps(Napoleon은 멈춰 서서 Snowball의 발자국 흔적을 찾아 땅을 킁킁거렸다)에서, 지도자가 개처럼 땅에 코를 박는 우스꽝스러운 모습과, 그 행위가 자아내는 공포가 기묘하게 겹친다. 냄새는 증거가 아니지만, 그가 맡았다고 하면 증거가 된다.", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "blood-curdling", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈblʌdˌkɜːdlɪŋ/", "mean": "피가 얼어붙는, 소름 끼치는", "ctx": "He would put his snout to the ground, give several deep sniffs, ad exclaim in a terrible voice, “Snowball! He has been here! I can smell him distinctly!” and at the word “Snowball” all the dogs let out ⟦blood-curdling⟧ growls and showed their side teeth.The animals were thoroughly frightened.", "marked": true, "note": "'피를 응고시키는(curdle)'이라는 과장에서 온 말로, 극도의 공포를 뜻한다. all the dogs let out blood-curdling growls(개들이 모두 소름 끼치는 으르렁 소리를 냈다)에서, Napoleon이 'Snowball'이라는 이름을 말할 때마다 개들의 위협이 따라붙는다. 이름과 폭력이 한 쌍으로 묶여, 그 이름을 입에 올리는 것조차 위험해진다.", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "pervade", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/pəˈveɪd/", "mean": "(구석구석) 스며들다, 만연하다", "ctx": "and at the word “Snowball” all the dogs let out blood-curdling growls and showed their side teeth.The animals were thoroughly frightened. It seemed to them as though Snowball were some kind of invisible influence, ⟦pervading⟧ the air about them and menacing them with all kinds of dangers.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 것이 공간 전체에 가득 퍼져 있다는 뜻이다. some kind of invisible influence, pervading the air about them(그들 주위의 공기에 스며든 보이지 않는 어떤 영향력)에서, Snowball은 사람이 아니라 공기처럼 어디에나 깔린 위협이 된다. 형태가 없기에 피할 수도, 반박할 수도 없는 공포다.", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "menace", "pos": "v./n.", "pron": "/ˈmenəs/", "mean": "위협하다; 위협(적 존재)", "ctx": "and at the word “Snowball” all the dogs let out blood-curdling growls and showed their side teeth.The animals were thoroughly frightened. It seemed to them as though Snowball were some kind of invisible influence, pervading the air about them and ⟦menacing⟧ them with all kinds of dangers.", "marked": true, "note": "위협하거나 위험을 가한다는 뜻이다. menacing them with all kinds of dangers(온갖 위험으로 그들을 위협하면서)에서, 보이지 않는 Snowball이 동물들을 끊임없이 위협하는 존재로 그려진다. 구체적 사건이 아니라 막연한 '온갖 위험'이라는 표현이, 공포를 형체 없이 무한히 키운다.", "sid": "c7s008"}, {"word": "comrades", "pos": "n. (pl., vocative)", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪdz/", "mean": "동지들이여", "ctx": "In the evening Squealer called them together, and with an alarmed expression on his face told them that he had some serious news to report.“⟦Comrades⟧!” cried Squealer, making little nervous skips, “a most terrible thing has been discovered.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "cowshed", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkaʊʃed/", "mean": "외양간, 소 우리", "ctx": "It has all been proved by documents which he left behind him and which we have only just discovered. To my mind this explains a great deal, comrades. Did we not see for ourselves how he attempted — fortunately without success — to get us defeated and destroyed at the Battle of the ⟦Cowshed⟧?”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "alarmed", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/əˈlɑːmd/", "mean": "깜짝 놀란, 불안해하는", "ctx": "In the evening Squealer called them together, and with an ⟦alarmed⟧ expression on his face told them that he had some serious news to report.“Comrades!” cried Squealer, making little nervous skips, “a most terrible thing has been discovered.", "marked": true, "note": "위험을 느껴 불안하고 놀란 상태를 뜻한다. with an alarmed expression on his face(놀란 표정을 한 채)에서, Squealer는 충격적 소식을 전하기에 앞서 먼저 표정으로 분위기를 잡는다. 말의 내용보다 먼저 얼굴이 공포를 연출한다. 선동은 종종 정보가 아니라 연기로 시작된다.", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "plot", "pos": "v./n.", "pron": "/plɒt/", "mean": "음모를 꾸미다; 음모", "ctx": "cried Squealer, making little nervous skips, “a most terrible thing has been discovered. Snowball has sold himself to Frederick of Pinchfield Farm, who is even now ⟦plotting⟧ to attack us and take our farm away from us! Snowball is to act as his guide when the attack begins.", "marked": true, "note": "남몰래 나쁜 일을 꾸민다는 뜻이다. who is even now plotting to attack us(바로 지금 우리를 공격하려 음모를 꾸미고 있는)에서, 'even now(바로 지금)'가 위협을 임박한 것으로 만든다. 멀리 있는 위험이 아니라 이 순간 진행 중인 음모라는 시제가, 즉각적인 공포와 단결을 끌어낸다.", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "in league with", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɪn ˈliːɡ wɪð/", "mean": "~와 결탁한, 한패인", "ctx": "Snowball is to act as his guide when the attack begins. But there is worse than that. We had thought that Snowball’s rebellion was caused simply by his vanity and ambition. But we were wrong, comrades. Do you know what the real reason was? Snowball was ⟦in league with⟧ Jones from the very start!", "marked": true, "note": "남몰래 한편이 되어 결탁했다는 뜻이다. Snowball was in league with Jones from the very start(Snowball은 처음부터 Jones와 결탁해 있었다)에서, 혁명의 영웅이 사실은 적의 첩자였다는 가장 충격적인 거짓말이 나온다. 'from the very start(맨 처음부터)'는 과거 전체를 한꺼번에 다시 칠한다.", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "vanity", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈvænəti/", "mean": "허영심, 자만", "ctx": "Snowball is to act as his guide when the attack begins. But there is worse than that. We had thought that Snowball’s rebellion was caused simply by his ⟦vanity⟧ and ambition. But we were wrong, comrades. Do you know what the real reason was? Snowball was in league with Jones from the very start!", "marked": true, "note": "근거 없는 자기과시·허영을 뜻한다. caused simply by his vanity and ambition(단지 그의 허영심과 야망에서 비롯된)에서, Squealer는 먼저 '예전 설명'을 깎아내린 뒤 더 끔찍한 '진짜 이유'를 내놓는다. 작은 죄를 인정하는 척하다가 더 큰 죄를 씌우는 것은, 한 단계 높인 거짓을 그럴듯하게 만드는 수법이다.", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "prove", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/pruːv/", "mean": "증명하다, 입증하다", "ctx": "But we were wrong, comrades. Do you know what the real reason was? Snowball was in league with Jones from the very start! He was Jones’s secret agent all the time. It has all been ⟦proved⟧ by documents which he left behind him and which we have only just discovered.", "marked": true, "note": "증거로 사실임을 보인다는 뜻이다. It has all been proved by documents ... which we have only just discovered(우리가 방금 발견한 문서들로 모두 입증되었다)에서, '입증'과 '문서'라는 말이 거짓에 사실의 외피를 입힌다. 그러나 그 문서는 누구에게도 보여지지 않는다. 검증할 수 없는 증거는 증거가 아니라 권위의 장식이다.", "sid": "c7s009"}, {"word": "wickedness", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈwɪkɪdnəs/", "mean": "사악함, 악행", "ctx": "The animals were stupefied. This was a ⟦wickedness⟧ far outdoing Snowball’s destruction of the windmill. But it was some minutes before they could fully take it in.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "outdoing", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˌaʊtˈduːɪŋ/", "mean": "능가하는, 앞지르는", "ctx": "The animals were stupefied. This was a wickedness far ⟦outdoing⟧ Snowball’s destruction of the windmill. But it was some minutes before they could fully take it in.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010", "base": "outdo — 능가하다, 앞지르다"}, {"word": "rallied", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/ˈrælid/", "mean": "결집시켰다, 다시 모았다", "ctx": "They all remembered, or thought they remembered, how they had seen Snowball charging ahead of them at the Battle of the Cowshed, how he had ⟦rallied⟧ and encouraged them at every turn, and how he had not paused for an instant even when the pellets from Jones’s gun had wounded his back.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "pellets", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈpelɪts/", "mean": "작은 알갱이; (산탄총의) 산탄", "ctx": "They all remembered, or thought they remembered, how they had seen Snowball charging ahead of them at the Battle of the Cowshed, how he had rallied and encouraged them at every turn, and how he had not paused for an instant even when the ⟦pellets⟧ from Jones’s gun had wounded his back.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "seldom", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈseldəm/", "mean": "거의 ~하지 않다. 드물게", "ctx": "At first it was a little difficult to see how this fitted in with his being on Jones’s side. Even Boxer, who ⟦seldom⟧ asked questions, was puzzled. He lay down, tucked his fore hoofs beneath him, shut his eyes, and with a hard effort managed to formulate his thoughts.“I do not believe that,”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "hoofs", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/hʊfs/", "mean": "발굽 (복수, = hooves)", "ctx": "At first it was a little difficult to see how this fitted in with his being on Jones’s side. Even Boxer, who seldom asked questions, was puzzled. He lay down, tucked his fore ⟦hoofs⟧ beneath him, shut his eyes, and with a hard effort managed to formulate his thoughts.“I do not believe that,”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "lure", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/lʊə/", "mean": "유혹, 미끼", "ctx": "I saw him myself. Did we not give him ‘Animal Hero, first Class,’ immediately afterwards?”“That was our mistake, comrade. For we know now — it is all written down in the secret documents that we have found — that in reality he was trying to ⟦lure⟧ us to our doom.”“But he was wounded,” said Boxer.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "sank", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/sæŋk/", "mean": "가라앉았다 (sink의 과거)", "ctx": "And do you not remember, too, that it was just at that moment, when panic was spreading and all seemed lost, that Comrade Napoleon sprang forward with a cry of ‘Death to Humanity!’ and ⟦sank⟧ his teeth in Jones’s leg? Surely you remember THAT, comrades?”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "frisking", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈfrɪskɪŋ/", "mean": "깡충거리며 뛰노는", "ctx": "Surely you remember THAT, comrades?” exclaimed Squealer, ⟦frisking⟧ from side to side.Now when Squealer described the scene so graphically, it seemed to the animals that they did remember it. At any rate, they remembered that at the critical moment of the battle Snowball had turned to flee.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010", "base": "frisk — 깡충거리며 뛰놀다"}, {"word": "graphically", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈɡræfɪkli/", "mean": "생생하게, 눈에 보이듯", "ctx": "Surely you remember THAT, comrades?” exclaimed Squealer, frisking from side to side.Now when Squealer described the scene so ⟦graphically⟧, it seemed to the animals that they did remember it. At any rate, they remembered that at the critical moment of the battle Snowball had turned to flee.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "uneasy", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ʌnˈiːzi/", "mean": "불안한, 께름칙한, 마음이 편치 않은", "ctx": "At any rate, they remembered that at the critical moment of the battle Snowball had turned to flee. But Boxer was still a little ⟦uneasy⟧.“I do not believe that Snowball was a traitor at the beginning,” he said finally. “What he has done since is different.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "traitor", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtreɪtə/", "mean": "배신자, 반역자", "ctx": "At any rate, they remembered that at the critical moment of the battle Snowball had turned to flee. But Boxer was still a little uneasy.“I do not believe that Snowball was a ⟦traitor⟧ at the beginning,” he said finally. “What he has done since is different.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "twinkling", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈtwɪŋklɪŋ/", "mean": "반짝이는", "ctx": "said Boxer. “If Comrade Napoleon says it, it must be right.”“That is the true spirit, comrade!” cried Squealer, but it was noticed he cast a very ugly look at Boxer with his little ⟦twinkling⟧ eyes.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "stupefied", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈstjuːpɪfaɪd/", "mean": "멍해진, 어안이 벙벙한", "ctx": "The animals were ⟦stupefied⟧. This was a wickedness far outdoing Snowball’s destruction of the windmill. But it was some minutes before they could fully take it in.", "marked": true, "note": "충격으로 생각이 마비된 상태를 뜻한다. The animals were stupefied(동물들은 어안이 벙벙했다)에서, 너무 큰 거짓 앞에서 동물들은 따지기보다 먼저 멍해진다. 충격은 사고를 멈추게 하고, 멈춘 사고는 거짓을 검증하지 못한다. 선동이 노리는 것은 바로 이 마비의 순간이다.", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "formulate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈfɔːmjuleɪt/", "mean": "(생각을) 정리해 표현하다, 형성하다", "ctx": "At first it was a little difficult to see how this fitted in with his being on Jones’s side. Even Boxer, who seldom asked questions, was puzzled. He lay down, tucked his fore hoofs beneath him, shut his eyes, and with a hard effort managed to ⟦formulate⟧ his thoughts.“I do not believe that,”", "marked": true, "note": "막연한 생각을 또렷한 말로 정리한다는 뜻이다. with a hard effort managed to formulate his thoughts(힘겨운 노력으로 가까스로 자기 생각을 정리해 냈다)에서, Boxer는 자기가 직접 본 것을 말로 옮기기 위해 안간힘을 쓴다. 그의 저항은 영리해서가 아니라, 본 것을 끝까지 붙들려는 우직함에서 나온다.", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "graze", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɡreɪz/", "mean": "스치다, 살짝 긁히게 하다", "ctx": "For we know now — it is all written down in the secret documents that we have found — that in reality he was trying to lure us to our doom.”“But he was wounded,” said Boxer. “We all saw him running with blood.”“That was part of the arrangement!” cried Squealer. “Jones’s shot only ⟦grazed⟧ him.", "marked": true, "note": "총알 등이 살갗을 스치고 지나간다는 뜻이다. Jones's shot only grazed him(Jones의 총알은 그를 스치기만 했다)에서, Squealer는 Boxer가 직접 본 부상('피 흘리며 달리던 모습')을 '계획의 일부'로 재해석한다. 실제 상처조차 거짓의 증거로 뒤집는, 사실의 역전이 일어난다.", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "categorically", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˌkætəˈɡɒrɪkli/", "mean": "단정적으로, 명백히", "ctx": "announced Squealer, speaking very slowly and firmly, “has stated ⟦categorically⟧ — categorically, comrade — that Snowball was Jones’s agent from the very beginning — yes, and from long before the Rebellion was ever thought of.”“Ah, that is different!” said Boxer.", "marked": true, "note": "의심의 여지 없이 단호하게라는 뜻이다. has stated categorically — categorically, comrade(단정적으로 진술했습니다. 단정적으로 말입니다. 동무)에서, Squealer는 이 단어를 반복함으로써 근거 대신 단정의 무게로 밀어붙인다. 증명할 수 없을 때, 권위는 '단호함' 그 자체를 증거로 내민다.", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "lurk", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/lɜːk/", "mean": "숨어서 도사리다, 잠복하다", "ctx": "He turned to go, then paused and added impressively: “I warn every animal on this farm to keep his eyes very wide open. For we have reason to think that some of Snowball’s secret agents are ⟦lurking⟧ among us at this moment!”", "marked": true, "note": "남몰래 숨어 기회를 노린다는 뜻이다. some of Snowball's secret agents are lurking among us at this moment(Snowball의 비밀 첩자 일부가 바로 지금 우리 가운데 숨어 있다)에서, 위협은 마침내 농장 안으로 옮겨 온다. 적이 '우리 가운데' 있다는 경고가, 곧 닥칠 숙청의 공포를 미리 깔아 둔다.", "sid": "c7s010"}, {"word": "assemble", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈsembl/", "mean": "모이다, 집결하다", "ctx": "Four days later, in the late afternoon, Napoleon ordered all the animals to ⟦assemble⟧ in the yard.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "shivers", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈʃɪvəz/", "mean": "오싹함, 몸서리", "ctx": "When they were all gathered together, Napoleon emerged from the farmhouse, wearing both his medals (for he had recently awarded himself “Animal Hero, First Class”, and “Animal Hero, Second Class”), with his nine huge dogs frisking round him and uttering growls that sent ⟦shivers⟧ down all the animals’ spines.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "flung", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/flʌŋ/", "mean": "(세게) 내던졌다 (fling의 과거)", "ctx": "The pigs’ ears were bleeding, the dogs had tasted blood, and for a few moments they appeared to go quite mad. To the amazement of everybody, three of them ⟦flung⟧ themselves upon Boxer. Boxer saw them coming and put out his great hoof, caught a dog in mid-air, and pinned him to the ground.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "hoof", "pos": "n. (pl. hoofs/hooves)", "pron": "/huːf/", "mean": "(말·소 등의) 발굽", "ctx": "The pigs’ ears were bleeding, the dogs had tasted blood, and for a few moments they appeared to go quite mad. To the amazement of everybody, three of them flung themselves upon Boxer. Boxer saw them coming and put out his great ⟦hoof⟧, caught a dog in mid-air, and pinned him to the ground.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "whereat", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/weərˈæt/", "mean": "그러자, 그 말에 (고어)", "ctx": "Boxer looked at Napoleon to know whether he should crush the dog to death or let it go. Napoleon appeared to change countenance, and sharply ordered Boxer to let the dog go, ⟦whereat⟧ Boxer lifted his hoof, and the dog slunk away, bruised and howling.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "slunk", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/slʌŋk/", "mean": "살금살금 달아났다 (slink의 과거)", "ctx": "Boxer looked at Napoleon to know whether he should crush the dog to death or let it go. Napoleon appeared to change countenance, and sharply ordered Boxer to let the dog go, whereat Boxer lifted his hoof, and the dog ⟦slunk⟧ away, bruised and howling.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "bruised", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/bruːzd/", "mean": "멍든, 타박상을 입은", "ctx": "Boxer looked at Napoleon to know whether he should crush the dog to death or let it go. Napoleon appeared to change countenance, and sharply ordered Boxer to let the dog go, whereat Boxer lifted his hoof, and the dog slunk away, ⟦bruised⟧ and howling.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "cower", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈkaʊə/", "mean": "(겁에 질려) 움츠리다, 웅크리다", "ctx": "They all ⟦cowered⟧ silently in their places, seeming to know in advance that some terrible thing was about to happen.Napoleon stood sternly surveying his audience; then he uttered a high-pitched whimper.", "marked": true, "note": "두려움에 몸을 움츠린다는 뜻이다. They all cowered silently in their places(그들은 모두 제자리에서 말없이 움츠렸다)에서, 무슨 일이 벌어질지 알기도 전에 동물들은 이미 굴종의 자세를 취한다. 공포가 명령보다 먼저 몸을 길들였음을 한 단어가 보여 준다.", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "survey", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/səˈveɪ/", "mean": "(전체를) 둘러보다, 살피다", "ctx": "They all cowered silently in their places, seeming to know in advance that some terrible thing was about to happen.Napoleon stood sternly ⟦surveying⟧ his audience; then he uttered a high-pitched whimper.", "marked": true, "note": "위에서 전체를 훑어본다는 뜻이다. Napoleon stood sternly surveying his audience(Napoleon은 엄숙하게 서서 청중을 둘러보았다)에서, 동물들이 '청중(audience)'으로 불리는 것이 의미심장하다. 처형은 정의의 집행이 아니라, 관객 앞에서 연출되는 한 편의 공연이다.", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "whimper", "pos": "n./v.", "pron": "/ˈwɪmpə/", "mean": "낑낑거리는 소리; 훌쩍이다", "ctx": "They all cowered silently in their places, seeming to know in advance that some terrible thing was about to happen.Napoleon stood sternly surveying his audience; then he uttered a high-pitched ⟦whimper⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "작고 가는 소리를 뜻한다. he uttered a high-pitched whimper(그는 높고 가는 소리를 냈다)에서, 학살을 부르는 신호가 거창한 호령이 아니라 작은 낑낑 소리라는 점이 서늘하다. 5장에서 Snowball을 쫓아낼 때 낸 바로 그 소리이며, 이제 그것은 공포의 신호로 굳었다.", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "pin (down)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/pɪn/", "mean": "꼼짝 못하게 누르다, 제압하다", "ctx": "The pigs’ ears were bleeding, the dogs had tasted blood, and for a few moments they appeared to go quite mad. To the amazement of everybody, three of them flung themselves upon Boxer. Boxer saw them coming and put out his great hoof, caught a dog in mid-air, and ⟦pinned⟧ him to the ground.", "marked": true, "note": "힘으로 눌러 움직이지 못하게 한다는 뜻이다. caught a dog in mid-air, and pinned him to the ground(개를 공중에서 붙잡아 땅에 짓눌렀다)에서, Boxer의 압도적 힘이 드러난다. 그는 마음만 먹으면 개를 죽일 수 있었다. 그러나 그 힘조차 지도자의 명령 한마디 앞에서 멈춘다. 힘이 충성에 종속된다.", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "countenance", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkaʊntənəns/", "mean": "안색, 표정, 얼굴", "ctx": "Boxer looked at Napoleon to know whether he should crush the dog to death or let it go. Napoleon appeared to change ⟦countenance⟧, and sharply ordered Boxer to let the dog go, whereat Boxer lifted his hoof, and the dog slunk away, bruised and howling.", "marked": true, "note": "얼굴빛·표정을 뜻하는 문어적 단어다. Napoleon appeared to change countenance(Napoleon은 안색이 변하는 듯했다)에서, Boxer의 압도적 힘을 본 순간 그의 표정이 흔들린다. 폭군이 자기 무력의 한계를 잠시 깨닫는 순간이며, 그래서 그는 개를 풀어 주라 서둘러 명령한다. 두려움은 동물들만의 것이 아니다.", "sid": "c7s011"}, {"word": "tumult", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtjuːmʌlt/", "mean": "소란, 소동", "ctx": "Presently the ⟦tumult⟧ died down. The four pigs waited, trembling, with guilt written on every line of their countenances. Napoleon now called upon them to confess their crimes. They were the same four pigs as had protested when Napoleon abolished the Sunday Meetings.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "trembling", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈtremblɪŋ/", "mean": "떠는, 벌벌 떨리는", "ctx": "Presently the tumult died down. The four pigs waited, ⟦trembling⟧, with guilt written on every line of their countenances. Napoleon now called upon them to confess their crimes. They were the same four pigs as had protested when Napoleon abolished the Sunday Meetings.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012", "base": "tremble — 떨다, 벌벌 떨다"}, {"word": "countenances", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkaʊntənənsɪz/", "mean": "얼굴 표정", "ctx": "Presently the tumult died down. The four pigs waited, trembling, with guilt written on every line of their ⟦countenances⟧. Napoleon now called upon them to confess their crimes. They were the same four pigs as had protested when Napoleon abolished the Sunday Meetings.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "abolished", "pos": "v. (past part.)", "pron": "/əˈbɒlɪʃt/", "mean": "폐지된, 영원히 제거된", "ctx": "Presently the tumult died down. The four pigs waited, trembling, with guilt written on every line of their countenances. Napoleon now called upon them to confess their crimes. They were the same four pigs as had protested when Napoleon ⟦abolished⟧ the Sunday Meetings.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012", "base": "abolish — 폐지하다"}, {"word": "tore", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/tɔː/", "mean": "찢었다; 쏜살같이 내달렸다 (tear의 과거)", "ctx": "When they had finished their confession, the dogs promptly ⟦tore⟧ their throats out, and in a terrible voice Napoleon demanded whether any other animal had anything to confess.The three hens who had been the ringleaders in the attempted rebellion over the eggs now came forward and stated that Snowball had appeared to them in a dream and incited them to disobey Napoleon’s orders.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "ringleaders", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈrɪŋliːdəz/", "mean": "주모자, 주동자", "ctx": "When they had finished their confession, the dogs promptly tore their throats out, and in a terrible voice Napoleon demanded whether any other animal had anything to confess.The three hens who had been the ⟦ringleaders⟧ in the attempted rebellion over the eggs now came forward and stated that Snowball had appeared to them in a dream and incited them to disobey Napoleon’s orders.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "urinated", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/ˈjʊərɪneɪtɪd/", "mean": "오줌을 누었다", "ctx": "Then a sheep confessed to having ⟦urinated⟧ in the drinking pool — urged to do this, so she said, by Snowball — and two other sheep confessed to having murdered an old ram, an especially devoted follower of Napoleon, by chasing him round and round a bonfire when he was suffering from a cough.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "bonfire", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbɒnfaɪə/", "mean": "모닥불, 큰 화톳불", "ctx": "Then a sheep confessed to having urinated in the drinking pool — urged to do this, so she said, by Snowball — and two other sheep confessed to having murdered an old ram, an especially devoted follower of Napoleon, by chasing him round and round a ⟦bonfire⟧ when he was suffering from a cough.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "slain", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/sleɪn/", "mean": "살해된, 죽임을 당한 (slay의 과거분사)", "ctx": "They were all ⟦slain⟧ on the spot. And so the tale of confessions and executions went on, until there was a pile of corpses lying before Napoleon’s feet and the air was heavy with the smell of blood, which had been unknown there since the expulsion of Jones.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "confess", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kənˈfes/", "mean": "자백하다, 고백하다", "ctx": "Presently the tumult died down. The four pigs waited, trembling, with guilt written on every line of their countenances. Napoleon now called upon them to ⟦confess⟧ their crimes. They were the same four pigs as had protested when Napoleon abolished the Sunday Meetings.", "marked": true, "note": "잘못을 인정해 털어놓는다는 뜻이다. Without any further prompting they confessed(별다른 강요 없이 그들은 자백했다)에서, '강요 없이'라는 말이 도리어 공포의 깊이를 드러낸다. 매질이 필요 없을 만큼 두려움이 내면화되면, 자백은 자발적인 형식을 띤다. 그러나 그 자발성은 공포가 만든 것이다.", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "collaborate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kəˈlæbəreɪt/", "mean": "(적과) 결탁하다, 협력하다", "ctx": "Without any further prompting they confessed that they had been secretly in touch with Snowball ever since his expulsion, that they had ⟦collaborated⟧ with him in destroying the windmill, and that they had entered into an agreement with him to hand over Animal Farm to Mr. Frederick.", "marked": true, "note": "함께 일한다는 뜻이지만, 여기서는 적과 내통한다는 부정적 의미다. they had collaborated with him in destroying the windmill(그들이 풍차 파괴에서 그와 결탁했다)에서, 동물들은 일어난 적도 없는 일을 자백한다. 죄목은 이미 정해져 있고, 자백은 그 죄목을 채워 넣는 의식일 뿐이다.", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "incite", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɪnˈsaɪt/", "mean": "선동하다, 부추기다", "ctx": "When they had finished their confession, the dogs promptly tore their throats out, and in a terrible voice Napoleon demanded whether any other animal had anything to confess.The three hens who had been the ringleaders in the attempted rebellion over the eggs now came forward and stated that Snowball had appeared to them in a dream and ⟦incited⟧ them to disobey Napoleon’s orders.", "marked": true, "note": "나쁜 행동을 하도록 부추긴다는 뜻이다. Snowball had appeared to them in a dream and incited them to disobey(Snowball이 꿈에 나타나 그들에게 불복종하도록 선동했다)에서, 자백은 꿈속의 일까지 죄목으로 끌어들인다. 현실에서 일어날 수 없는 일조차 자백되면서, 이 재판의 완전한 허구성이 폭로된다.", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "slaughter", "pos": "v./n.", "pron": "/ˈslɔːtə/", "mean": "도살하다, 학살하다; 학살", "ctx": "They, too, were ⟦slaughtered⟧. Then a goose came forward and confessed to having secreted six ears of corn during the last year’s harvest and eaten them in the night.", "marked": true, "note": "짐승을 도살하듯 무자비하게 죽인다는 뜻이다. They, too, were slaughtered(그들 역시 도살되었다)에서, 1장에서 Major가 인간의 죄로 고발했던 바로 그 단어가 이제 동물들 사이에서 되풀이된다. 인간을 몰아낸 혁명이, 인간이 하던 일을 그대로 답습하는 순간이다.", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "retribution", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌretrɪˈbjuːʃn/", "mean": "(가혹한) 응징, 보복", "ctx": "Presently the tumult died down. The four pigs waited, trembling, with guilt written on every line of their countenances. Napoleon now called upon them to confess their crimes. They were the same four pigs as had protested when Napoleon abolished the Sunday Meetings. Without any further prompting the…", "marked": false, "note": "잘못에 대한 가혹한 처벌·보복을 뜻한다(다음 블록 c7s013에 이어짐). 자백과 처형이 거듭되며 a pile of corpses(시체 더미)가 Napoleon의 발치에 쌓이고, the air was heavy with the smell of blood(공기가 피 냄새로 무거웠다). 응징의 외피를 쓴 학살이 농장을 뒤덮는다.", "sid": "c7s012"}, {"word": "treachery", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtretʃəri/", "mean": "배신, 반역", "ctx": "When it was all over, the remaining animals, except for the pigs and dogs, crept away in a body. They were shaken and miserable. They did not know which was more shocking — the ⟦treachery⟧ of the animals who had leagued themselves with Snowball, or the cruel retribution they had just witnessed.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "bloodshed", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈblʌdʃed/", "mean": "유혈, 살상", "ctx": "In the old days there had often been scenes of ⟦bloodshed⟧ equally terrible, but it seemed to all of them that it was far worse now that it was happening among themselves. Since Jones had left the farm, until today, no animal had killed another animal. Not even a rat had been killed.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "flock", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/flɒk/", "mean": "(양·새의) 떼, 무리", "ctx": "They had made their way on to the little knoll where the half-finished windmill stood, and with one accord they all lay down as though huddling together for warmth — Clover, Muriel, Benjamin, the cows, the sheep, and a whole ⟦flock⟧ of geese and hens — everyone, indeed, except the cat, who had suddenly disappeared just before Napoleon ordered the animals to assemble.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "fidgeted", "pos": "v. (past part.)", "pron": "/ˈfɪdʒɪtɪd/", "mean": "안절부절 꼼지락거렸다", "ctx": "For some time nobody spoke. Only Boxer remained on his feet. He ⟦fidgeted⟧ to and fro, swishing his long black tail against his sides and occasionally uttering a little whinny of surprise. Finally he said:“I do not understand it. I would not have believed that such things could happen on our farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s013", "base": "fidget — 안절부절 꼼지락거리다"}, {"word": "swishing", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈswɪʃɪŋ/", "mean": "(꼬리를) 휙휙 휘젓는", "ctx": "For some time nobody spoke. Only Boxer remained on his feet. He fidgeted to and fro, ⟦swishing⟧ his long black tail against his sides and occasionally uttering a little whinny of surprise. Finally he said:“I do not understand it. I would not have believed that such things could happen on our farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s013", "base": "swish — (꼬리를) 휙휙 휘젓다"}, {"word": "whinny", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈwɪni/", "mean": "(말의) 가벼운 울음, 히힝 소리", "ctx": "For some time nobody spoke. Only Boxer remained on his feet. He fidgeted to and fro, swishing his long black tail against his sides and occasionally uttering a little ⟦whinny⟧ of surprise. Finally he said:“I do not understand it. I would not have believed that such things could happen on our farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "creep", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/kriːp/", "mean": "살금살금 기어가다, 슬그머니 움직이다", "ctx": "When it was all over, the remaining animals, except for the pigs and dogs, crept away in a body. They were shaken and miserable. They did not know which was more shocking — the treachery of the animals who had leagued themselves with Snowball, or the cruel retribution they had just witnessed. In the…", "marked": false, "note": "소리 없이 조용히 움직인다는 뜻이다. the remaining animals ... crept away in a body(남은 동물들이 무리 지어 슬그머니 물러났다)에서, 학살의 핏자국에서 말없이 빠져나가는 동물들의 모습이 그려진다. 항의도 비명도 없이 그저 '기어서' 물러나는 동작이, 이미 꺾여 버린 의지를 보여 준다.", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "knoll", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/nəʊl/", "mean": "작은 언덕, 둔덕", "ctx": "They had made their way on to the little ⟦knoll⟧ where the half-finished windmill stood, and with one accord they all lay down as though huddling together for warmth — Clover, Muriel, Benjamin, the cows, the sheep, and a whole flock of geese and hens — everyone, indeed, except the cat, who had suddenly disappeared just before Napoleon ordered the animals to assemble.", "marked": true, "note": "완만하고 작은 언덕을 뜻한다(k는 묵음). the little knoll where the half-finished windmill stood(반쯤 지어진 풍차가 서 있는 작은 언덕)에서, 동물들은 자기들 희망의 상징인 풍차 곁으로 모인다. 미완의 풍차 아래 몸을 맞대는 장면이, 무너진 이상과 그래도 남은 온기를 동시에 담는다.", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "with one accord", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/wɪð wʌn əˈkɔːd/", "mean": "일제히, 한마음으로", "ctx": "They had made their way on to the little knoll where the half-finished windmill stood, and ⟦with one accord⟧ they all lay down as though huddling together for warmth — Clover, Muriel, Benjamin, the cows, the sheep, and a whole flock of geese and hens — everyone, indeed, except the cat, who had suddenly disappeared just before Napoleon ordered the animals to assemble.", "marked": true, "note": "약속하지 않았는데도 모두가 동시에라는 뜻이다. with one accord they all lay down as though huddling together for warmth(그들은 일제히 몸을 누여 마치 온기를 나누려 모여드는 듯했다)에서, 말이 아니라 몸으로 표현되는 연대가 그려진다. 권력의 강요된 만장일치와 달리, 이것은 본능에서 우러난 진짜 한마음이다.", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "lumbering", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈlʌmbərɪŋ/", "mean": "(육중하게) 느릿느릿 움직이는", "ctx": "I would not have believed that such things could happen on our farm. It must be due to some fault in ourselves. The solution, as I see it, is to work harder. From now onwards I shall get up a full hour earlier in the mornings.”And he moved off at his ⟦lumbering⟧ trot and made for the quarry.", "marked": true, "note": "덩치 큰 것이 둔하고 느리게 움직이는 모양을 뜻한다. he moved off at his lumbering trot and made for the quarry(그는 느릿한 속보로 떠나 채석장으로 향했다)에서, Boxer의 둔중하지만 멈추지 않는 걸음이 그려진다. 그 우직한 움직임이, '더 열심히 일하자'는 그의 비극적 해답을 몸으로 보여 준다.", "sid": "c7s013"}, {"word": "hayfield", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈheɪfiːld/", "mean": "건초밭", "ctx": "Most of Animal Farm was within their view — the long pasture stretching down to the main road, the ⟦hayfield⟧, the spinney, the drinking pool, the ploughed fields where the young wheat was thick and green, and the red roofs of the farm buildings with the smoke curling from the chimneys.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "ploughed", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/plaʊd/", "mean": "(밭을) 갈았다", "ctx": "Most of Animal Farm was within their view — the long pasture stretching down to the main road, the hayfield, the spinney, the drinking pool, the ⟦ploughed⟧ fields where the young wheat was thick and green, and the red roofs of the farm buildings with the smoke curling from the chimneys.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "hillside", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈhɪlsaɪd/", "mean": "산비탈, 언덕 비탈", "ctx": "Never had the farm — and with a kind of surprise they remembered that it was their own farm, every inch of it their own property — appeared to the animals so desirable a place. As Clover looked down the ⟦hillside⟧ her eyes filled with tears.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "overthrow", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈəʊvəθrəʊ/", "mean": "전복, 타도", "ctx": "As Clover looked down the hillside her eyes filled with tears. If she could have spoken her thoughts, it would have been to say that this was not what they had aimed at when they had set themselves years ago to work for the ⟦overthrow⟧ of the human race.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "brood", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/bruːd/", "mean": "한 배의 새끼, 한 둥지의 새끼 떼", "ctx": "If she herself had had any picture of the future, it had been of a society of animals set free from hunger and the whip, all equal, each working according to his capacity, the strong protecting the weak, as she had protected the lost ⟦brood⟧ of ducklings with her foreleg on the night of Major’s speech.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "ducklings", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdʌklɪŋz/", "mean": "새끼 오리", "ctx": "If she herself had had any picture of the future, it had been of a society of animals set free from hunger and the whip, all equal, each working according to his capacity, the strong protecting the weak, as she had protected the lost brood of ⟦ducklings⟧ with her foreleg on the night of Major’s speech.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "foreleg", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈfɔːleɡ/", "mean": "앞다리 (네발짐승의)", "ctx": "If she herself had had any picture of the future, it had been of a society of animals set free from hunger and the whip, all equal, each working according to his capacity, the strong protecting the weak, as she had protected the lost brood of ducklings with her ⟦foreleg⟧ on the night of Major’s speech.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "roamed", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/rəʊmd/", "mean": "돌아다녔다, 배회했다", "ctx": "Instead — she did not know why — they had come to a time when no one dared speak his mind, when fierce, growling dogs ⟦roamed⟧ everywhere, and when you had to watch your comrades torn to pieces after confessing to shocking crimes. There was no thought of rebellion or disobedience in her mind.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "disobedience", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌdɪsəˈbiːdiəns/", "mean": "불복종, 반항", "ctx": "Instead — she did not know why — they had come to a time when no one dared speak his mind, when fierce, growling dogs roamed everywhere, and when you had to watch your comrades torn to pieces after confessing to shocking crimes. There was no thought of rebellion or ⟦disobedience⟧ in her mind.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "needful", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈniːdfl/", "mean": "필요한", "ctx": "There was no thought of rebellion or disobedience in her mind. She knew that, even as things were, they were far better off than they had been in the days of Jones, and that before all else it was ⟦needful⟧ to prevent the return of the human beings.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "toiled", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/tɔɪld/", "mean": "고되게 일했다, 힘써 일했다", "ctx": "Whatever happened she would remain faithful, work hard, carry out the orders that were given to her, and accept the leadership of Napoleon. But still, it was not for this that she and all the other animals had hoped and ⟦toiled⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "prospect", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈprɒspekt/", "mean": "전망, 멀리 내다보이는 경치", "ctx": "The animals huddled about Clover, not speaking. The knoll where they were lying gave them a wide ⟦prospect⟧ across the countryside.", "marked": true, "note": "멀리 펼쳐진 경치, 또는 미래의 전망을 뜻한다. The knoll ... gave them a wide prospect across the countryside(언덕은 그들에게 들판 너머로 펼쳐진 넓은 전망을 주었다)에서, 농장 전체를 굽어보는 시야가 열린다. 'prospect'에는 '미래의 전망'이라는 뜻도 겹쳐, Clover가 곧 떠올릴 '한때 꿈꾸던 미래'와 조용히 호응한다.", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "gild", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɡɪld/", "mean": "금빛으로 물들이다, 금박을 입히다", "ctx": "It was a clear spring evening. The grass and the bursting hedges were ⟦gilded⟧ by the level rays of the sun. Never had the farm — and with a kind of surprise they remembered that it was their own farm, every inch of it their own property — appeared to the animals so desirable a place.", "marked": true, "note": "금빛으로 빛나게 한다는 뜻이다. The grass and the bursting hedges were gilded by the level rays of the sun(풀과 움트는 울타리가 나직한 햇살에 금빛으로 물들었다)에서, 학살 직후의 농장이 역설적으로 가장 아름답게 빛난다. 이 눈부신 풍경이 도리어 잃어버린 것의 크기를 더 사무치게 만든다.", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "desirable", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/dɪˈzaɪərəbl/", "mean": "바람직한, 갖고 싶은, 사랑스러운", "ctx": "It was a clear spring evening. The grass and the bursting hedges were gilded by the level rays of the sun. Never had the farm — and with a kind of surprise they remembered that it was their own farm, every inch of it their own property — appeared to the animals so ⟦desirable⟧ a place.", "marked": true, "note": "탐나고 사랑스럽다는 뜻이다. Never had the farm ... appeared to the animals so desirable a place(농장이 그토록 사랑스러운 곳으로 보인 적이 없었다)에서, 'every inch of it their own property(구석구석이 자기들 소유)'라는 자각이 함께 온다. 자기 것이라는 깨달음과 그것이 변질되었다는 슬픔이, 한 풍경 속에 겹쳐진다.", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "according to (one's) capacity", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/əˈkɔːdɪŋ tə kəˈpæsəti/", "mean": "각자의 능력에 따라", "ctx": "If she herself had had any picture of the future, it had been of a society of animals set free from hunger and the whip, all equal, each working ⟦according⟧ to his capacity, the strong protecting the weak, as she had protected the lost brood of ducklings with her foreleg on the night of Major’s speech.", "marked": true, "note": "저마다의 능력에 맞게라는 뜻이다. each working according to his capacity, the strong protecting the weak(각자 능력에 따라 일하고, 강한 자가 약한 자를 보호하는)에서, Clover가 그렸던 평등 사회의 이상이 압축된다. 이 구절은 사회주의 분배 원리를 떠올리게 하며, 그 이상과 눈앞의 현실 사이의 간극을 더없이 또렷하게 한다.", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "faithful", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈfeɪθfl/", "mean": "충실한, 변함없는", "ctx": "Whatever happened she would remain ⟦faithful⟧, work hard, carry out the orders that were given to her, and accept the leadership of Napoleon. But still, it was not for this that she and all the other animals had hoped and toiled.", "marked": true, "note": "신의를 지켜 변함없다는 뜻이다. Whatever happened she would remain faithful, work hard, carry out the orders(무슨 일이 있어도 그녀는 충실히 남아, 열심히 일하고, 명령을 따르겠다)에서, Clover의 충성은 Boxer와 닮았으되 다르다. 그녀는 환멸을 또렷이 느끼면서도 충성을 택한다. 그 자각 있는 충성이, 도리어 더 깊은 비극을 만든다.", "sid": "c7s014"}, {"word": "tunefully", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈtjuːnfəli/", "mean": "곡조 맞게, 가락 좋게", "ctx": "The other animals sitting round her took it up, and they sang it three times over — very ⟦tunefully⟧, but slowly and mournfully, in a way they had never sung it before.They had just finished singing it for the third time when Squealer, attended by two dogs, approached them with the air of having something important to say.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "comrade", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪd/", "mean": "동지, 동무 (뜻을 같이하는 벗)", "ctx": "He announced that, by a special decree of ⟦Comrade⟧ Napoleon, ‘Beasts of England’ had been abolished. From now onwards it was forbidden to sing it.The animals were taken aback.“Why?” cried Muriel.“It’s no longer needed, comrade,” said Squealer stiffly.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "traitors", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtreɪtəz/", "mean": "배신자, 반역자", "ctx": "cried Muriel.“It’s no longer needed, comrade,” said Squealer stiffly. “‘Beasts of England’ was the song of the Rebellion. But the Rebellion is now completed. The execution of the ⟦traitors⟧ this afternoon was the final act. The enemy both external and internal has been defeated.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "hoisting", "pos": "v. (-ing)", "pron": "/ˈhɔɪstɪŋ/", "mean": "(밧줄·기로) 끌어올리는, 게양하는", "ctx": "which went on for several minutes and put an end to the discussion.So ‘Beasts of England’ was heard no more. In its place Minimus, the poet, had composed another song which began:and this was sung every Sunday morning after the ⟦hoisting⟧ of the flag.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c7s015", "base": "hoist — 끌어올리다, 게양하다"}, {"word": "substitute", "pos": "n./v.", "pron": "/ˈsʌbstɪtjuːt/", "mean": "대신하는 것, 대체물; 대체하다", "ctx": "At last, feeling this to be in some way a ⟦substitute⟧ for the words she was unable to find, she began to sing ‘Beasts of England’.", "marked": true, "note": "무언가를 대신하는 것을 뜻한다. feeling this to be in some way a substitute for the words she was unable to find(이것이 어떤 식으로든 그녀가 찾지 못한 말의 대체물이라고 느끼며)에서, Clover는 말로 못 한 것을 노래로 대신한다. 언어를 빼앗긴 자에게 노래는 마지막 표현의 통로다. 그러나 바로 그 통로마저 곧 막힌다.", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "mournfully", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˈmɔːnfli/", "mean": "애처롭게, 구슬프게", "ctx": "The other animals sitting round her took it up, and they sang it three times over — very tunefully, but slowly and ⟦mournfully⟧, in a way they had never sung it before.They had just finished singing it for the third time when Squealer, attended by two dogs, approached them with the air of having something important to say.", "marked": true, "note": "슬픔에 잠겨라는 뜻이다. they sang it three times over ... but slowly and mournfully(그들은 세 번 거듭 불렀으나, 느리고 구슬프게)에서, 한때 희망의 행진곡이던 노래가 이제 장송곡처럼 불린다. 같은 가사가 정반대의 정서로 불리며, 변질된 혁명의 현재가 노래의 곡조 하나에 담긴다.", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "abolish", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/əˈbɒlɪʃ/", "mean": "(제도·관습을) 폐지하다", "ctx": "He announced that, by a special decree of Comrade Napoleon, ‘Beasts of England’ had been ⟦abolished⟧. From now onwards it was forbidden to sing it.The animals were taken aback.“Why?” cried Muriel.“It’s no longer needed, comrade,” said Squealer stiffly.", "marked": true, "note": "법이나 관습을 공식적으로 없앤다는 뜻이다. 'Beasts of England' had been abolished. From now onwards it was forbidden to sing it('Beasts of England'가 폐지되었다. 이제부터 그것을 부르는 것이 금지되었다)에서, 혁명의 찬가가 포고 한 장으로 사라진다. 일요 회의를 '폐지'한 것과 같은 단어가, 이제 노래마저 지운다.", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "taken aback", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ˈteɪkən əˈbæk/", "mean": "깜짝 놀란, 당황한", "ctx": "He announced that, by a special decree of Comrade Napoleon, ‘Beasts of England’ had been abolished. From now onwards it was forbidden to sing it.The animals were ⟦taken aback⟧.“Why?” cried Muriel.“It’s no longer needed, comrade,” said Squealer stiffly.", "marked": true, "note": "예상 못 한 일에 흠칫 놀란다는 뜻이다. The animals were taken aback(동물들은 흠칫 놀랐다)에서, Muriel이 \"왜?\"라고 묻는 짧은 저항이 인다. 그러나 그 미약한 의문은, 곧 양들의 구호에 묻혀 사라진다. 놀라움이 질문이 되려는 순간, 그 질문은 봉쇄된다.", "sid": "c7s015"}, {"word": "bleating", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈbliːtɪŋ/", "mean": "(양·염소의) 매애 우는 소리", "ctx": "But that society has now been established. Clearly this song has no longer any purpose.”Frightened though they were, some of the animals might possibly have protested, but at this moment the sheep set up their usual ⟦bleating⟧ of “Four legs good, two legs bad,”", "marked": true, "note": "양이 우는 소리를 뜻하며, 흔히 분별없는 동조를 비유한다. the sheep set up their usual bleating of \"Four legs good, two legs bad\"(양들이 늘 하던 대로 \"네 발은 좋고 두 발은 나쁘다\"고 매애 울어 댔다)에서, 단순한 구호의 반복이 토론을 압살한다. 생각 없는 합창이 질문을 삼키는 것, 그것이 가장 효율적인 검열이다.", "sid": "c7s015"}], "8": [{"word": "meddle", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈmedl/", "mean": "참견하다, 간섭하다", "ctx": "Clover asked Benjamin to read her the Sixth Commandment, and when Benjamin, as usual, said that he refused to ⟦meddle⟧ in such matters, she fetched Muriel. Muriel read the Commandment for her. It ran: “No animal shall kill any other animal WITHOUT CAUSE.”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "fetched", "pos": "v. (past part.)", "pron": "/fetʃt/", "mean": "가서 가져왔다, 데려왔다", "ctx": "Clover asked Benjamin to read her the Sixth Commandment, and when Benjamin, as usual, said that he refused to meddle in such matters, she ⟦fetched⟧ Muriel. Muriel read the Commandment for her. It ran: “No animal shall kill any other animal WITHOUT CAUSE.”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s001", "base": "fetch — 가서 가져오다, 데려오다"}, {"word": "traitors", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtreɪtəz/", "mean": "배신자, 반역자", "ctx": "But they saw now that the Commandment had not been violated; for clearly there was good reason for killing the ⟦traitors⟧ who had leagued themselves with Snowball.Throughout the year the animals worked even harder than they had worked in the previous year.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "trotter", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtrɒtə(r)/", "mean": "돼지의 발", "ctx": "On Sunday mornings Squealer, holding down a long strip of paper with his ⟦trotter⟧, would read out to them lists of figures proving that the production of every class of foodstuff had increased by two hundred per cent, three hundred per cent, or five hundred per cent, as the case might be.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "foodstuff", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈfuːdstʌf/", "mean": "식료품, 먹을거리", "ctx": "On Sunday mornings Squealer, holding down a long strip of paper with his trotter, would read out to them lists of figures proving that the production of every class of ⟦foodstuff⟧ had increased by two hundred per cent, three hundred per cent, or five hundred per cent, as the case might be.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "decree", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/dɪˈkriː/", "mean": "포고하다, (법으로) 정하다", "ctx": "A few days later, when the terror caused by the executions had died down, some of the animals remembered — or thought they remembered — that the Sixth Commandment ⟦decreed⟧ “No animal shall kill any other animal.”", "marked": true, "note": "공식적인 법으로 정한다는 뜻이다. the Sixth Commandment decreed \"No animal shall kill any other animal\"(여섯 번째 계명은 '어떤 동물도 다른 동물을 죽여서는 안 된다'고 정했다)에서, 계명은 '불변의 법'으로 선포된 것이었다. 그러나 그 불변의 법이 어느새 두 단어가 덧붙은 채 바뀌어 있다. 포고된 것조차 조용히 고쳐진다.", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "square with", "pos": "phr.v.", "pron": "/skweə wɪð/", "mean": "~와 들어맞다, 일치하다", "ctx": "And though no one cared to mention it in the hearing of the pigs or the dogs, it was felt that the killings which had taken place did not ⟦square with⟧ this.", "marked": true, "note": "두 가지가 서로 부합한다는 뜻이다. the killings which had taken place did not square with this(벌어진 살해들이 이것과 들어맞지 않았다)에서, 동물들은 학살이 계명과 모순됨을 어렴풋이 느낀다. 그러나 'no one cared to mention it(아무도 입에 올리려 하지 않았다)'는 말이 곧바로 뒤따른다. 모순을 느끼는 것과 말하는 것은 다르다.", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "slip out of", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/slɪp aʊt əv/", "mean": "~에서 빠져나가다, 슬그머니 사라지다", "ctx": "Muriel read the Commandment for her. It ran: “No animal shall kill any other animal WITHOUT CAUSE.” Somehow or other, the last two words had ⟦slipped⟧ out of the animals’ memory.", "marked": true, "note": "소리 없이 사라진다는 뜻이다. the last two words had slipped out of the animals' memory(마지막 두 단어가 동물들의 기억에서 슬그머니 빠져나갔다)에서, 계명의 조작이 마치 동물들 자신의 기억 탓인 양 그려진다. 능동으로 '누가 고쳤다'가 아니라, 단어가 스스로 '빠져나갔다'는 표현이 책임을 흐린다.", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "tremendous", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/trəˈmendəs/", "mean": "엄청난, 어마어마한", "ctx": "To rebuild the windmill, with walls twice as thick as before, and to finish it by the appointed date, together with the regular work of the farm, was a ⟦tremendous⟧ labour.", "marked": true, "note": "규모나 정도가 막대하다는 뜻이다. was a tremendous labour(엄청난 노역이었다)에서, 두 배로 두꺼운 벽의 풍차를 정해진 날짜까지 다시 짓는 일의 고됨이 강조된다. 그러나 이 막대한 노동의 대가가 무엇인지, 동물들은 묻지 못한다. 노동은 점점 늘고, 그것을 따질 언어는 점점 줄어든다.", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "disbelieve", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˌdɪsbɪˈliːv/", "mean": "믿지 않다, 의심하다", "ctx": "The animals saw no reason to ⟦disbelieve⟧ him, especially as they could no longer remember very clearly what conditions had been like before the Rebellion. All the same, there were days when they felt that they would sooner have had less figures and more food.", "marked": true, "note": "믿기를 거부한다는 뜻이다. The animals saw no reason to disbelieve him(동물들은 그를 믿지 않을 이유를 찾지 못했다)에서, 의심의 근거가 사라진 상태가 그려진다. 'especially as they could no longer remember(특히 더는 기억하지 못했으므로)'가 그 이유다. 비교할 과거를 잃으면, 거짓 통계를 반박할 잣대도 사라진다. 기억의 상실이 곧 비판의 상실이다.", "sid": "c8s001"}, {"word": "retinue", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈretɪnjuː/", "mean": "수행원, 시종단", "ctx": "Napoleon himself was not seen in public as often as once in a fortnight. When he did appear, he was attended not only by his ⟦retinue⟧ of dogs but by a black cockerel who marched in front of him and acted as a kind of trumpeter, letting out a loud “cock-a-doodle-doo” before Napoleon spoke.", "marked": true, "note": "높은 사람을 따르는 무리를 뜻한다. attended not only by his retinue of dogs(개들의 수행단을 거느릴 뿐 아니라)에서, 한때 '동무'였던 지도자가 이제 군주처럼 시종을 거느린다. 평등을 외치던 농장에 궁정의 위계가 들어선다. 단어 하나가 권력의 변질을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c8s002"}, {"word": "trumpeter", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtrʌmpɪtə/", "mean": "나팔수, (등장을 알리는) 선포자", "ctx": "Napoleon himself was not seen in public as often as once in a fortnight. When he did appear, he was attended not only by his retinue of dogs but by a black cockerel who marched in front of him and acted as a kind of ⟦trumpeter⟧, letting out a loud “cock-a-doodle-doo” before Napoleon spoke.", "marked": true, "note": "왕의 등장을 알리는 나팔수를 뜻한다. a black cockerel who marched in front of him and acted as a kind of trumpeter(그 앞에서 행진하며 일종의 나팔수 노릇을 하는 검은 수탉)에서, 수탉의 \"꼬끼오\"가 군주의 등장 팡파르가 된다. 우스꽝스러운 동물의 울음이 거창한 의식이 되는 데서, 권력 연출의 허세와 희극성이 함께 드러난다.", "sid": "c8s002"}, {"word": "apartments", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/əˈpɑːtmənts/", "mean": "(대저택의) 전용 거처, 별실", "ctx": "before Napoleon spoke. Even in the farmhouse, it was said, Napoleon inhabited separate ⟦apartments⟧ from the others. He took his meals alone, with two dogs to wait upon him, and always ate from the Crown Derby dinner service which had been in the glass cupboard in the drawing-room.", "marked": true, "note": "궁전·대저택의 독립된 거처를 뜻하는 격식어다. Napoleon inhabited separate apartments from the others(Napoleon은 다른 이들과 분리된 별실에 거처했다)에서, 'apartments'라는 단어 선택이 농가를 궁전처럼 격상시킨다. 다른 돼지들과도 분리된 거처는, 지도자가 동료들 위로까지 올라섰음을 뜻한다.", "sid": "c8s002"}, {"word": "dinner service", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdɪnə ˌsɜːvɪs/", "mean": "정찬용 식기 세트", "ctx": "before Napoleon spoke. Even in the farmhouse, it was said, Napoleon inhabited separate apartments from the others. He took his meals alone, with two dogs to wait upon him, and always ate from the Crown Derby ⟦dinner service⟧ which had been in the glass cupboard in the drawing-room.", "marked": true, "note": "한 벌로 갖춰진 고급 식기를 뜻한다. always ate from the Crown Derby dinner service(언제나 Crown Derby 정찬 식기로 식사했다)에서, Jones 집안의 고급 도자기가 Napoleon의 일상 식기가 된다. 인간의 사치품을 전유(專有)하는 이 장면은, '인간처럼 되지 말라'던 계명이 이미 안에서부터 무너졌음을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c8s002"}, {"word": "fortnight", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈfɔːtnaɪt/", "mean": "2주, 14일", "ctx": "All orders were now issued through Squealer or one of the other pigs. Napoleon himself was not seen in public as often as once in a ⟦fortnight⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "영국 영어에서 '2주'를 뜻한다(fourteen nights에서 유래). not seen in public as often as once in a fortnight(2주에 한 번도 채 공개석상에 나타나지 않는)에서, 지도자의 부재가 강조된다. 모습을 감출수록 그는 신비롭고 두려운 존재가 된다. 보이지 않음이 곧 권위가 되는, 우상화의 한 방식이다.", "sid": "c8s002"}, {"word": "ducklings", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdʌklɪŋz/", "mean": "새끼 오리", "ctx": "Napoleon was now never spoken of simply as “Napoleon.” He was always referred to in formal style as “our Leader, Comrade Napoleon,” and this pigs liked to invent for him such titles as Father of All Animals, Terror of Mankind, Protector of the Sheep-fold, ⟦Ducklings⟧’ Friend, and the like.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "remark", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/rɪˈmɑːk/", "mean": "발언, 논평", "ctx": "You would often hear one hen ⟦remark⟧ to another, “Under the guidance of our Leader, Comrade Napoleon, I have laid five eggs in six days”; or two cows, enjoying a drink at the pool, would exclaim, “Thanks to the leadership of Comrade Napoleon, how excellent this water tastes!”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "in formal style", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɪn ˈfɔːml staɪl/", "mean": "격식을 갖춘 방식으로, 공식 칭호로", "ctx": "Napoleon was now never spoken of simply as “Napoleon.” He was always referred to ⟦in formal style⟧ as “our Leader, Comrade Napoleon,” and this pigs liked to invent for him such titles as Father of All Animals, Terror of Mankind, Protector of the Sheep-fold, Ducklings’ Friend, and the like.", "marked": true, "note": "정해진 격식과 칭호를 갖춘다는 뜻이다. always referred to in formal style as \"our Leader, Comrade Napoleon\"(언제나 '우리의 지도자 Napoleon 동무'라는 공식 칭호로 불렸다)에서, 이름 하나조차 자유롭게 부를 수 없게 된다. 평범한 'Napoleon'이 사라지고 정해진 호칭만 남는 것은, 언어가 통제되기 시작했다는 신호다.", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "protector", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/prəˈtektə/", "mean": "보호자, 수호자", "ctx": "Napoleon was now never spoken of simply as “Napoleon.” He was always referred to in formal style as “our Leader, Comrade Napoleon,” and this pigs liked to invent for him such titles as Father of All Animals, Terror of Mankind, ⟦Protector⟧ of the Sheep-fold, Ducklings’ Friend, and the like.", "marked": true, "note": "지켜 주는 이를 뜻한다. Father of All Animals, Terror of Mankind, Protector of the Sheep-fold, Ducklings' Friend(만물 동물의 아버지, 인류의 공포, 양 우리의 수호자, 새끼 오리의 친구) 같은 칭호가 줄줄이 붙는다. 거창한 칭호일수록 그 속은 비어 있다. 'Protector'라는 단어가, 실제로는 동물들을 학살한 자에게 붙는 아이러니가 날카롭다.", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "stroke of good fortune", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/strəʊk əv ɡʊd ˈfɔːtʃuːn/", "mean": "뜻밖의 행운, 운수 좋은 일", "ctx": "It had become usual to give Napoleon the credit for every successful achievement and every ⟦stroke of good fortune⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "우연히 찾아온 행운을 뜻한다. to give Napoleon the credit for every successful achievement and every stroke of good fortune(모든 성취와 모든 행운을 Napoleon의 공으로 돌리는)에서, 노력의 결과만이 아니라 우연한 행운까지 지도자의 덕으로 돌려진다. 좋은 일은 모두 그의 공, 나쁜 일은 모두 Snowball의 탓. 인과의 모든 화살이 한 사람을 향해 정렬된다.", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "under the guidance of", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ˈʌndə ðə ˈɡaɪdns əv/", "mean": "~의 지도 아래, ~의 인도로", "ctx": "You would often hear one hen remark to another, “⟦Under the guidance of⟧ our Leader, Comrade Napoleon, I have laid five eggs in six days”; or two cows, enjoying a drink at the pool, would exclaim, “Thanks to the leadership of Comrade Napoleon, how excellent this water tastes!”", "marked": true, "note": "누군가의 이끎을 받는다는 뜻이다. \"Under the guidance of our Leader, Comrade Napoleon, I have laid five eggs in six days\"('우리의 지도자 Napoleon 동무의 지도 아래, 나는 엿새 동안 알 다섯 개를 낳았다')에서, 암탉이 알을 낳은 것조차 지도자 덕분이라 말한다. 일상의 사소한 일까지 권력자에게 공을 돌리는 이 정형구가, 우상화가 언어 깊숙이 스며들었음을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "be well expressed in", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/biː wel ɪkˈsprest ɪn/", "mean": "~에 잘 드러나 있다", "ctx": "Napoleon was now never spoken of simply as “Napoleon.” He was always referred to in formal style as “our Leader, Comrade Napoleon,” and this pigs liked to invent for him such titles as Father of All Animals, Terror of Mankind, Protector of the Sheep-fold, Ducklings’ Friend, and the like. In his spee…", "marked": false, "note": "어떤 감정·생각이 잘 표현되어 있다는 뜻이다. The general feeling on the farm was well expressed in a poem entitled Comrade Napoleon(농장의 전반적 분위기는 'Comrade Napoleon'이라는 시에 잘 드러나 있었다)에서, 강요된 숭배가 마치 '전반적 분위기'인 양 제시된다. 위에서 만든 찬양이 아래에서 우러난 감정처럼 포장되는 지점을, 이 표현이 드러낸다.", "sid": "c8s003"}, {"word": "inscribe", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ɪnˈskraɪb/", "mean": "(벽·비석에) 새기다, 적어 넣다", "ctx": "Napoleon approved of this poem and caused it to be ⟦inscribed⟧ on the wall of the big barn, at the opposite end from the Seven Commandments.", "marked": true, "note": "돌이나 벽에 글자를 새긴다는 뜻이다. caused it to be inscribed on the wall of the big barn(그것이 큰 헛간 벽에 새겨지게 했다)에서, 헌시가 계명과 같은 벽에 영구히 새겨진다. 한때 'Seven Commandments(일곱 계명)'가 새겨졌던 벽에, 이제 지도자 찬가가 함께 오른다. 새겨진 글자는 권위를 갖는다. 무엇을 벽에 새기느냐가 무엇을 신성시하느냐를 보여 준다.", "sid": "c8s004"}, {"word": "at the opposite end", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/æt ði ˈɒpəzɪt end/", "mean": "반대쪽 끝에", "ctx": "Napoleon approved of this poem and caused it to be inscribed on the wall of the big barn, ⟦at the opposite end⟧ from the Seven Commandments.", "marked": true, "note": "맞은편 끝을 뜻한다. at the opposite end from the Seven Commandments(일곱 계명의 반대쪽 끝에)에서, 헌시가 계명과 같은 벽의 맞은편에 놓인다. 혁명의 원칙(계명)과 지도자 숭배(헌시)가 한 벽의 양 끝에서 마주 본다. 곧 그 둘 사이의 긴장은 계명 쪽의 패배로 기운다. 공간 배치가 권력의 이동을 상징한다.", "sid": "c8s004"}, {"word": "surmount", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/səˈmaʊnt/", "mean": "~의 위에 얹다, 꼭대기를 장식하다", "ctx": "It was ⟦surmounted⟧ by a portrait of Napoleon, in profile, executed by Squealer in white paint.Meanwhile, through the agency of Whymper, Napoleon was engaged in complicated negotiations with Frederick and Pilkington.", "marked": true, "note": "무언가의 맨 위에 놓인다는 뜻이다. It was surmounted by a portrait of Napoleon, in profile(그것은 옆모습의 Napoleon 초상으로 위가 장식되었다)에서, 헌시 위에 지도자의 초상이 얹힌다. 글과 그림이 함께 성상(聖像)처럼 배치된다. 지도자의 얼굴이 글 위에 군림하는 이 구도가, 우상화의 시각적 완성이다.", "sid": "c8s004"}, {"word": "in profile", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɪn ˈprəʊfaɪl/", "mean": "옆모습으로, 측면상으로", "ctx": "It was surmounted by a portrait of Napoleon, ⟦in profile⟧, executed by Squealer in white paint.Meanwhile, through the agency of Whymper, Napoleon was engaged in complicated negotiations with Frederick and Pilkington.", "marked": true, "note": "얼굴을 옆에서 본 모습을 뜻한다. a portrait of Napoleon, in profile, executed by Squealer in white paint(흰 페인트로 Squealer가 그린, 옆모습의 Napoleon 초상)에서, '옆모습 초상'은 동전·메달·기념상에 새겨지는 군주와 위인의 전형적 구도다. 지도자를 역사적 위인의 도상(圖像)에 끼워 넣는 이 선택이, 신격화의 시각 언어다.", "sid": "c8s004"}, {"word": "negotiation", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/nɪˌɡəʊʃiˈeɪʃn/", "mean": "협상, 교섭", "ctx": "It was surmounted by a portrait of Napoleon, in profile, executed by Squealer in white paint.Meanwhile, through the agency of Whymper, Napoleon was engaged in complicated ⟦negotiations⟧ with Frederick and Pilkington.", "marked": true, "note": "이해를 조율하는 교섭을 뜻한다. engaged in complicated negotiations with Frederick and Pilkington(Frederick, Pilkington과 복잡한 협상에 들어가 있었다)에서, 'Meanwhile(그러는 동안)'이 우상화의 장면과 외교의 장면을 잇는다. 안으로는 숭배를 키우고 밖으로는 인간들과 거래하는 두 일이 나란히 진행된다. 이 협상이 곧 8장 후반의 배신과 전투로 이어진다.", "sid": "c8s004"}, {"word": "unsold", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˌʌnˈsəʊld/", "mean": "팔리지 않은", "ctx": "The pile of timber was still ⟦unsold⟧. Of the two, Frederick was the more anxious to get hold of it, but he would not offer a reasonable price.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "rumours", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈruːməz/", "mean": "소문, 풍문 (복수)", "ctx": "At the same time there were renewed ⟦rumours⟧ that Frederick and his men were plotting to attack Animal Farm and to destroy the windmill, the building of which had aroused furious jealousy in him. Snowball was known to be still skulking on Pinchfield Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "aroused", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/əˈraʊzd/", "mean": "(감정을) 불러일으켰다, 자극했다", "ctx": "At the same time there were renewed rumours that Frederick and his men were plotting to attack Animal Farm and to destroy the windmill, the building of which had ⟦aroused⟧ furious jealousy in him. Snowball was known to be still skulking on Pinchfield Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "jealousy", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈdʒeləsi/", "mean": "질투, 시기", "ctx": "At the same time there were renewed rumours that Frederick and his men were plotting to attack Animal Farm and to destroy the windmill, the building of which had aroused furious ⟦jealousy⟧ in him. Snowball was known to be still skulking on Pinchfield Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "anxious (to)", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈæŋkʃəs/", "mean": "몹시 ~하고 싶어 하는, 안달하는", "ctx": "The pile of timber was still unsold. Of the two, Frederick was the more ⟦anxious⟧ to get hold of it, but he would not offer a reasonable price.", "marked": true, "note": "여기서는 '걱정하는'이 아니라 '간절히 ~하고 싶어 하는'이라는 뜻이다. Frederick was the more anxious to get hold of it(Frederick이 그것을 손에 넣고 싶어 더 안달이었다)에서, 목재를 둘러싼 두 농장주의 경쟁 심리가 드러난다. 이 안달이 곧 Napoleon이 둘 사이를 저울질하며 값을 올리는 흥정의 지렛대가 된다.", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "skulk", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/skʌlk/", "mean": "(나쁜 의도로) 숨어 다니다, 잠복하다", "ctx": "At the same time there were renewed rumours that Frederick and his men were plotting to attack Animal Farm and to destroy the windmill, the building of which had aroused furious jealousy in him. Snowball was known to be still ⟦skulking⟧ on Pinchfield Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "남몰래 음흉하게 숨어 다닌다는 뜻이다. Snowball was known to be still skulking on Pinchfield Farm(Snowball이 여전히 Pinchfield 농장에 숨어 있는 것으로 알려졌다)에서, 부재한 Snowball이 또다시 '어딘가에 도사린 위협'으로 소환된다. 'was known to be(~으로 알려졌다)'라는 모호한 전언이, 확인되지 않은 소문을 사실처럼 굳힌다.", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "plot (to)", "pos": "n./v.", "pron": "/plɒt/", "mean": "음모; 음모를 꾸미다", "ctx": "At the same time there were renewed rumours that Frederick and his men were ⟦plotting⟧ to attack Animal Farm and to destroy the windmill, the building of which had aroused furious jealousy in him. Snowball was known to be still skulking on Pinchfield Farm.", "marked": true, "note": "은밀한 모의를 뜻한다. they had entered into a plot to murder Napoleon(그들이 Napoleon을 살해할 음모에 가담했다)에서, 암탉들이 '꿈에서 선동당했다'던 7장의 자백이 이번엔 '암살 음모'로 격상된다. 자백의 죄목이 점점 커지는 것은, 공포를 갱신해 숙청과 통제를 지속하기 위함이다.", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "precaution", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/prɪˈkɔːʃn/", "mean": "예방 조치, 경계", "ctx": "In the middle of the summer the animals were alarmed to hear that three hens had come forward and confessed that, inspired by Snowball, they had entered into a plot to murder Napoleon. They were executed immediately, and fresh ⟦precautions⟧ for Napoleon’s safety were taken.", "marked": true, "note": "위험을 막기 위한 사전 조치를 뜻한다. fresh precautions for Napoleon's safety were taken(Napoleon의 안전을 위한 새로운 경계 조치가 취해졌다)에서, '암살 음모'라는 명분이 곧바로 지도자 신변 경비 강화로 이어진다. 공포의 서사는 늘 권력 강화로 회수된다. 위협이 클수록, 보호라는 이름의 통제도 커진다.", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "lest", "pos": "conj.", "pron": "/lest/", "mean": "~하지 않도록, ~할까 봐", "ctx": "They were executed immediately, and fresh precautions for Napoleon’s safety were taken. Four dogs guarded his bed at night, one at each corner, and a young pig named Pinkeye was given the task of tasting all his food before he ate it, ⟦lest⟧ it should be poisoned.", "marked": true, "note": "'~할까 봐 (염려하여)'라는 뜻의 격식 있는 접속사다. a young pig named Pinkeye was given the task of tasting all his food before he ate it, lest it should be poisoned(Pinkeye라는 어린 돼지가 독이 들었을까 봐 그가 먹기 전에 모든 음식을 맛보는 일을 맡았다)에서, 독 시식관(毒味)을 둔다는 군주의 관습이 등장한다. 동무들을 두려워해 시식관을 두는 지도자의 모습이, 그가 이미 동물들과 분리된 폭군임을 드러낸다.", "sid": "c8s005"}, {"word": "distrusted", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/dɪsˈtrʌstɪd/", "mean": "불신했다, 믿지 않았다", "ctx": "The relations between Napoleon and Pilkington, though they were only conducted through Whymper, were now almost friendly. The animals ⟦distrusted⟧ Pilkington, as a human being, but greatly preferred him to Frederick, whom they both feared and hated.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "practised", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/ˈpræktɪst/", "mean": "행했다, (관행으로) 일삼았다", "ctx": "Moreover, terrible stories were leaking out from Pinchfield about the cruelties that Frederick ⟦practised⟧ upon his animals.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "starved", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/stɑːvd/", "mean": "굶주렸다, 굶겨 죽였다", "ctx": "He had flogged an old horse to death, he ⟦starved⟧ his cows, he had killed a dog by throwing it into the furnace, he amused himself in the evenings by making cocks fight with splinters of razor-blade tied to their spurs.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "furnace", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈfɜːnɪs/", "mean": "화덕, 용광로, 소각로", "ctx": "He had flogged an old horse to death, he starved his cows, he had killed a dog by throwing it into the ⟦furnace⟧, he amused himself in the evenings by making cocks fight with splinters of razor-blade tied to their spurs.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "splinters", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈsplɪntəz/", "mean": "가시 같은 조각, 파편", "ctx": "He had flogged an old horse to death, he starved his cows, he had killed a dog by throwing it into the furnace, he amused himself in the evenings by making cocks fight with ⟦splinters⟧ of razor-blade tied to their spurs.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "razor-blade", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈreɪzə bleɪd/", "mean": "면도날", "ctx": "He had flogged an old horse to death, he starved his cows, he had killed a dog by throwing it into the furnace, he amused himself in the evenings by making cocks fight with splinters of ⟦razor-blade⟧ tied to their spurs.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "comrades", "pos": "n. (pl., vocative)", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪdz/", "mean": "동지들이여", "ctx": "The animals’ blood boiled with rage when they heard of these things beingdone to their ⟦comrades⟧, and sometimes they clamoured to be allowed to go out in a body and attack Pinchfield Farm, drive out the humans, and set the animals free.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "rash", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ræʃ/", "mean": "성급한, 경솔한", "ctx": "But Squealer counselled them to avoid ⟦rash⟧ actions and trust in Comrade Napoleon’s strategy.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "comrade", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkɒmreɪd/", "mean": "동지, 동무 (뜻을 같이하는 벗)", "ctx": "The animals’ blood boiled with rage when they heard of these things beingdone to their ⟦comrades⟧, and sometimes they clamoured to be allowed to go out in a body and attack Pinchfield Farm, drive out the humans, and set the animals free.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "it was given out (that)", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɪt wəz ˈɡɪvn aʊt/", "mean": "~라고 발표·공표되었다", "ctx": "At about the same time ⟦it was given out⟧ that Napoleon had arranged to sell the pile of timber to Mr. Pilkington; he was also going to enter into a regular agreement for the exchange of certain products between Animal Farm and Foxwood.", "marked": true, "note": "공식적으로 알려졌다는 뜻의 수동 표현이다. it was given out that Napoleon had arranged to sell the pile of timber to Mr. Pilkington(Napoleon이 목재 더미를 Pilkington에게 팔기로 했다고 공표되었다)에서, 누가 발표했는지는 지워진다. 곧 이 '공표'는 거짓으로 드러나고, 목재는 Frederick에게 팔린다. 공식 발표조차 믿을 수 없는 세계임을, 이 수동 표현이 예고한다.", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "impending", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ɪmˈpendɪŋ/", "mean": "곧 닥칠, 임박한", "ctx": "The animals distrusted Pilkington, as a human being, but greatly preferred him to Frederick, whom they both feared and hated. As the summer wore on, and the windmill neared completion, the rumours of an ⟦impending⟧ treacherous attack grew stronger and stronger.", "marked": true, "note": "나쁜 일이 곧 일어날 듯하다는 뜻이다. the rumours of an impending treacherous attack grew stronger and stronger(임박한 배신적 공격에 대한 소문이 점점 더 거세졌다)에서, 임박감이 긴장을 끌어올린다. 'grew stronger and stronger(점점 더 거세졌다)'의 반복이, 위협이 서서히 조여 오는 분위기를 만든다.", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "bribe", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/braɪb/", "mean": "뇌물로 매수하다", "ctx": "Frederick, it was said, intended to bring against them twenty men all armed with guns, and he had already ⟦bribed⟧ the magistrates and police, so that if he could once get hold of the title-deeds of Animal Farm they would ask no questions.", "marked": true, "note": "돈으로 부정하게 매수한다는 뜻이다. he had already bribed the magistrates and police(그가 이미 치안판사와 경찰을 매수해 두었다)에서, 인간 사회의 사법·치안이 부패해 있음이 드러난다. Frederick의 위협이 단지 무력만이 아니라 매수된 제도까지 동원한다는 점이, 동물들이 의지할 외부의 정의가 없음을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "flog", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/flɒɡ/", "mean": "채찍질하다, 매질하다", "ctx": "He had ⟦flogged⟧ an old horse to death, he starved his cows, he had killed a dog by throwing it into the furnace, he amused himself in the evenings by making cocks fight with splinters of razor-blade tied to their spurs.", "marked": true, "note": "채찍으로 심하게 때린다는 뜻이다. He had flogged an old horse to death(그가 늙은 말을 채찍질해 죽였다)에서, Frederick의 잔혹상이 구체적 목록으로 나열된다. 1장에서 Major가 고발한 인간의 잔혹(채찍)이 여기서 되살아난다. 그러나 독자는 곧, 농장 안의 Boxer도 다른 방식으로 '죽도록 부려진다'는 아이러니를 떠올리게 된다.", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "clamour (to)", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈklæmə/", "mean": "떠들썩하게 요구하다, 아우성치다", "ctx": "The animals’ blood boiled with rage when they heard of these things beingdone to their comrades, and sometimes they ⟦clamoured⟧ to be allowed to go out in a body and attack Pinchfield Farm, drive out the humans, and set the animals free.", "marked": true, "note": "시끄럽게 강하게 요구한다는 뜻이다. they clamoured to be allowed to go out in a body and attack Pinchfield Farm(그들은 떼 지어 나가 Pinchfield 농장을 공격하게 해 달라고 아우성쳤다)에서, 동물들의 분노가 행동의 열망으로 끓어오른다. 그러나 그 분노는 곧 Squealer에 의해 '경솔한 행동을 피하라'며 다시 권력의 통제 아래로 회수된다. 동물들의 정당한 분노조차, 지도자의 '전략'에 종속된다.", "sid": "c8s006"}, {"word": "feeling against (sb)", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ˈfiːlɪŋ əˈɡenst/", "mean": "~에 대한 반감, 적대 감정", "ctx": "Nevertheless, ⟦feeling against⟧ Frederick continued to run high.", "marked": true, "note": "누군가를 향한 집단적 적개심을 가리킨다. feeling against Frederick continued to run high(Frederick에 대한 반감은 계속 높게 끓었다)에서, 이 반감은 동물들 스스로 품은 것이라기보다 선전이 빚어 키운 것이다. 바로 다음 블록들에서 같은 반감이 'Death to Pilkington'으로 손쉽게 방향을 틀게 된다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "run high", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/rʌn haɪ/", "mean": "(감정이) 격해지다, 고조되다", "ctx": "Nevertheless, feeling against Frederick continued to ⟦run high⟧.", "marked": true, "note": "감정이나 긴장이 거세게 치솟는다는 뜻이다. feeling against Frederick continued to run high에서, 반감의 수위가 높이 유지되고 있음을 보여 준다. 이 고조된 감정은 곧 Napoleon의 외교적 줄타기를 가려 줄 연막이 된다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "contemplate", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈkɒntəmpleɪt/", "mean": "(~할 것을) 고려하다, 생각하다", "ctx": "One Sunday morning Napoleon appeared in the barn and explained that he had never at any time ⟦contemplated⟧ selling the pile of timber to Frederick; he considered it beneath his dignity, he said, to have dealings with scoundrels of that description.", "marked": true, "note": "어떤 일을 진지하게 생각하거나 의도한다는 뜻이다. he had never at any time contemplated selling the pile of timber to Frederick(그는 어느 때도 목재를 Frederick에게 팔 생각을 한 적이 없었다)에서, 'never at any time(어느 때도 없이)'이라는 단호한 부정이 거짓을 떠받친다. 곧 그 목재는 정확히 Frederick에게 팔린다. 가장 강하게 부정한 것이 곧 일어날 일이다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "beneath one's dignity", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/bɪˈniːθ ˈdɪɡnəti/", "mean": "품위에 어울리지 않는, 체면에 손상되는", "ctx": "One Sunday morning Napoleon appeared in the barn and explained that he had never at any time contemplated selling the pile of timber to Frederick; he considered it ⟦beneath⟧ his dignity, he said, to have dealings with scoundrels of that description.", "marked": true, "note": "자신의 위신에 걸맞지 않아 하지 않는다는 뜻이다. he considered it beneath his dignity to have dealings with scoundrels of that description(그런 부류의 악당과 거래하는 것은 자신의 품위에 어울리지 않는다고 여겼다)에서, Napoleon은 도덕적 고결함을 가장한다. 며칠 뒤 바로 그 '악당'과 거래했음이 드러날 때, 이 '품위'는 위선의 가면이었음이 폭로된다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "scoundrel", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈskaʊndrəl/", "mean": "악당, 불한당", "ctx": "One Sunday morning Napoleon appeared in the barn and explained that he had never at any time contemplated selling the pile of timber to Frederick; he considered it beneath his dignity, he said, to have dealings with ⟦scoundrels⟧ of that description.", "marked": true, "note": "파렴치한 사람을 경멸조로 부르는 말이다. scoundrels of that description(그런 부류의 악당들)에서, Napoleon은 Frederick을 도덕적으로 단죄한다. 그러나 이 단죄의 언어가 거래 직전에 동원된다는 점에서, 욕설은 진심이 아니라 곧 뒤집힐 입장을 잠시 포장하는 수사일 뿐이다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "tidings", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈtaɪdɪŋz/", "mean": "소식, 기별 (다소 격식체·옛말투)", "ctx": "The pigeons who were still sent out to spread ⟦tidings⟧ of the Rebellion were forbidden to set foot anywhere on Foxwood, and were also ordered to drop their former slogan of “Death to Humanity” in favour of “Death to Frederick.”", "marked": true, "note": "소식을 뜻하는 문어적 단어다. pigeons ... sent out to spread tidings of the Rebellion(혁명의 소식을 퍼뜨리러 보내진 비둘기들)에서, 한때 비둘기는 혁명의 복음을 나르는 전령이었다. 'Beasts of England'를 이웃 농장에 전하던 그 이상주의가, 이제는 'Death to Frederick'이라는 표적 구호를 나르는 도구로 전락한다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "in favour of", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/ɪn ˈfeɪvər əv/", "mean": "~을 (대신) 택하여, ~으로 바꾸어", "ctx": "The pigeons who were still sent out to spread tidings of the Rebellion were forbidden to set foot anywhere on Foxwood, and were also ordered to drop their former slogan of “Death to Humanity” ⟦in favour of⟧ “Death to Frederick.”", "marked": true, "note": "앞의 것을 버리고 뒤의 것을 택한다는 뜻이다. drop their former slogan of “Death to Humanity” in favour of “Death to Frederick”(예전 구호 'Death to Humanity'를 버리고 'Death to Frederick'으로 바꾸다)에서, 보편적 적('인류 전체')이 특정 개인('Frederick')으로 좁혀진다. 혁명의 적이 추상에서 구체적 표적으로 바뀌는 이 순간이, 적을 권력의 필요에 맞춰 재단하는 정치의 시작이다.", "sid": "c8s007"}, {"word": "hitherto", "pos": "adv.", "pron": "/ˌhɪðəˈtuː/", "mean": "지금까지, 이제까지", "ctx": "A gander who had been privy to the plot had confessed his guilt to Squealer and immediately committed suicide by swallowing deadly nightshade berries. The animals now also learned that Snowball had never — as many of them had believed ⟦hitherto⟧ — received the order of “Animal Hero, First Class.”", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "cowshed", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈkaʊʃed/", "mean": "외양간, 소 우리", "ctx": "The animals now also learned that Snowball had never — as many of them had believed hitherto — received the order of “Animal Hero, First Class.” This was merely a legend which had been spread some time after the Battle of the ⟦Cowshed⟧ by Snowball himself.", "marked": true, "note": "", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "nightshade", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˈnaɪtʃeɪd/", "mean": "가지과 독초", "ctx": "The wheat crop was full of weeds, and it was discovered that on one of his nocturnal visits Snowball had mixed weed seeds with the seed corn. A gander who had been privy to the plot had confessed his guilt to Squealer and immediately committed suicide by swallowing deadly ⟦nightshade⟧ berries.", "marked": true, "note": "‘deadly nightshade’는 맹독성 식물(벨라돈나). 한 거위가 이 열매(berries)를 먹고 자살한다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "machinations", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌmækɪˈneɪʃənz/", "mean": "음모, 책략", "ctx": "In the late summer yet another of Snowball’s ⟦machinations⟧ was laid bare. The wheat crop was full of weeds, and it was discovered that on one of his nocturnal visits Snowball had mixed weed seeds with the seed corn.", "marked": true, "note": "비밀스럽고 교활한 계략. ‘Snowball’s machinations’ = Snowball의 농간이라며 둘러댄 것.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "censured", "pos": "v. (past)", "pron": "/ˈsenʃəd/", "mean": "공식적으로 견책당했다", "ctx": "This was merely a legend which had been spread some time after the Battle of the Cowshed by Snowball himself. So far from being decorated, he had been ⟦censured⟧ for showing cowardice in the battle.", "marked": true, "note": "censure는 공식적이고 엄중한 질책. 검열의 censor와 혼동 주의. Snowball이 상을 받기는커녕 비겁했다며 견책당했다는 날조.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "machination", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌmækɪˈneɪʃn/", "mean": "음모, 책략, 흉계", "ctx": "In the late summer yet another of Snowball’s ⟦machinations⟧ was laid bare. The wheat crop was full of weeds, and it was discovered that on one of his nocturnal visits Snowball had mixed weed seeds with the seed corn.", "marked": true, "note": "남을 해치려는 교활한 계략을 뜻한다. yet another of Snowball’s machinations was laid bare(Snowball의 또 하나의 음모가 들춰졌다)에서, 'yet another(또 하나의)'가 Snowball의 죄목이 끝없이 쌓여 감을 강조한다. 부재한 인물에게 무한정 누적되는 이 죄목들이, 그를 만능 희생양으로 만든다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "lay bare (laid bare)", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/leɪ beə/", "mean": "폭로하다, (감춰진 것을) 드러내다", "ctx": "In the late summer yet another of Snowball’s machinations was laid bare. The wheat crop was full of weeds, and it was discovered that on one of his nocturnal visits Snowball had mixed weed seeds with the seed corn. A gander who had been privy to the plot had confessed his guilt to Squealer and immed…", "marked": false, "note": "덮여 있던 것을 벗겨 내 드러낸다는 뜻이다. another of Snowball’s machinations was laid bare에서, 수동태가 '누가 드러냈는지'를 지운다. '발견되었다(laid bare)'는 객관의 외피를 두르지만, 실은 권력이 지어낸 죄가 '발견'으로 둔갑하는 것이다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "nocturnal", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/nɒkˈtɜːnl/", "mean": "야간의, 밤에 일어나는", "ctx": "In the late summer yet another of Snowball’s machinations was laid bare. The wheat crop was full of weeds, and it was discovered that on one of his ⟦nocturnal⟧ visits Snowball had mixed weed seeds with the seed corn.", "marked": true, "note": "밤에 이루어진다는 뜻이다. on one of his nocturnal visits(그의 야간 방문 중 한 번에)에서, Snowball은 결코 목격되지 않는 밤의 유령으로 그려진다. 검증 불가능한 '밤의 방문'이라는 설정이, 어떤 불행이든 그에게 떠넘길 수 있게 만드는 장치다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "privy to", "pos": "adj.", "pron": "/ˈprɪvi tu/", "mean": "(비밀을) 몰래 아는, 내막에 정통한", "ctx": "The wheat crop was full of weeds, and it was discovered that on one of his nocturnal visits Snowball had mixed weed seeds with the seed corn. A gander who had been ⟦privy to⟧ the plot had confessed his guilt to Squealer and immediately committed suicide by swallowing deadly nightshade berries.", "marked": true, "note": "비밀스러운 일의 내막을 안다는 뜻이다. A gander who had been privy to the plot had confessed his guilt(음모의 내막을 알던 거위 한 마리가 죄를 자백했다)에서, '자백'과 곧 이은 '자살'이 죄의 증거로 제시된다. 그러나 강요된 자백과 의문스러운 죽음은, 7장 대숙청의 자백 장면을 그대로 되풀이한다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "censure", "pos": "v.", "pron": "/ˈsenʃə/", "mean": "공식적으로 비난하다, 견책하다", "ctx": "This was merely a legend which had been spread some time after the Battle of the Cowshed by Snowball himself. So far from being decorated, he had been ⟦censured⟧ for showing cowardice in the battle.", "marked": true, "note": "공식적으로 질책한다는 뜻이다. he had been censured for showing cowardice in the battle(그는 전투에서 비겁함을 보여 견책받았다)에서, 한때 영웅이던 Snowball이 이제 겁쟁이로 다시 쓰인다. 'censure(견책)'와 'decorated(훈장)'의 정반대 단어가, 과거가 통째로 뒤집혀 다시 기록됨을 보여 준다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "so far from (being)", "pos": "phr.", "pron": "/səʊ fɑː frəm/", "mean": "~하기는커녕, ~과는 거리가 멀게", "ctx": "This was merely a legend which had been spread some time after the Battle of the Cowshed by Snowball himself. ⟦So far from⟧ being decorated, he had been censured for showing cowardice in the battle.", "marked": true, "note": "예상과 정반대임을 강조하는 표현이다. So far from being decorated, he had been censured(훈장을 받기는커녕 그는 견책받았다)에서, 동물들의 기억(훈장)과 새로운 공식 기록(견책)이 정면충돌한다. 'so far from'이 그 역전의 낙차를 극대화한다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "bewilderment", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/bɪˈwɪldəmənt/", "mean": "당혹, 어리둥절함", "ctx": "So far from being decorated, he had been censured for showing cowardice in the battle. Once again some of the animals heard this with a certain ⟦bewilderment⟧, but Squealer was soon able to convince them that their memories had been at fault.", "marked": true, "note": "혼란스럽고 어쩔 줄 모르는 상태를 뜻한다. some of the animals heard this with a certain bewilderment(일부 동물은 이를 약간의 당혹과 함께 들었다)에서, 동물들의 기억이 미약하게나마 저항한다. 그러나 그 당혹은 곧 Squealer에 의해 '너희 기억이 틀렸다'로 무마된다. 진실을 향한 마지막 직감조차 매번 설득당해 지워진다.", "sid": "c8s008"}, {"word": "inexperience", "pos": "n.", "pron": "/ˌɪnɪkˈspɪəriəns/", "mean": "미숙, 경험 부족", "ctx": "In the teeth of every difficulty, in spite of ⟦inexperience⟧, of primitive implements, of bad luck 